%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Introduction}
%******************************************************************************

The goal of this book is to explain with full details the source code of
a {kernel}.

\section{Motivations}

Why a kernel?
Because I think you are a better programmer if
you fully understand how things work under the hood, and the
kernel is the program that everything else rely on.

%claude:
Indeed, every program you write---from a simple [[hello]]
to a web server---relies on the kernel for its most
basic operations: 
reading files,
allocating memory,
communicating with other programs,
and even printing text on the screen.
Understanding what happens below
those system calls removes an entire layer of mystery
and gives you a far more accurate mental model of how
software actually executes on hardware.

%claude:
Moreover, the kernel is a fascinating program in its own
right. It must manage {concurrency} (multiple processes
sharing the CPU), {virtual memory} (giving each process
the illusion of having all memory for itself), and
{devices} (keyboards, disks, screens)---all while
remaining small enough to be trustworthy and fast enough
to stay out of the way. The tension between generality
and efficiency produces elegant solutions that are worth
studying even if you never write kernel code yourself.
%
Finally, many concepts introduced by the kernel---locks,
scheduling, caches, interrupt handling---reappear in
user-space programs such as databases, web servers, and
even build systems. Understanding the kernel is thus
also a way to understand those programs better.

Here are a few questions I hope this book will answer:
\begin{itemize}

\item What happens when the user turn on the computer?
Which code gets executed? How does the kernel initialise itself?

\item What happens when the user types [[ls]] in a terminal?
What are the set of programs involved in such a command? What
is the trace of such a command through the different layers
of the software stack, from the keyboard interrupt to
the display of text glyphs on the screen?
\l actually different if do ls and ls RET

\item Where does the kernel store meta data about the user processes?

\item Why do the kernel code and some kernel data structures reside
in the virtual memory space of every processes?

\item What is the trace of a system call?

\item What is the memory image of the kernel and the user
processes?

\end{itemize}
