\section{The \plan kernel: [[9]]}

%yoann: I chose plan9 kernel. A good basis for the other books.
% Made by Unix master Ken Thompson! Unix 2.0 (see Principia.nw)
%claude:
Like for most books in \principia, I chose a \plan program.
The \plan kernel, called [[9]], was written by Ken Thompson---the
creator of \unix---together with Dave Presotto and others at
Bell Labs. 
%unix:
If \unix was ``version~1,'' then \plan is
``version~2'': a chance to redesign an operating system with
decades of hindsight. The result is a kernel that is remarkably
small, clean, and coherent---a good basis for the other
\principia books.

%yoann: I will focus on code of 9 for Raspberry Pi, ARM archi. Simpler archi.
% Will have (ARM) in section when ARM specific. But most of the code
% in this book is portable code. The same code is used for x86 and arm.
%claude:
I will focus on the code of [[9]] for the Raspberry Pi, which
uses the ARM architecture. ARM is a RISC design, far simpler
than x86, making it a better target for a teaching book.
Sections covering ARM-specific code are marked with ``(ARM)''
in their title, but most of the code in this book is
{portable} C---the same source is shared between the ARM
and x86 ports of [[9]].

%yoann: Graphics and network in other books.
%claude:
The graphics stack and the networking stack are covered in
separate \principia volumes (\book{Graphics} and \book{Network}),
so this book focuses on the kernel's core: processes, memory,
files, and devices.

