\section{[[9]]'s syscall interface}

%trans: Saw general principles. Will now focus on plan9 kernel. 

%yoann: Plan9 is successor of Unix so share philosphy.
% Philosphy unix is everything is a file.
% Philosphy plan9 is everything is a file server.
%claude:
\plan is the successor to \unix and inherits its philosophy
that ``everything is a file.'' \plan pushes this further:
``everything is a {file server}''. Devices, the console, the
screen, the process table---all are accessed through
[[open]]/[[read]]/[[write]]/[[close]], served by in-kernel
or user-space file servers. This design lets the syscall
interface remain remarkably small.

% see 9.ps, excellent introduction to Plan9 advanced features
% see also docs/doc/ and docs/man/

%claude:
The entire interface fits in a small single header, [[sys.h]],
which lives in [[lib_core/libc/9syscall/]]---it is shared
between the kernel and the C library (see \book{Libcore}) because it defines
the interface between them. The same directory also
contains the auto-generated assembly wrappers (one per
syscall) that user programs link against. Each syscall is
a small integer used as an index into a dispatch table
(the [<systab>] array shown later).



<<lib_core/libc/9syscall/sys.h>>=
#define NOP     0
<<[[sys.h]] process syscalls>>
<<[[sys.h]] memory syscalls>>
<<[[sys.h]] file syscalls>>
<<[[sys.h]] directory syscalls>>
<<[[sys.h]] namespace syscalls>>
<<[[sys.h]] time syscalls>>
<<[[sys.h]] ipc syscalls>>
<<[[sys.h]] concurrency syscalls>>
<<[[sys.h]] special file syscalls>>
<<[[sys.h]] security syscalls>>
#define ERRSTR      39
@ 
%ocaml: use full ADT instead of int
% (but then more complex interface to call kernel; 
%  need to know ocaml object format and marshall format)
% maybe could use ADT only internally but expose easier C interface.
%ocaml: replace ERRSTR by exceptions
%c: accessible also in assembly because assembler usually can use cpp too
% (could also use cpp in OCaml though)

%yoann: Only 39! linux: more than 200 now? How many in Linux 0.01?
%claude:
Only 39 syscalls! Modern Linux has more than 400.
The reason \plan can get away with so few is the
``everything is a file server'' philosophy: operations
that would require dedicated syscalls in other systems
(e.g., [[getpid]], [[ioctl]]) are instead handled by
reading or writing special files.

%yoann: small comment on NOP usefulness and ERRSTR use and interface
%claude:
The [[NOP]] syscall at position~0 does nothing useful in
production---here it just prints ``Hello World'' for
testing purposes.
%
The [[ERRSTR]] syscall at position~39
is \plan's error-reporting mechanism.
%claude: %unix:
Unlike \unix, which uses the opaque numeric error code [[errno]]
(where you need a man page to find out what [[ENOENT]]
means), \plan uses human-readable error strings that
programs retrieve via [[errstr()]]---one of the many
small cleanups \plan made over \unix.

% will see in helloraw.c how to use those codes to perform syscall to kernel.
% will see sys_nop() soon.

% use an enum instead in sys.h? but then the script that generates
%  the .s in libc/ will be a bit more complicated and the syscall numbers
% are accessed from assembly so need to use #define

%claude:
The process syscalls mirror the \unix model: [[RFORK]] creates
a new process (a generalization of \unix\ [[fork]]),
[[EXEC]] replaces the current program, [[EXITS]] terminates,
and [[AWAIT]] waits for a child (like \unix\ [[wait]]).

<<[[sys.h]] process syscalls>>=
#define RFORK       1
#define EXEC        2
#define EXITS       3
#define AWAIT       4
@

%yoann: maybe say again cleaning up Unix/Linux where no need fork() and clone() but instead more general mechanism RFORK (resource fork) where can fork or share many resources (memory, fds, env, etc.) so clone is just RFORK with memory not forked but shared
%claude: %unix:
\plan cleans up \unix here too. Instead of having
separate [[fork()]] and [[clone()]] syscalls (as Linux
does), \plan has a single [[RFORK]] (``resource fork'')
that takes flags specifying which resources to copy and
which to share: memory, file descriptors, environment,
namespace, etc. A traditional [[fork]] is [[RFORK]] with
everything copied; a thread (shared memory) is [[RFORK]]
with memory shared.

%yoann: EXITS is another cleaning, does not take error code but clearer string so no need man page to describe each time mapping from error code to actual meaning
%claude: %unix:
Similarly, [[EXITS]] takes an error {string} (or [[nil]]
for success), not a numeric exit code. The parent reads
this string via [[AWAIT]]. No need to memorize that
exit code~2 means ``file not found''---the string says
it directly.

% for EXITS it generates _exits assembly function, not exits
%  because exits is a C function in libc/port/atexit.c
%old: TODO ugly! change it. Put EXIT here?)

% alternative to fork? just exec? but then fork allows easily to have
% pipe or things that adjust the environment before executing other programs.
% unix philosphy!
% cells are using fork so it must be a good API :)

%yoann: what BRK mean? no malloc/free here? one syscall is enough?
%claude:
There is only one memory syscall: [[BRK]] (for ``break''),
which moves the boundary between the data segment and free
memory. The name comes from the traditional \unix term for
the end of the process's data area.
There is no [[malloc]] or [[free]] syscall---those are
implemented entirely in user space (in the C library, see \book{Libcore}) on
top of [[brk]]. The library requests large chunks of memory
from the kernel via [[brk]] and then subdivides them.

<<[[sys.h]] memory syscalls>>=
#define BRK     5
@ 
%old: this used to be BRK_, because I think of APE. Some applications
% call brk() but POSIX brk() has a different semantic than Plan9
% brk, and making brk() a syscall makes things difficult to change.
% but it's ugly to have this _, so instead I've modified ape
% and assume nobody calls directly brk()!

% alternative to brk? if were using full segmentation power a la Multics
% then could have better scheme, and for instance hardware checked array
% bound! if the array was in his own segment!
%todo: bad name btw, not sure what it means

%claude:
The file syscalls are the workhorses of the interface.
Because so many things in \plan are files, most of
the kernel's services are accessed through these five calls.
Note [[PREAD]] and [[PWRITE]] instead of the traditional
\unix\ [[read]]/[[write]]: the [['p']] stands for
``positional''---they take an explicit file offset, making
seek-then-read atomic.
%claude: %unix:
This is another cleanup: in \unix, [[read]] and [[seek]]
are separate syscalls, so a concurrent [[seek]]+[[read]]
from two threads can race. \plan avoids this by combining
them into a single [[pread]] call.

<<[[sys.h]] file syscalls>>=
#define OPEN        6
#define CLOSE       7
#define PREAD       8
#define PWRITE      9
#define SEEK        10
@
% pread/pwrite? what is the p for? page read? page write?
% it does have an extra arg for seek, so have atomic seek;read? 

% Note that read() might mention a big count but this might not be honored.
% The kernel might return less bytes. For example the shell will read
% /dev/cons and ask for 8192 bytes (a buffer), but the kernel will return
% only the bytes until the newline.

%yoann: small paragraph explaining those syscalls, why all the xSTAT variation? fd2path seems original too
%claude:
The directory syscalls include [[CREATE]], [[REMOVE]],
[[CHDIR]], and a family of [[STAT]] variants. The
proliferation of [[STAT]]/[[FSTAT]]/[[WSTAT]]/[[FWSTAT]]
comes from two axes: [[STAT]] vs.\ [[FSTAT]] (take a
path name vs.\ a file descriptor), and read vs.\ write
(``w'' for write, i.e., change metadata). [[FD2PATH]]
is a \plan addition that returns the file name associated
with an open file descriptor---useful because in \plan,
with per-process namespaces, a file descriptor is often
more reliable than a path.
%claude: %unix:
Note [[CREATE]] with the full spelling---in \unix, the
syscall was famously called [[creat]] without the final
`e'. When asked what he would change about \unix, Ken
Thompson once answered: ``I'd spell creat with an e.''
\plan finally fixed this.

<<[[sys.h]] directory syscalls>>=
#define CREATE      11
#define REMOVE      12
#define CHDIR       13
#define FD2PATH     14
#define STAT        15
#define FSTAT       16
#define WSTAT       17
#define FWSTAT      18
@
% why so many stat, ugly a bit. each time variant where take name
% or file descriptor (the f stands for fd). Could remove maybe.

%plan9 specific! vs general os principles, e.g. namespace so have
% nice /dev/cons, /dev/draw, which enable easier network and graphics
%claude:
The namespace syscalls below are specific to \plan. [[BIND]] and
[[MOUNT]] let each process customize its own view of the
file system by overlaying directories or attaching file
servers at arbitrary mount points. This is what makes
[[/dev/cons]], [[/dev/draw]], etc.\ work cleanly: each
process can have its own [[/dev]] populated by different
servers.

<<[[sys.h]] namespace syscalls>>=
#define BIND        19
#define MOUNT       20
#define UNMOUNT     21
@


