\section{[[helloraw.c]] and [[helloraw.s]]}
% always good to start with concrete example of interaction

% print -> pwrite.
% C convention vs syscall convention => R0 store PWRITE.

% show asm so really low level!
% PWRITE =

%claude:
To see the syscall interface concretely, it is always good to
start with the simplest possible program. Here is a ``Hello World''
that uses [[pwrite()]] directly, without going through libc [[print()]]:

<<helloraw.c>>=
#include <u.h>
#include <libc.h>

void main() {
  pwrite(1, "hello world\n", 12, 0LL);
  exits(nil);
}
@

%claude:
The [[pwrite()]] call writes 12 bytes to file descriptor [[1]]
(standard output) at offset~0.\footnote{The [[0LL]]
suffix makes the offset a 64-bit [[long long]], because
\plan's [[pwrite]] takes a 64-bit file offset, allowing
files larger than 4~GiB.}
Under the hood, [[pwrite()]] is
a thin assembly wrapper that places the syscall number ([[PWRITE]],
which is [[9]] from [[sys.h]]) in register [[R0]] and
executes a [[SWI]] (software interrupt) instruction to trap
into the kernel.
%
The assembly version makes this mechanism fully visible:

<<helloraw.s>>=
TEXT _main(SB), $20
        /* pwrite(1, &hello, 12, 0LL) */
        MOVW $1, R1
        MOVW R1, 4(R13)
        MOVW $hello(SB), R1
        MOVW R1, 8(R13)
        MOVW $12, R1
        MOVW R1, 12(R13)
        MOVW $0, R1
        MOVW R1, 16(R13)
        MOVW R1, 20(R13)
        MOVW $9 /*PWRITE*/, R0
        SWI $0

        /* exits(0) */
        MOVW $0, R1
        MOVW R1, 4(R13)
        MOVW $3 /*EXITS*/, R0
        SWI $0

GLOBL   hello(SB), $12
DATA    hello+0(SB)/8, $"hello wo"
DATA    hello+8(SB)/4, $"rld\n"
@
% Plan 9 assembler DATA directives can only initialize up to 8 bytes at a time,
% so a 12-byte string must be split across two DATA statements.

%claude:
To compile and run the C version:
\begin{verbatim}
$ 5c helloraw.c
$ 5l helloraw.5 -o helloraw
$ ./helloraw
hello world
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
For the assembly version:
\begin{verbatim}
$ 5a helloraw.s
$ 5l helloraw.5 -o helloraw
$ ./helloraw
hello world
\end{verbatim}

%claude:
You can also use [[ratrace]], the \plan equivalent of [[strace]],
to see the syscalls executed by the program:
\begin{verbatim}
$ ratrace -c ./helloraw
...
Pwrite 9, "hello world\n", 12
...
Exits  0
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
This confirms that our small program generates exactly the
two system calls we expected: [[PWRITE]] and [[EXITS]].
We will see in Chapters~\ref{chap:interrupts}
and~\ref{chap:processes} how the kernel handles the [[SWI]]
instruction, dispatches the syscall number through [[systab]],
and executes the corresponding kernel function.

\section{[[minishell.c]]}

% illustrate also a few syscalls?
% illustrate also relation with shell?

% reopen /dev/cons, pread, pwrite, fork, exec, await, exits, etc.
%claude:
A slightly more interesting example is a minimal shell that
illustrates several syscalls working together:

<<minishell.c>>=
#include <u.h>
#include <libc.h>

void main() {
  char buf[256];
  char *args[2];
  int n;

  for(;;) {
    pwrite(1, "$ ", 2, 0LL);
    n = pread(0, buf, sizeof(buf)-1, 0LL);
    if(n <= 0)
      break;
    buf[n-1] = '\0';  /* strip newline */
    args[0] = buf;
    args[1] = nil;
    if(rfork(RFPROC|RFFDG) == 0) {
      exec(buf, args);
      exits("exec failed");
    }
    await(buf, sizeof(buf));
  }
  exits(0);
}
@
%$

%claude:
This program reads commands from standard input (file descriptor [[0]]),
forks a child
with [[rfork]], loads the requested program with [[exec]], and
waits for it to finish with [[await]]. Running it under
[[ratrace]] reveals the full sequence of syscalls for a single
command---a preview of the machinery this book will explain.

\section{The Raspberry Pi machine (ARM)}

% Raspberry Pi. Hobbyist machine. Cheap. Education for computer science.
% Perfect target!

% * Broadcom bcm2835 SoC, as used in Raspberry Pi
% * arm1176jzf-s processor (armv6)

% In this book I will focus mostly on code for Pi 1 Model B. ARMv6 32 bits.
% See Appendix~\ref{} for code for Raspberry Pi 2 and SMP.
% In rest when I say Raspberry Pi and ARM is mostly Raspberry Pi 1 Model B
% and ARMv6!.
%claude:
The target hardware for this book is the Raspberry Pi Model~B,
a cheap hobbyist board designed for education. It is built around
a Broadcom BCM2835 System-on-Chip (SoC) with an ARM1176JZF-S
processor implementing the ARMv6 instruction set (32~bits).
In the rest of this book, ``Raspberry Pi'' and ``ARM'' refer
specifically to this board and this processor unless noted otherwise.

%x86: PC vs Raspberry Pi?

%https://www.raspberrypi.org/documentation/hardware/raspberrypi/
%https://www.raspberrypi.org/documentation/hardware/raspberrypi/bcm2835/README.md
%http://embedded-xinu.readthedocs.io/en/latest/arm/rpi/index.html

\subsection{ARM CPU}

% ARM processor (far simpler than x86, great for our teaching purpose).
% arm1176jzf-s processor
% armv6 instruction set.

% Most popular archi in smartphones. Most popular archi in number of devices.
% More than x86!
%claude:
The ARM is a RISC processor, far simpler than the x86 CISC
architecture. This makes it a better target for a teaching book.
ARM is also the most popular architecture by number of
devices shipped---it powers most smartphones---so understanding
it is useful beyond this book.

%references:
% - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ARM_architecture
% - http://infocenter.arm.com/help/index.jsp?topic=/com.arm.doc.ddi0301h/index.html
% - https://www.heyrick.co.uk/armwiki/Main_Page 
%  (RiscOS oriented, but still a few good pages)
% - https://courses.cs.washington.edu/courses/cse466/10au/pdfs/lectures/07-arm_overview.pdf 
%  (slides, small, very good)
% - http://embedded-xinu.readthedocs.io/en/latest/arm/index.html

ARM is a 32 bits architecture, hence the constant definition below ``bytes per word''.
%claude:
A {word} is the natural unit of data for a processor---the
size of a general-purpose register and typically the width
of the data bus. The term dates back to early computing
where a ``word'' was the fundamental chunk of data a
machine could process in one operation. On a 32-bit ARM,
a word is 4~bytes.

<<constant [[BY2WD]](arm)>>=
#define BY2WD       4
@

%yoann: what V stands for?
%claude:
[[BY2V]] stands for ``bytes per vlong.'' A [[vlong]]
(``very long'') is \plan's name for a 64-bit integer.
In \plan, [[long]] is always 32~bits regardless of the
architecture (unlike [[gcc]] where [[long]] is 64~bits
on 64-bit systems). So [[vlong]] (equivalent to C99's
[[long long]]) is 8~bytes.

<<constant [[BY2V]](arm)>>=
#define BY2V        8           /* only used in xalloc.c */
@
%dead:
% <<constant BY2SE(arm)>> =
% #define BY2SE       4
% @
%dead:
% <<constant BI2BY(arm)>> =
% #define BI2BY       8           /* bits per byte */
% @
% seems unused on arm archi, and very rarely used on x86. Stupid constant.
% A byte is always 8 bits.

% ARM state, Thumb state, Jazelle state, but care only about
% ARM state where instructions are 32 bits wide and word aligned.

\subsubsection{Main registers, [[Ureg]]}

%claude:
The ARM has 16 general-purpose 32-bit registers ([[R0]]--[[R15]]),
of which [[R13]] is the stack pointer ([[SP]]), [[R14]] the
link register (return address), and [[R15]] the program counter
([[PC]]). The [[Ureg]] structure below captures the full
register state of a user process. The kernel saves a [[Ureg]]
on the stack every time it takes control from a user process
(on a syscall, interrupt, or exception), and restores it when
returning.
<<struct [[Ureg]](arm)>>=
//coupling: do not change the order! some assembly code assumes this order.
struct Ureg {
    ulong   r0;
    ulong   r1;
    ulong   r2;
    ulong   r3;
    ulong   r4;
    ulong   r5;
    ulong   r6;
    ulong   r7;
    ulong   r8;
    ulong   r9;
    ulong   r10;
    ulong   r11;
    ulong   r12;    /* sb */

    union {
        ulong   r13;
        ulong   sp;
    };
    union {
        ulong   r14;
        ulong   link;
    };

    ulong   type;   /* of exception */
    ulong   psr;

    ulong   pc; /* interrupted addr */ // r15
};
@
%c: can do union! (but maybe confusing)
%x86: less regular naming
%coupling: see  _vswitch and _userexcep

% Ureg for user registers. 
% Ureg will be used when saving state of processes.
% Save pc/sp but also value of current registers
% (and also of float registers, see Appendix).
% Save PSR because contains the flag bits NZCV (dont care so much
% about control bits because it should be PsrUsr always)
\l Ureg.type not really a register no?

%qemu: use C-Alt-2 and then 'info registers' 'info cpus' etc :)
