\subsubsection{Program Status Register ([[PSR]])}

% Special register not accessed in normal programs. No need.
% But important for kernel! State of process regarding ALU flags.
% Ureg.psr! important. Need to restore it too!
%claude:
In addition to the general-purpose registers, the ARM has a
{Program Status Register} (PSR) that contains both the
arithmetic flags (negative, zero, carry, overflow) and
control bits (processor mode, interrupt disable). Normal
user programs never access the PSR directly, but the kernel
must save and restore it---this is the [[Ureg.psr]] field---because
the flags are part of the process state. The control bits
are critical too: they determine whether the processor is in
user or supervisor mode, and whether interrupts are enabled.

% http://infocenter.arm.com/help/topic/com.arm.doc.ddi0301h/I2837.html
% https://www.heyrick.co.uk/armwiki/The_Status_register

%example of use:
% CPSR

%dead: non-control bits
% <<type PsrArith(arm)>> =
% #define PsrV        0x10000000      /* overflow */
% #define PsrC        0x20000000      /* carry/borrow/extend */
% #define PsrZ        0x40000000      /* zero */
% #define PsrN        0x80000000      /* negative/less than */
% @

% Depending on the value of those flags, following instruction
% like B.EQ will do different things, so really need to store/restore
% those flags.

%yoann: ASCII diagram with PSR and all the bits and meaning, and maybe also all registers together
%claude:
The ARM actually has two copies of the PSR. The {CPSR}
(Current Program Status Register) reflects the current state.
The {SPSR} (Saved Program Status Register) is a shadow copy
that the processor fills automatically when entering an
exception: it saves the old CPSR so the handler can restore
it when returning. Both have the same layout:

\begin{verbatim}
  31  30  29  28  27       8   7   6   5   4    0
 +---+---+---+---+-- ... --+---+---+---+---+-----+
 | N | Z | C | V |         | I | F |   | T | Mode|
 +---+---+---+---+-- ... --+---+---+---+---+-----+
   |   |   |   |             |   |       |   |
   |   |   |   |             |   |       |   +-- PsrMusr (0x10) = user
   |   |   |   |             |   |       |       PsrMsvc (0x13) = supervisor
   |   |   |   |             |   |       |       PsrMirq (0x12) = IRQ
   |   |   |   |             |   |       |       PsrMabt (0x17) = abort
   |   |   |   |             |   |       |       etc.
   |   |   |   |             |   |       |
   |   |   |   |             |   |       +-- Thumb mode (0=ARM, 1=Thumb)
   |   |   |   |             |   |
   |   |   |   |             |   +-- PsrDfiq (0x40): disable FIQ
   |   |   |   |             |
   |   |   |   |             +-- PsrDirq (0x80): disable IRQ
   |   |   |   |
   |   |   |   +-- V: overflow
   |   |   +-- C: carry
   |   +-- Z: zero
   +-- N: negative
\end{verbatim}


%claude:
%And here is the ARM register set, showing which registers are
%{banked} (i.e., the processor has a separate physical copy for
%each mode):
%\begin{verbatim}
%           User/   SVC     IRQ     ABT     FIQ     UND
%           System
%  R0       R0      R0      R0      R0      R0      R0
