%  ...      ...     ...     ...     ...     ...     ...
%  R7       R7      R7      R7      R7      R7      R7
%  R8       R8      R8      R8      R8      R8_fiq  R8
%  ...      ...     ...     ...     ...     ...     ...
%  R12      R12     R12     R12     R12     R12_fiq R12
%  R13 (SP) R13     R13_svc R13_irq R13_abt R13_fiq R13_und
%  R14 (LR) R14     R14_svc R14_irq R14_abt R14_fiq R14_und
%  R15 (PC) R15     R15     R15     R15     R15     R15
%  CPSR     CPSR    CPSR    CPSR    CPSR    CPSR    CPSR
%           --      SPSR_svc SPSR_irq SPSR_abt SPSR_fiq SPSR_und
%\end{verbatim}
%%claude:
%The banked R13 (SP) and R14 (LR) are why the kernel does
%not need to save those registers explicitly when entering
%an exception handler: the processor automatically switches
%to the banked copies. The [[_vsvc]] handler has its own
%[[R13_svc]] (the kernel stack pointer) ready to use, and [[R14_svc]]
%holds the return address. The user's R13 and R14 are saved
%later via the [[MOVM.S]] instruction which accesses the
%user-mode registers.

\subsubsection{Processor modes}

%PSR contains also "control bits". Last 8 bits in PSR register. Can not be
% changed by user. Can be changed only when in privileged mode.
% (the control bits changes also when an exception occurs).

% 4 bits so potentially 16 domains, but really use 2,
% user vs supervisor(privileged/protected).
%claude:
The low bits of the PSR encode the {processor mode}. The ARM
supports several modes, but the kernel cares mainly about two:
user mode ([[PsrMusr]]), where normal programs run with
restricted privileges, and supervisor mode ([[PsrMsvc]]),
where the kernel runs with full access to hardware. When
an exception (e.g., a [[SWI]]) occurs, the processor
automatically switches to supervisor mode; the kernel must
switch back to user mode before returning to the user program.
The mode field is 5~bits wide (bits 4--0),
but Bit~4 is always set in the defined modes (it
distinguishes ``32-bit modes'' from legacy 26-bit modes).
Bits 3--0 select the specific mode. 

Bit~5 (the T~bit) selects Thumb vs.\ ARM instruction mode.
%claude:
Thumb is a compact 16-bit instruction encoding that ARM
processors can use to reduce code size. The \plan kernel
does not use Thumb mode---all kernel and user code runs
in ARM mode (32-bit instructions)---so we can ignore the
T~bit in this book.



<<type [[PsrMode]](arm)>>=
// Last 5 bits of PSR
#define PsrMusr     0x00000010  /* user mode */
#define PsrMsvc     0x00000013  /* `protected mode for OS' */
<<[[PsrMode]] other cases(arm)>>

#define PsrMask     0x0000001F
@
%dead: #define PsrMmon     0x00000016  /* `secure monitor' (trustzone hyper) */
%dead: #define PsrMsys     0x0000001F  /* `privileged user mode for OS' (trustzone) */
% what is the 1 in bit5? 

%example of use: (but can change those bits only when already in svc mode)
% 

% When reset, supervisor mode.
% When create first user process, will set PSR to MsrMusr before RFE.


% PSR controls also interrupts.
%claude:
The PSR also controls whether interrupts are enabled.
Setting [[PsrDirq]] disables IRQ interrupts. The kernel
uses this to protect {critical sections} where it must
not be preempted---for instance, while manipulating the
scheduler's run queue.
<<type [[PsrDisable]](arm)>>=
#define PsrDirq     0x00000080      /* disable IRQ interrupts */
<<[[PsrDisable]] other cases(arm)>>
@
