\subsubsection{Exceptions}

%yoann: maybe define Exception vs Interrupt vs IRQ terms
%claude:
A note on terminology: the ARM uses the word {exception}
as the general term for any event that diverts the processor
from normal execution. This includes {interrupts} (external
hardware signals, called {IRQ} for Interrupt Request),
{software interrupts} (the [[SWI]] instruction used for
syscalls), and {aborts} (page faults, undefined instructions).
Each exception type has its own entry in the vector table
and its own processor mode.

%Ureg.type
%matches closely processor modes actually
% (which is why will abuse PsrMode for that)

% When exception, processor copies CPSR to SPSR,
% set appropriate CPSR control bits depending on exception
% set PC to vector address.
%claude:
When an exception occurs, the ARM processor automatically
saves the current CPSR into the SPSR, switches to
the appropriate privileged mode, and jumps to a fixed address
in the {exception vector table}. This table is normally at
physical address~0, but the kernel configures the ARM (via the
[[CpChv]] bit in the system control register) to use
``high vectors'' at [[0xFFFF0000]]. This is more convenient
both because it lives in the kernel's virtual address space,
and because it frees physical address~0 for the null pointer
trap (the first page of user virtual memory is left unmapped).

%yoann: HVECTORS is virtual address. Must mapped to physical 0. Need CpChv (later).
%claude:
Of course, [[0xFFFF0000]] is a virtual address, so once
the MMU is enabled the hardware itself relies on the MMU
to translate it to the physical memory containing the vector
code. This is not a chicken-and-egg problem: the kernel sets
up the page tables and copies the vector code to physical
page~0 first (while still using physical addresses or
identity-mapped memory during early boot), then enables the
MMU and [[CpChv]] together. From that point on, any
exception causes the ARM to fetch the handler from virtual
[[0xFFFF0000]], which the MMU translates to physical~0.

<<constant [[HVECTORS]](arm)>>=
#define HVECTORS    0xffff0000
@
% will contain notably callback for SWI!

\subsection{ARM coprocessors}

% PSR nice, but limited. For extra functionalities, enter coprocessors
% and their registers.
% Regular programs dont use those instructions (generate fault?).
% Only useful for kernel.
%claude:
Beyond the main registers and the PSR, the ARM provides access
to {coprocessors} that control hardware features such as the
MMU, caches, and performance counters. Coprocessor registers
are accessed via special instructions ([[MRC]] to read,
[[MCR]] to write) and are only available in privileged mode.
Normal user programs never touch them---they are the kernel's
private interface to the hardware.

% http://infocenter.arm.com/help/topic/com.arm.doc.ddi0211k/Bihggafj.html

% example of use:
%  MRC ...
%  MCR ...
%  and also MCRR MRCC

