\subsubsection{Floating point coprocessors}
% 2 coprocessors, one for single and other for double precision.

% See Advanced Topics.

%yoann: introduce complex world of floating point, and maybe say will talk more about it later
%claude:
The ARM has two coprocessors dedicated to floating-point
arithmetic: one for single precision and one for double
precision. Floating point adds considerable complexity to a
kernel because the floating-point registers must be saved
and restored on context switches, and some ARM chips lack
hardware floating-point entirely (requiring software
emulation). These issues are discussed in the Advanced Topics
chapter.

\subsection{ARM MMU}

% Physical memory and virtual memory.
% CpTTB, CpTLB,
% CpFAR, CpFSR ...

% More about virtual memory in chapter X.

% More about memory layout in Overview section.
%claude:
The ARM includes a {Memory Management Unit} (MMU) that
translates virtual addresses to physical addresses using
{page tables}. The page table base address is stored in the
[[CpTTB]] coprocessor register---this is a {physical} address,
since the MMU itself needs to walk the page table before any
virtual-to-physical translation is available. When a
translation fails, the MMU generates a fault and records the
faulting address in [[CpFAR]] and the reason in [[CpFSR]].
The kernel uses the MMU to give each process its own virtual
address space and to protect kernel memory from user access.
More details are in Chapter~\ref{chap:virtual-memory}.

%claude:
The ARM MMU supports two {granularities} of mapping.
An L1 (first-level) table entry can either map a full
1~MiB {section} directly to a physical address, or point
to an L2 (second-level) table that maps individual
4~KiB {pages}:
\begin{verbatim}
  L1 entry types:
    Section  --> maps 1 MiB directly (no L2 table needed)
    Coarse   --> points to an L2 table (256 entries x 4 KiB = 1 MiB)
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
Sections are efficient for large contiguous mappings (the
kernel maps all of RAM this way), while pages are needed
for fine-grained control (individual user pages, the
exception vector page at [[HVECTORS]]).

%claude:
The basic unit of memory managed at the finest level is
a {page}, which on ARM (and on x86) is 4~KiB:

%yoann: maybe ASCII diagram already useful here?
%claude:
When using pages (L1 entry of type Coarse), the MMU
translates virtual addresses using a two-level walk.
The virtual address is split into three fields:
\begin{verbatim}
  31        20 19       12 11          0
 +------------+-----------+------------+
 | L1 index   | L2 index  | page offset|
 | (12 bits)  | (8 bits)  | (12 bits)  |
 +-----+------+-----+-----+-----+------+
       |            |           |
       v            v           v
  +--------+   +--------+   +------+
  | L1     |-->| L2     |-->| byte |
  | table  |   | table  |   | in   |
  | (4096  |   | (256   |   | page |
  | entries)|  | entries)|  |      |
  +--------+   +--------+   +------+
     ^
     |
   CpTTB register (physical address of L1 table)
\end{verbatim}

%claude:
When using sections (L1 entry of type Section), the L2 step
is skipped entirely: the L1 entry contains the physical base
address of a 1~MiB region directly, and bits 19--0 of the
virtual address become the offset within that region.

%yoann: maybe ASCII diagram showing the L1 Table and the format of each entry, how bits are used; also show which bits control whether the entry is a section or coarse
%claude:
The lowest 2 bits of each L1 entry determine its type:
\begin{verbatim}
  L1 entry (32 bits):

  Fault (bits[1:0] = 00):  unmapped, any access causes a fault
  +-----------------------------------------------------------+
  |                     ignored                         | 0 0 |
  +-----------------------------------------------------------+

  Coarse (bits[1:0] = 01):  points to an L2 table
  +-----------------------------------------------------------+
  | L2 table base address (phys, 1 KiB aligned) | dom | 0 | 1 |
  +-----------------------------------------------------------+
   31                                         10  8-5   2   0

  Section (bits[1:0] = 10):  maps 1 MiB directly
  +-----------------------------------------------------------+
  | phys base (1 MiB aligned) | flags | AP  | dom | C B | 1 0 |
  +-----------------------------------------------------------+
   31                      20  19-12  11-10  8-5   3  2   1  0
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
The [[Section]] type is used for the kernel's RAM mapping
(512 entries covering 512~MiB) and the I/O register mapping.
The [[Coarse]] type is used for the exception vectors at
[[HVECTORS]] and for user-process pages, where fine-grained
4~KiB mapping is needed.

%yoann: maybe explain a few bits, dom, flags, AP, C B that are useful to understand
%claude:
A few of the bit fields in these entries are worth knowing
about now. [[AP]] (Access Permission, bits~11--10) controls
whether the page is readable/writable by user code or only
by the kernel---this is how user/kernel memory protection is
enforced. [[dom]] (domain, bits~8--5) selects one of 16
{domains}; the domain register then says whether accesses to
that domain are checked (``client''), unchecked (``manager''),
or faulted (``no access''), providing a coarse-grained
override. The [[C]] and [[B]] bits (bits~3 and~2) control
caching: [[C]]=1 enables the data cache, [[B]]=1 enables
write buffering. Kernel RAM is mapped with both set
(write-back cached); I/O registers are mapped with both
clear (uncached, so reads/writes go directly to hardware).

