\subsubsection{Memory-mapped IO}

% Yet another way to access external registers. Not coprocessors
% here but registers in external devices.
%x86: ins/out special instruction
%claude:
On ARM, devices are accessed through {memory-mapped I/O}:
each device exposes its control registers at fixed physical
addresses, and the kernel reads and writes them using
ordinary load/store instructions ([[MOVW]], which is really
[[LDR]]/[[STR]] under the hood). This is simpler than the
x86 approach, which uses special [[IN]]/[[OUT]] instructions
for I/O ports.
%claude:
The kernel maps the physical I/O region (starting at
[[0x20000000]] on the Raspberry Pi~1) to a virtual address
[[VIRTIO]], so that all device registers are accessed as
offsets from [[VIRTIO]]:

%example of use:
% no need MCR, MRC, can use simply MOVW (really LDR/STR under the hood)

