\subsubsection{Output device: VideoCore GPU}
%VideoCore IV.
%GPU with framebuffer.
%claude:
The Raspberry Pi's BCM2835 contains a VideoCore~IV GPU that
is actually more powerful than the ARM CPU itself. The GPU
manages the screen and provides a {framebuffer}: a region of
memory where each pixel is represented by a few bytes. The
kernel writes pixels to this framebuffer, and the GPU
continuously scans it to produce the video signal.
%claude:
Communication between the ARM CPU and the GPU goes through
a {mailbox} mechanism---a set of hardware registers at
a fixed address where the ARM can send requests and receive
responses:

<<constant [[MAILBOX]](arm)>>=
#define MAILBOX     (VIRTIO+0xB880)
@
%for GPU, add in constant name?

% example of use:
%  ???

%claude:
To set up the framebuffer, the kernel fills an [[Fbinfo]]
structure with the desired resolution and pixel depth, sends
its physical address to the GPU via the mailbox, and the GPU
responds by filling in the [[pitch]], [[base]], and
[[screensize]] fields. The [[base]] field is the physical
address of the framebuffer memory that the GPU has allocated.
Note how the field order in the C struct must exactly match
the hardware's expected memory layout:
<<struct [[Fbinfo]](arm)>>=
// Framebuffer
// The order matters! the fields match the memory-mapped external registers.
struct Fbinfo {
    u32int  xres;
    u32int  yres;
    u32int  xresvirtual;
    u32int  yresvirtual;
    u32int  pitch;          /* returned by gpu */
    u32int  bpp;
    u32int  xoffset;
    u32int  yoffset;
    u32int  base;           /* returned by gpu */
    u32int  screensize;     /* returned by gpu */
};
@
%c: easy to match directly the hardware (no need cstruct ocaml package)

%claude:
The kernel then maps this GPU-allocated physical memory to
the virtual address [[FRAMEBUFFER]] so it can write pixels
directly. See the \book{Graphics} for the full story of how
the windowing system uses this framebuffer.
<<constant [[FRAMEBUFFER]](arm)>>=
#define FRAMEBUFFER 0xC0000000      /* video framebuffer */
@
% Virtual address mapped to physical Fbinfo.base returned by GPU.
% Then used in Graphics.nw via gscreen->bdata
% Virtual address Must be after kernel, so safe to go to 0xC0000000
% Why not 0xF? to allow for giant framebuffer? giant screen?

