\section{C and assembly}

% compilation scheme of kernel assumes pass parameters in stack,
% return value in R0 (EAX for x86), and caller save registers it needs
% after call before calling (so Label structure is simple).
% hmm unless return a vlong in which case pass an extra pointer
% to the function for the callee to set the value
% also assumes structures are 4bytes aligned? see PG_ONSWAP
%claude:
The kernel is written almost entirely in C, compiled by
the \plan C compiler [[5c]] (see the \book{Compiler}).
A small amount of assembly is necessary for operations that
C cannot express: saving and restoring registers, switching
between processor modes, manipulating coprocessor registers,
and performing the initial boot sequence.
%claude:
The calling convention used by [[5c]] is straightforward:
parameters are passed on the stack, the return value goes
in [[R0]], and all registers are caller-saved. This simplifies
the kernel's context-switch code, because the [[Label]]
structure (shown later) only needs to store [[SP]] and
[[PC]]---the caller has already saved any registers it
cares about. Note that this [[Label]] (just [[SP]]+[[PC]])
is used for voluntary context switches between kernel
threads. When the kernel takes control from a user process
(via a syscall or interrupt), it saves {all} registers
into a [[Ureg]] on the kernel stack---because the user
did not follow any calling convention that the kernel
could rely on.

%yoann: ASCII diagram for calling conventions, and also C vs kernel
% calling convention
%claude:
Here is the stack layout when a C function [[foo(a, b, c)]]
calls [[bar(x, y)]]:
\begin{verbatim}
          +-------------+
          |  c (arg 3)  |  12(FP)  for foo
          +-------------+
          |  b (arg 2)  |   8(FP)
          +-------------+
          |  a (arg 1)  |   4(FP)
          +-------------+
          | return addr |   0(FP)  = saved R14
  SP ---> +-------------+
          |  y (arg 2)  |   8(SP)  for bar
          +-------------+
          |  x (arg 1)  |   4(SP)
          +-------------+
          | (R14 save)  |   0(SP)
          +-------------+
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
For syscalls, the convention is different: the syscall number
goes in [[R0]] (not on the stack), and the [[SWI]] instruction
traps into the kernel. The kernel then reads the user's stack
to find the syscall arguments. This is why the [[Syscall]]
typedef takes a [[ulong*]]---it points to the arguments on
the user's stack.

