\section{Code organization}

%claude:
The kernel source is split across many files organized by
subsystem: [[core/]], [[concurrency/]], [[memory/]],
[[processes/]], [[files/]], [[filesystems/]], [[time/]],
[[interrupts/]], [[devices/]], [[init/]], [[console/]], etc.
These directories map directly to the chapters in this book.

Each subsystem has both portable code (in [[port/]]) and
architecture-specific code (in [[bcm/]] for ARM).

\subsection{Portable versus arch-specific code}

%pad:
% I added some arch_ and Arch_ prefix on arch-specific functions/structures
% called/used from port/.
% I added some arch__ for arch-specific functions not called from port
% but that have almost the same signatures in different arch. Not called
% from port because called from arch-specific code (e.g. interrupt code)
% but in the end provides same functionalities in different archs.
%claude:
To make the boundary visible in the code, arch-specific
functions called from portable code are prefixed with
[[arch_]] (e.g., [[arch_coherence()]]), and arch-specific
structures embedded in portable ones with [[Arch_]]
(e.g., [[Arch_Cpu]], [[Arch_Proc]]).

