\section{Software architecture}

% will need a big picture ...
%claude:
Unlike a compiler or an assembler, a kernel is not a pipeline
that transforms an input into an output. It is a {reactive}
program: while user programs run, the kernel is dormant.
It only wakes up when an event occurs---a syscall, an
interrupt, a timer tick---handles it, and then lets
the user program resume.

%yoann: monolithic kernel, but thx to 9P lots of user-space file-servers so ideas from microkernel too; In fact the all kernel is pretty small at 30K LOC.
%claude:
The \plan kernel is {monolithic}---device drivers,
the file system switch, memory management, and scheduling
all run in kernel space. But thanks to the 9P protocol,
much functionality that would live in the kernel on
other systems is pushed out to user-space file servers
(e.g., the window system [[rio]], the authentication
agent [[factotum]], the file server [[fossil]]). This
borrows a key idea from {microkernel} designs: keep the
kernel small and move services to user space. In fact,
the entire kernel is only about 30\,000 lines of
C---remarkably small for a complete operating system.

%claude:
The kernel's execution can be understood along three axes.
First, the {boot sequence}: how the kernel starts from a bare
machine and ends up with a running user shell.
Second, the {memory layout}: how physical memory is divided
between the kernel, user processes, devices, and the
framebuffer.
Third, the {steady-state} operation: how syscalls flow from
user space into the kernel and back, how interrupts propagate
from hardware to sleeping processes, and how the scheduler
picks which process runs next.
The following subsections give an overview of the first two;
the normal operation (once the system is up and running)
is the subject of the rest of the book.

\subsection{Booting overview (ARM)}

% broadcom System on Chip boot sequence is a bit secret and closed source.
% How things really work with this start_elf.cd file?
% But does not matter; in the end all archi have this idea
% of bootstrap code from disk to a special memory address.
%update: there is an open source firmware for Raspberry Pi
% https://github.com/raspberrypi/firmware
% https://github.com/christinaa/rpi-open-firmware
%  https://github.com/puppeh/vc4-toolchain toolchain for open firmwaire
%claude:
On the Raspberry Pi, the Broadcom firmware (closed source,
stored in ROM) loads a bootloader from the SD card, which
in turn loads the kernel binary at physical address
[[0x8000]]. The bootloader reads a configuration file
([[config.txt]]) from the SD card's boot partition, which
specifies the path to the kernel binary.
The details of this early firmware stage are
specific to the Broadcom SoC and not very interesting; what
matters is that all architectures share the same idea of
bootstrap code loading the kernel into memory at a known
address.

