\subsection{Memory overview (ARM)}

% many dimensions:
% - physical vs virtual
% - kernel vs user memory
%   and even per-process kernel stack kstack, user stack, main kernel stack
% - dynamic vs static (the static allocator so can bootstrap things)
%claude:
Understanding the kernel's memory layout requires thinking
along several dimensions: {physical} vs.\ {virtual} addresses,
{kernel} vs.\ {user} memory, and {static} vs.\ {dynamic}
allocation. On the Raspberry Pi, the physical memory starts
at address~0.\footnote{On some architectures, physical
memory does not start at~0---for example, on many x86
systems the first megabyte is reserved for legacy BIOS
structures. But on the Raspberry Pi's ARM SoC, physical
RAM genuinely begins at address~0.}
The kernel binary is loaded at physical
[[0x8000]] (virtual [[KTZERO]]).\footnote{Why [[0x8000]]
and not~0? Address~0 is reserved for the ARM exception
vector table. But the vectors only occupy a few dozen
bytes, so why not [[0x1000]]? The [[0x8000]] address is
a Broadcom firmware convention---the firmware uses the
memory below [[0x8000]] for its own data structures
during boot. The kernel in turn uses some of this space
(e.g., [[CPUADDR]] at [[0x2000]]) for early kernel
structures like the first [[Cpu]].}
Everything below [[KZERO]]
([[0x80000000]]) in the virtual address space belongs to
user processes; everything at or above [[KZERO]] belongs to
the kernel. The kernel's virtual addresses are simply the
physical addresses plus [[KZERO]].


% in <arch>/mem.h
%claude:
The following constants define the virtual address space
layout. [[KZERO]] at [[0x80000000]] (2~GiB) is the boundary:
below is user space, above is kernel space.
