%claude:
The following diagram shows the full virtual address space.
The kernel and user portions coexist in every process's
page table (though the kernel portion is shared and
identical across all processes):
\begin{verbatim}
                      ...
             +---------------------+
             | exception vectors   |
 0xFFFF0000  +---------------------+  <-- HVECTORS
                      ...
             +---------------------+
             | GPU framebuffer     |
 0xC0000000  +---------------------+  <-- FRAMEBUFFER
                      ...
             +---------------------+
             | kernel heap         |  xalloc pool (large allocs:
             |  (grows up)         |   Proc[], Page[], etc.)
             |                     |  then malloc pool
             +---------------------+
             | kernel bss          |
             +---------------------+
             | kernel data         |  globals: conf, systab, devtab,
             |                     |  xlists, palloc, procalloc...
             +---------------------+
             | kernel text         |  main(), sched(), syscall
             |                     |  handlers, device drivers...
 0x80008000  +---------------------+  <-- KTZERO
                      ...
             +---------------------+
             | Cpu0 struct         |  CPU 0's state
             | + kernel boot stack |  (1 page = CPUSIZE)
 0x80002000  +---------------------+  <-- CPUADDR
                      ...
 0x80000000  +=====================+  <-- KZERO
             |  KERNEL / USER      |
             |    BOUNDARY         |
             +=====================+
                      ...
             +---------------------+
             | memory-mapped I/O   |  device registers
             | (16 MiB = IOSIZE)   |  (SYSTIMERS, INTREGS, ...)
 0x7E000000  +---------------------+  <-- VIRTIO
                      ...
                 (unmapped gap)
                      ...
 0x20000000  +---------------------+  <-- USTKTOP
             | user stack          |  grows down
             |  (8 MiB max)        |  (USTKSIZE)
             +---------------------+
                      ...
             +---------------------+
             | user heap           |  managed by brk()
             |  (grows up)         |
             +---------------------+
             | user bss            |
             +---------------------+
             | user data           |
             +---------------------+
             | user text           |
 0x00001000  +---------------------+  <-- UTZERO
             | (unmapped page)     |  null pointer trap
 0x00000000  +---------------------+  <-- UZERO
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
A few things to notice. First, the kernel follows the standard
binary layout---text, then data, then bss---just like a user
program. The kernel heap (managed by [[xalloc]] and [[malloc]])
grows upward from the end of bss. Second, the first page at
address zero is intentionally left unmapped so that null
pointer dereferences cause an immediate fault. Third, the
I/O registers ([[VIRTIO]]) sit in the gap between the user
stack top and [[KZERO]]---they are mapped here for
convenience, even though they are only accessed by the kernel.
Fourth, the kernel's data section contains important global
variables such as [<systab>] (the syscall dispatch table),
[<devtab>] (the device driver table), [<conf>] (hardware
configuration), [<palloc>] (the page allocator state), and
[<procalloc>] (the process table). Finally, the [<Cpu>]
structure for CPU~0 occupies a single page at [<CPUADDR>],
below the kernel text, in the small gap between [<KZERO>]
and [<KTZERO>]. 

%claude:
On multi-processor systems (e.g.,
Raspberry Pi~2), each additional CPU has its own [[Cpu]]
struct allocated elsewhere; the [<cpus>] array and the
dedicated register [[R10]] allow each processor to find
its own.

%claude:
The physical memory layout is simpler. The Raspberry Pi~1
has 512~MiB of RAM from physical [[0x00000000]] to
[[0x20000000]]. The I/O registers start immediately after,
at [[0x20000000]] ([[Soc.physio]]). The GPU allocates the
framebuffer somewhere within the RAM.
%claude:
Here is the physical address space:
\begin{verbatim}
             +------------------+
             | I/O registers    |  SYSTIMERS, INTREGS,
             |  (16 MiB)        |  MAILBOX, USBREGS, ...
 0x20000000  +------------------+  PHYSIO
             |                  |
             |  free RAM        |  user pages,
             |  (user pages,    |  GPU framebuffer
             |   GPU framebuf)  |
             |                  |
             +------------------+
             |  kernel:         |
             |    bss + heap    |  xalloc, malloc pools
             +------------------+
             |    data          |  conf, systab, devtab,
             |                  |  palloc, procalloc, ...
             +------------------+
             |    text          |  main(), sched(), ...
 0x00008000  +------------------+
             | L1 page table    |  16 KiB, 4096 entries
             |  (CpTTB points   |  (Section or Coarse)
             |   here)          |
 0x00004000  +------------------+
             | L2 page table    |  for HVECTORS mapping
 0x00003000  +------------------+
             | Cpu0 struct +    |  CPU 0's state
             |  boot stack      |
 0x00002000  +------------------+
             |                  |
             | vector table     |  exception entry points
 0x00000000  +------------------+
\end{verbatim}

%claude:
The kernel's [<mmuinit()>] function (Chapter~\ref{chap:initialization})
fills the L1 page table at physical [[0x4000]] and then the
boot code stores this address in the [[CpTTB]] register and
enables the MMU and [[CpChv]] together. Here is what the
4096-entry L1 table looks like after [<mmuinit()>]:
\begin{verbatim}
  L1 page table (at phys 0x4000, pointed to by CpTTB)
  Each entry covers 1 MiB of virtual address space.

  index   virt range            entry type     maps to phys
  -----   ----------            ----------     ------------
  4095    0xFFF0_0000 HVECTORS   Coarse    -->  L2 at 0x3000
                                                (L2[0] = phys page 0)
  4094    ...                    Fault          (unmapped)
   ...     (unmapped)            ...
  3072    0xC000_0000 FRAMEBUF   Section   -->  GPU-chosen address
  3071    ...                    Fault          (unmapped)
   ...     (unmapped)            ...
  2559    0x9FF0_0000            Section   -->  0x1FF0_0000
   ...     (kernel RAM, contiguous)
  2049    0x8010_0000            Section   -->  0x0010_0000
  2048    0x8000_0000 KZERO      Section   -->  0x0000_0000
  ====     kernel / user boundary  ==================
  2031    0x7EF0_0000            Section   -->  0x20F0_0000
   ...     (I/O registers, 16 entries)
  2016    0x7E00_0000 VIRTIO     Section   -->  0x2000_0000 PHYSIO
  2015    ...                    Fault          (unmapped)
   ...     (unmapped gap)        ...
   512    0x2000_0000 USTKTOP    Fault          (unmapped)
   511    0x1FF0_0000            Fault initially, then
   ...     (user space)          Coarse when process mapped
     1    0x0010_0000            (filled on demand by
     0    0x0000_0000 UZERO      arch_putmmu / fixfault)
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
The user entries (indices 0--511) start as Fault after
[<mmuinit()>]. They are filled on demand by [<arch_putmmu()>]
when a process is created or when a page fault occurs: each
entry becomes a Coarse pointer to a per-process L2 table.
Within the first MiB (entry~0), the L2 table maps pages
starting at [[UTZERO]] ([[0x1000]]) but leaves page~0
permanently unmapped---this is the null pointer trap.
So it is not the entire first MiB that is inaccessible,
only the first 4~KiB page.


%claude:
The kernel mapping is a simple offset: virtual [[KZERO+x]]
maps to physical [[x]], using 512 consecutive L1 {Section}
entries (indices 2048--2559). The L1 table itself, the
[[Cpu]] structure, and the vector table are all within this
range, so they are accessible at both their physical
addresses and at [[KZERO]] plus that address.
%claude:
The three special mappings are the I/O registers (16 L1
sections mapping virtual [[VIRTIO]] to physical [[PHYSIO]]),
the exception vectors (one L1 Coarse entry at index~4095
pointing to an L2 table that maps a single 4~KiB page of
physical~0 to virtual [[HVECTORS]]---the ARM's [[CpChv]]
bit directs the processor to fetch vectors from
[[0xFFFF0000]]), and the GPU framebuffer (one L1 section
at index~3072). User mappings occupy indices 0--511 and
are filled per-process with Coarse entries pointing to
L2 tables, so that each process has its own pages.

