\subsection{Syscall overview (ARM)}
% kernel vs user code

% show assembly code of a syscall called from helloraw.c?
%claude:
We saw in the [[helloraw.s]] example how a user program
invokes a syscall: it places the syscall number in [[R0]]
and executes [[SWI $0]]. On the kernel side, the interrupt
handler extracts the number from [[R0]] and uses it as an
index into [[systab]], the syscall dispatch table. Each
entry in [[systab]] is a function pointer with a uniform
signature:

% On the kernel side, generic interface for syscalls:
<<typedef Syscall>>=
typedef long Syscall(ulong*); // user_wp? or copied in Sargs?
@
%ocaml: marshalled ADT instead of generic ulong*? 
% need also ADT for return value though and special matching return value.
%c: very generic interface and later cast (but good in the end?)

%yoann: explain more this ulong*, when use pwrite there is actually 4 arguments and now only one
%claude:
The [[ulong*]] parameter is a pointer into the user's stack,
where the syscall arguments have been laid out as a flat
array of machine words. For example, [[pwrite(fd, buf, n, off)]]
has four arguments, but on the kernel side they all arrive
as consecutive [[ulong]] values starting at this pointer:
[[arg[0]]] is the file descriptor, [[arg[1]]] the buffer
address, [[arg[2]]] the count, and [[arg[3]]] (possibly
two words for a 64-bit offset) the file position.
Each [[sys*()]] function casts and extracts what it needs
from this generic array.

