%yoann: ok maybe detail the trace of a sysnop syscall from C program to nop() with exception vector lookup, who sets this vector lookup, etc.
%claude:
To tie everything together, here is the complete trace of
a [[NOP]] syscall, from the user program down to [[sysnop()]]
and back:
\begin{verbatim}
  USER SPACE                          KERNEL SPACE

  1. nop()
     libc wrapper:
       MOVW $0, R0   (NOP=0)
       SWI $0
          |
          | ARM hardware:
          | - saves PC in R14_svc
          | - saves CPSR in SPSR_svc
          | - switches to SVC mode
          | - jumps to HVECTORS+0x08
          |   (SWI = vector #2)
          |
          +------------------------->  2. HVECTORS (0xFFFF0000):
                                          vectors[2]: LDR PC, vtable[2]
                                               |
                                               v
                                       3. vtable[2] = _vsvc
                                               |
                                               v
                                       4. _vsvc (assembly):
                                          - saves user regs -> Ureg
                                            (on kernel stack)
                                          - sets R12 = kernel SB
                                          - sets R(CPU), R(UP)
                                          - calls arch__syscall(ureg)
                                               |
                                               v
                                       5. arch__syscall (C):
                                          - scallnr = ureg->r0  (= 0)
                                          - sp = user stack pointer
                                            (the ulong* in Syscall)
                                          - ret = systab[0](sp)
                                               |
                                               v
                                       6. sysnop(ulong*):
                                          - print("Hello World\n")
                                          - return 0
                                               |
                                               v
                                       7. back in _vsvc:
                                          - restores user regs from Ureg
                                          - restores SPSR -> CPSR
                                          - RFE (return to user mode)
          |                                    |
          +<-----------------------------------+
          v
  8. user program continues
     after SWI instruction
\end{verbatim}


%claude:
Note the distinction between [[Ureg]] and [[Label]]: when
entering the kernel from user space (step~4), [[_vsvc]]
saves {all} user registers into a [[Ureg]] because the user
program did not follow any calling convention---its registers
could hold anything. Later, if the kernel decides to context
switch to another process (a voluntary switch between kernel
threads), it uses [[Label]], which saves only [[SP]] and
[[PC]]---because kernel code follows the caller-save
convention and the caller has already saved any registers
it needs.


%claude:
The exception vector table at [[HVECTORS]] is set up by
[<arch__trapinit()>] during initialization: it copies the
[[vectors]] code (a series of [[LDR PC]] instructions) and
the [[vtable]] data (an array of addresses like [[_vsvc]],
[[_virq]], etc.)\ to the page at [[0xFFFF0000]].
The [[CpChv]] bit (set during boot) tells the ARM to
fetch vectors from there instead of from address~0.
The ``v'' in [[_vsvc]] stands for ``vector'' and ``svc''
for the supervisor call (SWI) exception. Similarly,
[[_virq]] handles IRQ interrupts, [[_vdabt]] handles
data aborts, etc.

%yoann: explain R(CPU) R(UP), explain a bit R12/SB (refer to linker book maybe)
%claude:
A few things about the registers used in step~4. [[R(CPU)]]
is [[R10]], which by convention always holds a pointer to the
current processor's [<Cpu>] structure---this is the
[[extern register Cpu* cpu]] declaration we will see soon.
[[R(UP)]] is [[R9]], which holds a pointer to the current
process's [<Proc>] structure ([<up>] for ``user process'').
[[R12]] is the {static base} register ([[SB]]), used by
the \plan C compiler to access global variables (see the
\book{Linker} for details). The kernel must reload [[R12]]
because the user program may have used it for something
else.

