\subsection{FAQ}

%yoann: explain FAQ section as easy to be confused with complex virtual vs physical, kernel vs user, and some arch-specific requirement vs free design decision hard to understand
%claude:
The overview above introduced many addresses, registers,
tables, and mappings. It is easy to be confused, especially
because some aspects are imposed by the ARM hardware (e.g.,
the exception vector mechanism, the PSR layout, the MMU
page table format) while others are design decisions made
by the \plan kernel authors (e.g., the value of [[KZERO]],
the placement of [[VIRTIO]], the [[systab]] dispatch table).
The following questions and answers try to clarify the most
common sources of confusion.

%yoann: imagine a list of questions the reader could have

%yoann: HVector is specific address, but systab is another one, how force systab to be HVector? answer = actually systab is not exception table but syscall table, different concepts?
%claude:
{\bf Q: The exception vector table is at [[HVECTORS]] and the
syscall table is [[systab]]. How are they related?}
%claude:
A: They are different things. The exception vector table at
[[HVECTORS]] is a hardware mechanism: when a [[SWI]]
instruction executes, the ARM jumps to a fixed address in
this table. That entry loads the address of [[_vsvc]] from
[[vtable]]. Then [[_vsvc]] (assembly code) extracts the
syscall number from [[R0]] and calls [[arch__syscall()]]
(C code), which finally indexes into [[systab]] to find the
right kernel function. So [[HVECTORS]] is the hardware
entry point, and [[systab]] is the software dispatch table---they
are connected by the chain of code in between.

%yoann: SWI $0, other value used?  SWI $1?
%claude:
{\bf Q: Why [[SWI $0]]? Does the argument to [[SWI]] matter?}
%claude:
A: On \plan, the argument to [[SWI]] is ignored.  The syscall
number is passed in [[R0]] instead. The [[SWI]] instruction
is used purely for its side effect of trapping into supervisor
mode. Some other operating systems encode the syscall number
in the [[SWI]] argument, but \plan chose the simpler approach
of using a register. Similarly, Linux on x86 uses [[int 0x80]]
(or the faster [[syscall]] instruction on x86-64) to trap
into the kernel, with the syscall number passed in [[EAX]].

%yoann: Why kernel vs user  virtual space divide? why can't have user-space to
% be all of 4GB virtual address space and have kernel be different?
% (I think xv6 RISCV actually does that)
%claude:
{\bf Q: Why split the 4~GiB address space between kernel and user?
Could each have its own full 4~GiB?}
%claude:
A: Some systems do give user space the full address range and
switch page tables entirely when entering the kernel. For
example, xv6 on RISC-V maintains a separate kernel page table
(with direct virtual=physical mapping) and per-process user
page tables. On every syscall or interrupt, xv6 switches the
page table base register from the user's table to the kernel's.
To make this switch possible, both tables map a single
{trampoline} page at the same high virtual address---this is
where the switching code runs.
%claude:
The \plan approach is different and simpler: the kernel is
mapped in the upper half of {every} process's page table.
A syscall or interrupt does not need to switch page tables
at all---the kernel's code and data are always mapped and
immediately accessible. The trade-off is that user programs
get only 2~GiB of virtual space instead of 4~GiB (but on
a machine with 512~MiB of physical RAM this is not a
practical limitation). The benefits are: trap entry is
faster (no TLB flush from a page table switch), no
trampoline is needed, and the kernel can access user
memory directly (e.g., syscall arguments on the user
stack, buffer addresses) without switching page tables
first. The kernel still needs to validate user pointers
(e.g., check they are below [[KZERO]], handle page
faults), but the shared mapping makes the common case
simpler than with separate page tables where even
reading a user byte requires a special copy routine.

%yoann: can we have a page fault inside a page fault handler? Does kernel
% rely on TLB and MMU to access its own data structure? Can kernel memory
% be swapped?
%claude:
{\bf Q: Can a page fault occur inside the kernel? Can kernel
memory be swapped out?}
%claude:
A: The kernel's own pages are never swapped and are always
mapped (via the L1 section entries set up by [<mmuinit()>]).
So the kernel does not page-fault when accessing its own data
structures. A page fault can only occur for user-space
addresses. However, a page fault {can} occur while the kernel
is executing a syscall on behalf of a user process---for
example, when the kernel copies data from a user buffer
(the user's page might not be resident). The fault handler
recognizes this case and handles it.

%yoann: why VIRTIO mapped between user and kernel? why not above KZERO instead?
%claude:
{\bf Q: Why is [[VIRTIO]] mapped below [[KZERO]], in the gap
between user space and kernel space?}
%claude:
A: The kernel RAM mapping ([[KZERO+x]] = physical [[x]])
covers exactly [[Soc.dramsize]] (512~MiB), filling L1
entries 2048--2559. Placing the I/O registers above
[[KZERO]] would require additional L1 entries in the kernel
region, which would overlap with the simple offset mapping.
Putting them at [[0x7E000000]] (below [[KZERO]]) avoids
this conflict. User processes cannot access these pages
because the L1 entries are set with kernel-only permissions.

%yoann: Why CPUAddr below kernel? to reuse space below 0x8000 for something useful?
% alternatives?
%claude:
{\bf Q: Why is [[CPUADDR]] at [[0x2000]], below the kernel text
at [[0x8000]]?}
%claude:
A: The ARM firmware loads the kernel binary at physical
[[0x8000]]. The memory below that is unused by the binary,
so the kernel reuses it for the [[Cpu]] structure (at
[[0x2000]]), the L2 page table (at [[0x3000]]), and the L1
page table (at [[0x4000]]--[[0x8000]]). This avoids wasting
the 32~KiB gap that the firmware leaves.


\subsection{NSFAQ}

%yoann: explain "not-so-frequently asked question"
%claude:
The following are more subtle questions that may not occur
to every reader on first reading, but that help deepen the
understanding of the kernel's design.
\l TODO: add more NSFAQ as they come up


%yoann: maybe after all of this say that many things seem complicated and very arch-specific but say actually many things are the same across arch; list the essential things the kernel needs to organize and setup and even if concrete address can vary, the concept are very similar
%claude:
Much of this chapter may seem complicated and very
ARM-specific. But the essential concepts are the same
across architectures. Every kernel needs to:
\begin{itemize}
\item split the address space between kernel and user,
\item set up page tables (or their equivalent) so the MMU
can translate virtual to physical addresses,
\item place an exception/interrupt vector table at a known
address,
\item save and restore user registers on kernel entry/exit,
\item dispatch syscalls through a table of function pointers,
\item reserve memory for per-CPU state.
\end{itemize}
The concrete addresses ([[KZERO]], [[HVECTORS]], etc.), the
register conventions ([[R10]] for [[cpu]], [[R9]] for [[up]]),
and the page table format (L1 sections, L2 pages) are
ARM-specific details, but the architecture of the kernel
would look very similar on x86 or RISC-V.

\section{Book structure}

%claude:
The rest of the book is organized as follows.
Chapters~\ref{chap:core-ds} and~\ref{chap:concurrency}
present the foundational building blocks: core data
structures ([[Conf]], [[Cpu]], [[Label]], etc.) and
concurrency primitives (locks, [[sleep]]/[[wakeup]],
[[Rendez]]).
%claude:
Part~I, {\em Virtualizing the Machine}, covers how the
kernel gives each process the illusion of having the
hardware to itself: memory allocators
(Chapter~\ref{chap:memory}), processes
(Chapter~\ref{chap:processes}), interrupts and syscalls
(Chapter~\ref{chap:interrupts}), virtual memory
(Chapter~\ref{chap:virtual-memory}), scheduling
(Chapter~\ref{chap:scheduling}), time
(Chapter~\ref{chap:time}), and the boot sequence
(Chapter~\ref{chap:initialization}).
%claude:
Part~II, {\em Everything is a File}, covers \plan's
central abstraction: files as the uniform interface to
data, devices, and services. This includes the [[Chan]]
and [[Dev]] structures (Chapter~\ref{chap:files}),
directories (Chapter~\ref{chap:directories}), per-process
namespaces (Chapter~\ref{chap:namespaces}), the device
driver framework (Chapter~\ref{chap:devices}),
streaming I/O queues (Chapter~\ref{chap:queues}), and
on-disk file systems (Chapter~\ref{chap:filesystems}).
%claude:
Part~III, {\em Beyond the Basics}, covers the remaining
subsystems: inter-process communication
(Chapter~\ref{chap:ipc}), debugging and profiling
support (Chapters~\ref{chap:debugging-support}
and~\ref{chap:profiling-support}), advanced topics
(Chapter~\ref{chap:advanced}), and the conclusion
(Chapter~\ref{chap:conclusion}).
%claude:
Some appendices present non-functional code: debugging
helpers, error management, and generic utilities.


