%claude:
In this chapter, I will present the core data structures
of the kernel. Some have already been introduced in the
Overview: [<Ureg>], the processor modes ([[PsrMode]]),
the address typedefs, and the syscall dispatch table
([<systab>]). Here I will cover the remaining structures
that appear everywhere in the kernel: [<Conf>] (hardware
configuration), [<Cpu>] (per-processor state), [<Label>]
(context switch), and [<Ref>] (reference counting).

\section{[[Conf]] and [[conf]]}

%claude:
The [[Conf]] structure records what the kernel learned
about the hardware during the boot sequence: how many
processors, how much physical memory, and how many
processes to support. It is filled once by [<confinit()>]
during initialization and then treated as read-only.
<<struct [[Conf]]>>=
struct Conf
{
    ulong ncpu;    /* processors */
    Confmem mem[4];   /* physical memory */

    ulong nproc;    /* processes */
    <<[[Conf]] other fields>>
};
@ 
%old: 'ulong monitor;'

