\section{[[Cpu]] and [[cpu]]}

%claude:
The [[Cpu]] structure holds the per-processor state: which
process is currently running, the clock tick count, MMU
state, and a small kernel stack used during boot and
interrupts. On a uniprocessor Raspberry Pi~1 there is
a single [[Cpu]] at [[CPUADDR]]; on a multiprocessor
system each CPU has its own.

<<struct [[Cpu]]>>=
//coupling: do not change the order of the first 4 fields! 
// Some assembly code assumes this order.
struct Cpu
{
    int cpuno;     /* physical id of processor (KNOWN TO ASSEMBLY) */
    <<[[Cpu]] second field>>
      // ref<Proc>, or None if halting?
    Proc* proc;     /* current process on this processor */

    struct Arch_Cpu;

    <<[[Cpu]] time fields>>
    <<[[Cpu]] stat fields>>
    <<[[Cpu]] other fields>>
  
    // must be at the end of the structure!
    int stack[1];
};
@
%smp: obviously here because prepare the field for SMP coming later
%c: idiom to access not specified size (CPUSIZE - other fields)
%coupling: see 8(R(CPU)) in _vsvc code in bcm/, 12(R(CPU)) in cpureset
%history: %old:
% Cpu used to be called Mach, but in the end it didn't make sense.
% Maybe they originally used Mach for "machine" because back in the day
% there was only  monoprocessor machines, but now with multiprocessor
% machines having names like Mach to represent one cpu, or field names
% like machno, mach0init, etc seems wrong. So I've renamed it!
% A nice side effect is also that it avoids conflicts with libmach! 
% There it acually makes sense to use the Mach name because they speak 
% about a machine.

%claude:
The first fields have a fixed layout because assembly code
accesses them by hardcoded offsets. The [[stack[1]]] at
the end is a C idiom: the actual stack extends to the
end of the [[CPUSIZE]] page, so the array's ``one element''
is really the start of a much larger area.

% not that the stack actually is until CPUSIZE
<<constant [[CPUSIZE]](arm)>>=
#define CPUSIZE BY2PG
@
% will see lots of code like $(CPUADDR+CPUSIZE)
%x86: same


%yoann: more on ticks and hz in chapter~X
%claude:
We will see more about ticks and the clock in the
Interrupts chapter (Chapter~\ref{chap:interrupts}).

<<[[Cpu]] time fields>>=
ulong ticks;      /* of the clock since boot time */
@
% more on ticks in Time chapter. the "system clock"
% increments ticks. so ticks = number of "system clock" interrupts.
% in hzclock():    cpu->ticks++;
% why use arch_fastticks() function when can simply use cpu->ticks?
%  because fastticks are generated more frequently! faster ticks!
%  ticks, fastticks, perfticks, cycles, lcycles, grrr


<<[[Cpu]] time fields>>=
uvlong  cpuhz;
int cpumhz; // cpuhz / 1_000_000
@
%c: long long support; No need boxed Int64
% mv later? classic when speak about Cpu so maybe not too bad here.




%yoann: explain Cpu actually portable code, but obviously has arch specific fields too; also Kencc ext above where no need to give name to field, just 'struct Arch_Cpu;'
%claude:
The [[Cpu]] structure shown above is portable across all
architectures. But each architecture also has specific
fields (MMU state, floating-point context, etc.) that
are gathered in [[Arch_Cpu]]. Thanks to a Ken~C compiler
extension, [[struct Arch_Cpu;]] can be embedded in [[Cpu]]
without giving it a field name---its fields are accessed
directly as if they were part of [[Cpu]] itself.

<<struct [[Arch_Cpu]](arm)>>=
//coupling: do not change the first field! Some assembly code assumes this order
struct Arch_Cpu {
    <<[[Cpu]] [[Arch]] mmu fields(arm)>>
    <<[[Cpu]] [[Arch]] float fields(arm)>>
    <<[[Cpu]] [[Arch]] save of first five registers fields(arm)>>
};
@
%coupling: see 12(R(CPU)) in cpureset()
%dead: 
% Lock    alarmlock;      /* access to alarm list */
% void*   alarm;          /* alarms bound to this clock */
% ulong   delayloop;
% int cputype;
% int lastintr;
%    <<[[Cpu]] [[Arch]] other fields(arm)>>


% cpu must be "something" that is local to each processor. How to achieve
%  that? if there was a special instruction like MYCPUID then could
%  make cpu a macro to cpus[MYCPUID()]. Could also use one register
%  to hold it and so have something like extern register Cpu* cpu;
%  This is actually the case on some archi like bcm.
%     extern register Mach* m;			/* R10 */
%  for sure this is a technique leading to a local value and different
%  in each processor.
%  But on PC we can't do that because there is not enough registers to
%  spare.
%  So cpu is a variable holding an addr that points to an area that
%  is different on each processor, thx to a trick involving the page table.
% could also have instead of cpu and cpus have cpus and a Int *mycpu; where
% mycpu points to the per-processor memory area and hold the value
% of the processor, but then each access to cpu will be more costly
% than a direct access as it's done above.
%claude:
The [[cpu]] global must be per-processor: on a multiprocessor
system, each CPU must see its own [[Cpu]] structure.
Since each processor has its own set of registers,
a dedicated register is a natural way to hold
per-processor state.
On ARM, this is achieved by dedicating register [[R10]]---the [[5c]]
compiler's [[extern register]] extension reserves [[R10]]
so it is never used for anything else. Each processor sets
its [[R10]] to point to its own [[Cpu]] during boot.
Note that [[R10]] is only reserved in kernel code, not in
user-space programs; it is a kernel convention. That is why
[[_vsvc]] sets [[R(CPU)]] early upon entering kernel mode
(visible in the syscall trace diagram above).
On x86, where registers are scarce, a different trick
involving the page table is used instead.

<<global [[cpu]](arm)>>=
extern register Cpu* cpu;           /* R10 */
@
%smp:
%x86: differs in different archi!
%c: powerful! almost assembly level instruction from C
%old: was called [[m]]. Xv6 also use the name 'cpu'.

% (arm) because different in different archi. Can afford to use register
% (which simplifies things a lot) in arm because ARM has lots of registers.

% R10 will contain most likely CPUADDR. So cpu->xxx translate to yyy(R10)
%  where yyy is offset of xxx in Cpu struct.
\t on Raspberry Pi 2 with multiple processors??


<<global [[cpus]]>>=
/*
 * Each processor sees its own Cpu structure at address CPUADDR.
 * However, the Cpu structures must also be available via the per-processor
 * MMU information array cpus, mainly for disambiguation and access to
 * the clock which is only maintained by the bootstrap processor (0).
 */
// array<ref<Cpu>>
Cpu* cpus[MAXCPUS];
@
%smp:
%old: machaddr. xv6 also use the name 'cpus'.

% this is portable across all archs.


<<constant [[MAXCPUS]](arm)>>=
#define MAXCPUS     4           /* max # cpus system can run */
@
%smp:
%old: MAXMACH

% But on Raspberry Pi 1 only 1 really. On Pi 2? Pi 3?

% why macro? because again in other archi it could be more complex
%  but then why in portdat? (was originally elsewhere?)
<<macro [[CPUS]]>>=
#define CPUS(n)  (cpus[n])
@
%old: MACHP
%smp:

%yoann: explain Active and why need this given we already have cpus; seems redundant
%claude:
The [[Active]] structure tracks global multiprocessor
state that does not belong to any single [[Cpu]]. The
[[cpus]] bitmap records which processors are online,
and [[exiting]] signals a system-wide shutdown. While
[[cpus[]]] (the array) gives access to each processor's
[[Cpu]] structure, [[Active]] answers a different question:
which processors are alive, and is the system shutting down?
It also carries a [[Lock]] to serialize concurrent updates
from multiple CPUs.

<<struct [[Active]]>>=
struct Active
{
    // array<bool> (coupling: sizeof(int) must be >= MAXCPUS)
    int cpus;      /* bitmap of active CPUs */
    bool exiting;    /* shutdown */
    <<[[Active]] other fields>>
    // extra
    Lock;
};
@ 
%c: bitset
%smp: SMP specific so maybe move later?

<<global [[active]]>>=
struct Active active;
@ 
