\section{[[Proc]] and [[up]]}

% the big one
%claude:
The [[Proc]] structure is the largest and most important data
structure in the kernel---it is what the kernel knows about
a process. Each running program has one [[Proc]] containing
its state, memory map, open files, scheduling priority,
parent/child relationships, notes (signals), error handling
context, and much more. It is one of the largest
structures in the kernel.
%claude:
The structure is organized in sections (visible in the
comment banners below), each corresponding roughly to a
chapter in this book. We will only show the overview here;
the individual fields are introduced gradually in their
respective chapters.
<<struct [[Proc]]>>=
struct Proc
{
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
//coupling: have to be first! Some assembly code assumes this order.
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
    <<[[Proc]] assembly fields>>
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
// State
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
    <<[[Proc]] state fields>>
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
// Memory
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
    <<[[Proc]] memory fields>>

    struct Arch_Proc;
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
// Scheduling
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
    <<[[Proc]] scheduling fields>>
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
// Files
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
    <<[[Proc]] files fields>>
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
// Notes
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
    <<[[Proc]] notes fields>>
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
// Process hierarchy
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
    <<[[Proc]] hierarchy fields>>
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
// Synchronization
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
    <<[[Proc]] synchronization fields>>
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
// Error management
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
    <<[[Proc]] error managment fields>>
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
// Stats, profiling
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
    <<[[Proc]] stats and profiling fields>>
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
// Debugging (the kernel itself)
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
    <<[[Proc]] debugging fields>>
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
// For debugger, strace
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
    <<[[Proc]] debugger fields>>
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
// Other
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
    <<[[Proc]] other fields>>
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
// Extra
//--------------------------------------------------------------------
    <<[[Proc]] extra fields>>
};
@ 
% apparently this uses 3004 bytes ... huge. procalloc is 6Mo!


%yoann: like for Cpu and Arch_Cpu, has also arch-specific proc field we will detail later
%claude:
Just as [[Cpu]] has an [[Arch_Cpu]], [[Proc]] embeds an
anonymous [[struct Arch_Proc]] for architecture-specific
fields (on ARM, this is the per-process MMU state).
We will detail these fields later.

<<struct [[Arch_Proc]](arm)>>=
struct Arch_Proc
{
    <<[[Proc]] [[Arch]] memory fields(arm)>>
};
@
%old: PMMU

%yoann: give transition, first maybe most important field, state!
%claude:
Perhaps the most important field in [[Proc]] is its
{state}---whether the process is running, ready to run,
sleeping, or dead:

<<[[Proc]] state fields>>=
// enum<Procstate>
int state; // Dead, Queuing, etc, (used by /proc/#/status if psstate==nil)
@

% see Proc.pid also later.
%claude:
A process is always in one of the following states. The
most important ones are [[Running]] (executing on a CPU),
[[Ready]] (runnable, waiting for the scheduler to pick it),
and [[Wakeme]] (sleeping, waiting for an event):
<<enum [[procstate]]>>=
/* Process states, Proc.state */
enum Procstate
{
    Dead = 0,
    Running,
    <<[[Procstate]] cases>>
};
@ 
