\section{[[Chan]]}
% and proc->fd[]? in title?

% everything is a file/Chan :)
% diff with file descriptor? fd = index in chan table (fgrp),
% chan = opened/active file
%claude:
A [[Chan]] (``channel'') is the kernel's representation of
an {open file}. It is the internal object behind a user's
file descriptor---the file descriptor is just an integer
index into a per-process table of [[Chan]] pointers.
Because everything in \plan is a file, channels are used
everywhere: for real files on disk, for device control
files like [[/dev/cons]], for network connections, for
mounted file servers, etc.
%claude:
The key fields are [[type]] (which device driver owns this
channel), [[dev]] (a device-specific sub-identifier---together
[[type]] and [[dev]] play the role of \unix's major and
minor device numbers),
[[qid]] (the file's unique identity on that device, like
an inode number), [[path]] (the file name), [[offset]]
(the current read/write position), and [[mode]] (read,
write, or both):
<<struct [[Chan]]>>=
struct Chan
{
    ushort type; // idx in devtab
    ulong dev;
    Qid qid;

    Path* path;

    vlong offset;     /* in fd */

    //enum<open>, actually restricted to the OREAD|OWRITE|ORDWR of open type
    ushort mode;     /* read/write */

    bool ismtpt; // is a mount point

    union {
       void* aux; // generic pointer, for specific usages
       <<[[Chan]] union other fields>>
    };
    <<[[Chan]] other fields>>

    // extra
    Ref; /* the Lock in this Ref is also Chan's lock */
    <<[[Chan]] extra fields>>
};
@
% more LP split? type put closer to devtab?
% could put 'dev' closer to device for fs where want more than just type

% type =~ major, and dev =~ minor

%yoann: explain a few Proc fields have the Chan type
%claude:
Every process holds a few [[Chan]] pointers directly
in its [[Proc]] structure. The two most fundamental ones
are [[slash]] (the root of the process's namespace) and
[[dot]] (its current directory):

<<[[Proc]] files fields>>=
// ref<Chan>
Chan  *slash; // The root! used by namec()
// ref_counted<Chan>
Chan  *dot; // The current directory
@

% on pathchar() :) why DOS used '\' instead of '/'
%http://blogs.msdn.com/b/larryosterman/archive/2005/06/24/432386.aspx
% because IBM was already using / for utility flag marker, e.g. ls /a


% rob pike: "q for unique"
% qid =~ inode =~ internal representation of a file on a filesystem(fileserver)
%claude:
A [[Qid]] (``q'' for ``unique'') is \plan's equivalent of
a \unix inode number: it uniquely identifies a file within a
device or file server. The [[path]] field is the unique
identifier, [[vers]] is a version number for cache
invalidation, and [[type]] distinguishes files from
directories:
<<struct [[Qid]]>>=
struct Qid
{
  // note that this is not a string, but an int! it's kind of an inode
  uvlong  path;
  // for cache invalidation
  ulong vers;
  // enum<Qidtype>
  byte type;
};
@ 
%coupling: this structure ir also defined in libc.h

%yoann: explain maybe more path that is a number where one would expect a string, and vers that is unusual
%claude:
Despite its name, [[path]] is not a string but a 64-bit
integer---it is a unique numeric identifier for a file
within a device, much like a \unix inode number. The name
is confusing because [[Chan]] also has a separate [[path]]
field (of type [[Path*]]) that holds the actual string
pathname. The [[vers]] field is more unusual: it is a
version number that the file server increments whenever
the file's content changes. The kernel uses it for cache
invalidation---if a cached [[Qid]] has a stale [[vers]],
the kernel knows it must re-read the file's metadata.

% uvlong for path? need that many unique identifier on one device?

<<enum [[qidtype]]>>=
/* bits in Qid.type */
enum Qidtype {
  QTFILE = 0x00,    /* plain file */
  QTDIR = 0x80,    /* type bit for directories */
  <<[[Qidtype]] cases>>
};
@ 
