\section{[[Dev]] and [[devtab]]}
% actually Device also plays the role of filesystem and even fileserver!
% everything is a file ... server!

% so devtab = major/minor + VFS +??? . Devices are often a special case
% of a one-level directory containing a single file and thx to union
% dir we can gather them in one directory such as /dev/

% concrete device like kbd, screen, are exported via the
%  read() method below from /dev/cons, write() method to /dev/cons, and then
%  fancy graphics are write() to /dev/vga!

% open take a Chan? how bootstrap? how to get an handle to a file
% you want to open? first attach to get Chan from root?
%claude:
A [[Dev]] is a {device driver}---or more precisely, a
{file server} implemented in the kernel. Each [[Dev]]
provides a set of methods ([[open]], [[read]], [[write]],
[[close]], etc.)\ that implement the file interface for
a particular kind of resource: the console ([[devcons]]),
the process table ([[devproc]]), the root file system
([[devroot]]), the SD card ([[devsd]]), etc. The single
character [[dc]] (e.g., [['c']] for console, [['p']] for
proc) identifies the device in \plan's [[#c]], [[#p]]
naming convention.
%claude: %unix:
In \unix, devices are identified by {major} and {minor}
numbers---opaque integers that require a lookup table to
understand. Accessing a device requires creating special
files with [[mknod]] and a populated [[/dev]] directory.
\plan replaces the major number with a
human-readable Unicode character (a [[Rune]]): [['c']] for
the console, [['p']] for the process table, [['e']] for the
environment, etc. You can see these characters in
\plan's device path syntax: [[#c]] for the console device,
[[#p]] for the proc device. This is much clearer than
memorizing that major~4 means the console. And because
[[Rune]] is a Unicode code point (not an ASCII byte),
\plan can support more than 256 different device drivers.
While [[Chan.type]] is still a numeric index internally
(into [[devtab]]), the user-visible name uses the
character from [[Dev.dc]]---so the human never sees the
number.

<<struct [[Dev]]>>=
struct Dev
{
    Rune dc; // dev character code, e.g. '/' (devroot), 'e' (devenv), ...
    char* name;

    <<[[Dev]] methods>>
};
@ 
% no seek? seek is managed generically? actually read and write take an
% offset as a parameter. from read(2)
%  "By combining the operations in a single atomic call, they more closely
%   match the 9P protocol"
% does it match 9p? I guess it closely match 9p

%claude:
The global [[devtab]] is an array of pointers to all the
[[Dev]] structures compiled into the kernel---it is the
registry of all available device drivers. When a [[Chan]]
is opened on a device, [[Chan.type]] is the index into
[[devtab]], so that [[devtab[c->type]->read()]] calls the
right driver's read method.

<<global [[devtab]]>>=
// array<ref_own<Dev>>
Dev** devtab = nil;
@

