\section{Test and set: [[arch_tas()]] (ARM)}

%http://g.oswego.edu/dl/jmm/cookbook.html for barrier, tas, etc
% in different processors.

% TAS is the building block of concurrency primitives.
%claude:
{Test-and-set} is the hardware primitive on which all
spin locks are built. The idea is simple: atomically
write~1 into a memory word and return the old value.
If the old value was~0, the caller has acquired the lock;
if it was already~1, someone else holds it. In C terms,
[[lock()]] will call [[if(arch_tas(\&l->key) == 0)]].
%claude:
The key word is ``atomically.'' On a RISC architecture
like ARM, a naive implementation would need two separate
instructions---a load and a store:
\begin{verbatim}
  // hypothetical broken arch_tas:
  MOVW  0(R1), R0       // load key into R0
  MOVW  $1, 0(R1)       // store 1 into key
  RET                    // return old value in R0
\end{verbatim}
But an interrupt can fire between the load and the store:
\begin{verbatim}
  Process A (syscall):    Process B (interrupt handler):

  MOVW 0(R1), R0
    (reads key=0)
                          <--- timer interrupt fires --->
                          MOVW 0(R1), R0
                            (reads key=0, A hasn't stored yet)
                          MOVW $1, 0(R1)
                            (sets key=1)
                          R0==0 -> if() succeeds
                          ... enters critical section ...
                          ... done, returns from interrupt ...

  MOVW $1, 0(R1)
    (sets key=1)
  R0==0 -> if() succeeds
  ... also enters critical section! BUG
\end{verbatim}
Both see [[key]]=0 and both believe they acquired the lock.
%claude:
On the Raspberry Pi~1, the solution is the [[SWPW]]
(swap word) instruction, which performs the load-and-store
in a single indivisible operation---the interrupt sees
either the state before or after, never in between.
On the Pi~2 (ARMv7, SMP), a different mechanism using
[[LDREX]]/[[STREX]] is needed because [[SWPW]] is
deprecated and does not provide the memory ordering
guarantees required for multiprocessor correctness.

% call we will see later as arch_tas(&lock->key)
<<function [[arch_tas]](raspberry pi1)(arm)>>=
TEXT    arch_tas(SB), $-4
    MOVW    R0,R1
    MOVW    $1,R0
    SWPW    R0,(R1)         /* fix: deprecated in armv6 */
    RET
@
% return old value via R0 too.
% For Pi1 only concurrency issue is kernel code interrupted,
% so SWPW just ensure atomic instruction so interrupt will be done
% either before or after SWPW

