\section{Atomic count: [[arch_xinc()]] and [[arch_xdec()]] (ARM)}

% arch_tas() is to make sure one arrive first on something.
% another fundamental concurrency operation is increment/decrement atomically
% (actually can simulate second one with first, see Ref later, but can be
% useful to have something faster on certain architecture)

% x for exclusive? was better ainc, for atomic inc?
%claude:
The other fundamental atomic operation is
increment/decrement. These are used for reference counting
(e.g., [[Ref]]). On the uniprocessor Pi~1, the
implementation is trivial: disable interrupts, modify the
counter, re-enable. On SMP, a more sophisticated
approach using [[LDREX]]/[[STREX]] would be needed.

% (lock -> inccnt) | _allocb -> <>
<<function [[arch_xinc]](raspberry pi1)(arm)>>=
void
arch_xinc(long *p)
{
    int s;

    s = arch_splhi();
    ++*p;
    arch_splx(s);
}
@
%c: easy call from C assembly! just declare its prototype and
% follow simple convention in assembly code
%old: was called xinc? or _xinc? 
\t conflict with libc version? cleanup this _xinc ainc mess. rename atomic_inc

% good enough when have only 1 processor! for SMP see Section~\ref{sec:smp}.


<<function [[arch_xdec]](raspberry pi1)(arm)>>=
long
arch_xdec(long *p)
{
    int s, v;

    s = arch_splhi();
    v = --*p;
    arch_splx(s);
    return v;
}
@



\section{Spin [[Lock]]}

% arch_splhi good, but need finer granularity!
% Also does not really handle concurrency when have SMP.
% arch_tas can be building block for more complex critical regions.
%claude:
A [[Lock]] (spin lock) is built on top of [[arch_tas()]].
Unlike [[arch_splhi()]], a spin lock provides mutual
exclusion across CPUs, not just against interrupts on one
CPU. The caller spins in a tight loop until the lock
becomes available. Spin locks are appropriate for very
short critical regions (a few lines of code) where the
wait is expected to be brief.
%claude:
On a uniprocessor, a spin lock still serves a purpose:
while a process holds a lock, the kernel prevents it from
being scheduled out (via [[Proc.nlocks]]), which effectively
protects the critical region from other processes. However,
a spin lock on a uniprocessor does {not} protect against
interrupts---for that, [[ILock]] (next section) is needed.
Note that [[Lock]] itself is portable, architecture-independent
code (in [[port/]])---it provides mutual exclusion on any
architecture, uniprocessor or multiprocessor, by relying
on the arch-specific [[arch_tas()]] primitive we just saw.

<<struct [[Lock]]>>=
// a.k.a Spinlock
struct Lock
{
    ulong key; // 0 when unset, 1 (or 0xDEADDEAD) when acquired, could be a bool

    <<[[Lock]] ilock fields>>
    <<[[Lock]] debugging fields>>
    <<[[Lock]] other fields>>
};
@ 
