\section{Uninterruptable [[ILock]]}

%claude:
An [[ILock]] is a spin lock that also disables interrupts
before acquiring the lock. This is necessary when a data
structure is accessed both from normal kernel code (syscalls)
and from interrupt handlers. Without disabling interrupts,
a deadlock can occur: a syscall acquires the lock, an
interrupt fires on the same CPU, the interrupt handler tries
to acquire the same lock, and spins forever because the
interrupted syscall is the one holding it.
%claude:
[[ILock]] solves this by calling [[arch_splhi()]] before
[[arch_tas()]], and saving the old interrupt state in
[[Lock.sr]] so [[iunlock()]] can restore it. In practice,
[[ILock]] is used for structures accessed from interrupt
handlers: the timer list, device driver queues, etc.
<<struct [[ILock]]>>=
typedef Lock ILock;
@
