\section{Waiting [[QLock]]}
% can be seen also as a Waiting queue, Sleepable Lock?

%ocaml: similar to mutex.mli

% when QLock vs just Lock?
%claude:
A [[QLock]] (queuing lock, also known as a {mutex}) is a
lock where the caller goes to {sleep} instead of spinning
when the lock is not available. This is important for
critical regions that may take a long time---for instance,
I/O operations or file system lookups. Spinning for
milliseconds would waste CPU time; sleeping lets the
scheduler run other processes.
%claude:
The waiting processes form a queue ([[head]]/[[tail]]),
linked through [[Proc.qnext]]. When the lock holder calls
[[qunlock()]], it wakes the first waiter in the queue.
The internal coordination uses a [[Lock]] (spin lock) to
protect the queue itself, but the spin is only held for
the few instructions needed to enqueue or dequeue---the
actual wait is a sleep.
<<struct [[QLock]]>>=
// Kernel basic lock with Queue (renamed to avoid ambiguity with libc.h QLock)
// a.k.a Mutex
struct KQLock
{
    bool  locked;   /* flag */
  
    // list<ref<Proc>> (next = Proc.qnext)
    Proc  *head;    /* next process waiting for object */
    // option<ref<Proc>> (direct access to tail, queue)
    Proc  *tail;    /* last process waiting for object */

    <<[[KQLock]] debugging fields>>
  
