\section{Safeguards}

% Very easy to shoot yourself in the foot! Some bad interactions
% between spinlock, qlock, and ilocks.
%claude:
Concurrency bugs are notoriously hard to find, so the
kernel includes several runtime checks to catch common
mistakes: unlocking from the wrong process, sleeping
while holding a spin lock, or taking a qlock while
interrupts are disabled. We already saw several safeguards
earlier: [[Lock.pc]] and [[Proc.lastlock]] recording who
acquired a lock, [[Lock.cpu]] tracking which processor
holds it, and [[splpc]] in [[Cpu]] remembering who disabled
interrupts. This section covers additional checks.

\subsection{[[Lock.p]]}

%claude:
Each [[Lock]] records which process acquired it (in
[[Lock.p]]). On unlock, the kernel checks that the same
process is releasing it---a mismatch indicates a bug
(for instance, a context switch that should not have
happened while the lock was held):

<<[[Lock]] debugging fields>>=
// option<ref<Proc>>, None when key == 0
Proc  *p; // the process who did the locking should be the same unlocking
@
%c: complex graph relation with pointer! no need use intermediate
% pid here, link directly to the Proc

<<[[lock()]] got the lock, update other fields>>=
l->p = up;
@
<<[[canlock()]] lock was not already held, update other fields>>=
l->p = up;
@

<<[[unlock()]] sanity checks>>=
if(l->p != up)
    print("unlock: up changed: pc %#p, acquired at pc %lux, lock p %#p, unlock up %#p\n", getcallerpc(&l), l->pc, l->p, up);
@
%old: used to be second check in a list of 3 checks, but with LP it's reordered
% but I don't think it matters

% Note that this check is not done for qunlock.


<<[[ilock()]] got the lock, update other fields>>=
l->p = up;
@
