% sanity check in iunlock. 
\t Why? Because often used in interrupt context?


\subsection{[[Proc.nlocks]]}

%claude:
[[Proc.nlocks]] counts how many spin locks the current
process holds. This is crucial: a process holding a spin
lock must not be scheduled out, because the lock protects
a critical region that must complete without interruption.
The scheduler checks [[nlocks]] and delays rescheduling
until all locks are released. Similarly, [[qlock()]]
checks [[nlocks]] and prints a warning if a process tries
to sleep while holding a spin lock---that would deadlock,
because no other process could run to release the lock.
%claude:
Note that [[nlocks]] itself uses [[arch_xinc()]]/[[arch_xdec()]]
(via [[inccnt()]]/[[deccnt()]]) rather than
[[incref()]]/[[decref()]], because the latter use
[[lock()]]/[[unlock()]]---which would modify [[nlocks]],
creating a circular dependency.
<<[[Proc]] synchronization fields>>=
// As long as the current process hold spinlocks (to kernel data structures),
// we will not schedule another process in sched() or unlock(); 
// only the last unlock will eventually cause a rescheduling.
Ref nlocks;   /* number of locks held by proc */
@ 
% need Ref here? need exclusion access across processors?

% The code that avoid the scheduling is in sched() and also in unlock().
% see Section X.
% Also checked in sleep().
%ocaml: OCaml thread.ml does the same! so this is not just a safeguard.

<<[[lock()]] increment nlocks>>=
if(up)
    inccnt(&up->nlocks);    /* prevent being scheded */
@
<<[[lock()]] decrement nlocks>>=
if(up)
    deccnt(&up->nlocks);
@

<<function [[inccnt]]>>=
// See also ref.c incref() and decref(), but we can't use them here as they
// themselves rely on lock() and unlock(). 
static void
inccnt(Ref *r)
{
    arch_xinc(&r->ref);
}
@ 
% so why use incref()/decref()? why not use arch_xinc()/arch_xdec()?

<<function [[deccnt]]>>=
static int
deccnt(Ref *r)
{
    int x;

    x = arch_xdec(&r->ref);
    if(x < 0)
        panic("deccnt pc=%#p", getcallerpc(&r));
    return x;
}
@ 
