\section{Synchronization}
% different from critical regions
% what if want to do producer/consumer?
% consumer has to wait for producer to produce. How do that
% with the locking stuff we have seen before? Enough?

% already have seen kinda of synchro with sched()/ready()

% could put sysrendezvous actually here? or too early?
% maybe yes, after all in Qlock we already have seen
% some calls to sched()/ready()

% see sleep.ps in plan9 documents
%claude:
The locking primitives above provide {mutual exclusion}:
preventing two threads from accessing the same data at the
same time. But they do not solve {synchronization}: how does
a process wait for something to happen (e.g., a disk read
to complete, a pipe to have data)? For that, the kernel
needs a way to put a process to sleep and wake it up later.

\subsection{Rendez-vous}
% sleep/wakeup?
%claude:
The fundamental synchronization mechanism in the kernel is
[[sleep()]]/[[wakeup()]], built around the [[Rendez]]
structure (a ``rendezvous point''). A process calls
[[sleep()]] with a condition function; if the condition is
not yet true, the process is put to sleep. Later, when
another process or an interrupt handler makes the condition
true, it calls [[wakeup()]] to resume the sleeper.
The full code is in Chapter~\ref{chap:processes}.

\subsection{Producer/Consumer Queue}
%IO Queue
% will see later
%claude:
The I/O [[Queue]] structure (Chapter~\ref{chap:queues})
uses [[sleep()]]/[[wakeup()]] to implement producer/consumer
synchronization: a reader sleeps when the queue is empty,
a writer sleeps when it is full, and each wakes the other.

\subsection{Semaphore}
% those are actually used for user-level locks, see libcore/libc/port/lock.c
%claude:
The kernel also provides semaphores ([[SEMACQUIRE]]/[[SEMRELEASE]]
syscalls), but these are primarily for {user-level}
synchronization. The C library's [[Lock]] and [[QLock]]
(in [[libcore/libc/port/lock.c]]) are implemented on top
of these kernel semaphores. Inside the kernel itself,
the spin locks and qlocks described above are used instead.







%###############################################################################
\part{Virtualizing the Machine}
%###############################################################################

%claude:
The kernel's central job is to give each process the
illusion of having the entire machine to itself. This
part covers the mechanisms that make this illusion work:
virtual memory (page tables and page faults) backed by
a physical page allocator, process creation and management,
interrupt and syscall handling (the boundary between the
virtual and real machines), scheduling (virtualizing the
CPU so each process gets its turn), time keeping, and
finally the boot sequence that sets all of this up.

%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Memory}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:memory}

%yoann: Looks so simple from user point of view :) just brk()!
% but behind there are lots of machinery to make this possible.
%claude:
From the user's point of view, memory is simple: call
[[brk()]] (or [[malloc()]]) and get memory. Behind this
simple interface lies a hierarchy of allocators, each
solving a different problem.

<<[[systab]] memory syscalls>>=
[BRK]      sysbrk,
@

%http://duartes.org/gustavo/blog/post/how-the-kernel-manages-your-memory/

\section{Overview}
% kernel vs user memory

%claude:
Memory management has a bootstrapping problem: you need
memory to track which memory is free, but you do not have
an allocator yet. The kernel solves this by building
allocators in layers, each bootstrapped from the previous:
\begin{itemize}
\item[0.] The kernel binary's {data section} contains
statically allocated allocator metadata. The boot code
also detects physical memory here and records it in
[[Conf.mem]].
\item[1.] [<xalloc()>] carves large structures from those
banks. From here the hierarchy forks.
\item[2a.] On the kernel side, [<malloc()>] provides
fine-grained allocation from a [[Pool]] backed by
[[xalloc]].
\item[2b.] On the user side, [<palloc>] manages physical
pages. User [[brk()]] takes pages from [[palloc]];
user-space [[malloc()]] (in libc) subdivides them.
\end{itemize}
%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  Layer 2:  kernel malloc()        palloc
            (Pool)                 (page allocator)
               |                      |
          kernel side            user brk()
                                      |
                                 user malloc()
                                 (in libc)
                                      |
                                 user side

  Layer 1:          xalloc
               (allocates Proc[], Page[],
                Pool arenas, from Confmem)

  Layer 0:  kernel binary data section
            (xlists, conf, devtab, etc.)
            edata/end mark free memory start

  Hardware: physical RAM (detected by confinit)
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
The following sections present each layer in detail.


%allocation memory kinds:
% - static and initialized (data) in binary itself! "allocated" by 
%    kernel loader
% - static and unitiliaized (bss), "allocated" by kernel loader again,
%   initialized to zero in asm (via 'edata', 'end' linker info)
% - dynamic
%    - via static arena (and trick to maintain free list)
%    - via malloc (heap)

% malloc/free memory does not appear from thin air, need data structure
% to remember what was malloced, where, how much memory remains,
% so need memory to talk about memory ... chichen and egg.

% approach: 
% - end, edata fixed area
% - confmem detection (and mapram)
% - xalloc static metadata about mem
%  - then from it build pools
%    - then from it get malloc
%  - orthogonally also use xalloc for procs, pages, more??
% - palloc.mem

% then for user, pages is the granularity. see brk too.

% => figure of physical memory with zoom on kernel data and bss section,
%   conf.confmem, xalloc metadata, procallocs and pageallog, all procs,
%   all pages,  and then kernel memory area malloc. The user memory area
%   is made of all those pages.
% get the actual number (and try optimize? less % for kernel more for user,
%  reduce Page data structure? less conf.nproc?

% hierarchy of allocator:
%  - xalloc for big chunks (but small static list)
%    and also to handle possibly discontinuous free memory chunks (Confmem[4])
%  - pool for finer chunks
%  - (minor and major heap when in ocaml kernel)

% Malloc has fragmentation. It would be inefficient to make
% long-lived big structure interfere with those smalller/temporary structures.
% (this is a similar opti in ocaml with the minor vs major heap)

\section{Long-lived structure allocator: [[xalloc()]]}

%// Memory allocator for long lived allocated structures
%// e.g. array of Proc (procalloc), array of Pages (palloc.pages), but
%// It is also the pool provider for kernel malloc()
%long lived because xalloc does not support well fragmentation
% can only have certain number of disparate holes

% kinda of a first-fit no-compacting allocator?

% kernel memory allocator. This is for the kernel! For user
% it will be Palloc.mem (and Pages that is actually metadata about
% pages that are in kernel memory allocated by xalloc). Also all the
% memory here can be only before MAXKPA.

% start with Confmem, huge bank, now we want to use some memory.
% draw figure with idea. Draw also figures with many holes in memory.
% Can't support too much fragmentation (no compact() function)

% alternatives? why not just free bitmaps? instead we use
% free (linked) list below (and also for pages)
%claude:
[[xalloc()]] is the bottom-level dynamic allocator. It
manages the raw physical memory banks from [[Conf.mem]]
using a simple first-fit, non-compacting algorithm. Its
own metadata---the [[xlists]] global, containing the
[[Hole[128]]] array---lives in the kernel's data section
(layer~0), so it needs no memory allocation to get started.
%claude:
[[xalloc]] is called only during initialization to allocate
a few large, long-lived structures---the [[Proc]] array,
the [<Page>] array, and the [[malloc]] pool---that will
never be freed. This simplicity is deliberate: the
fixed-size hole array cannot handle heavy fragmentation,
but it does not need to.

\subsection{Data structures}

\subsubsection{[[Xalloc]]}

%claude:
The [[Xalloc]] structure manages free memory as a sorted
linked list of [[Hole]]s. 

%\subsection{[[Xalloc]]}

<<struct [[Xalloc]]>>=
// Long lived data structure allocator (singleton)
struct Xalloc
{
    // array<Hole> where each Hole is linked to another hole
    Hole  hole[Nhole];
  
    // list<ref<Hole>> (next = Hole.next) list of free hole entries (addr=top=size=0)
    Hole* unused_slots; 

    // list<ref<Hole>> (next = Hole.next) memory holes, sorted by their top addr
    Hole* sorted_holes; 
  
    // extra
    Lock;
};
@
%old: I renamed fields: flist -> unused_slots, table -> sorted_hole
% note that the hole entry is free means the metadata is free.
% a used hole in sorted_holes means actually the hole entry is valid
% and describe some free memory there
%c: bootstrapped global array in Data section.

<<[[Hole]] extra fields>>=
Hole* next; // list<ref<Hole>> of Xalloc.sorted_holes or Xalloc.unused_slots
@

<<constants holes>>=
enum
{
    Nhole   = 128,
    <<constant [[Magichole]]>>
};
@


%claude:
Each [[Hole]] describes a
contiguous region of free memory (between [[addr]] and
[[top]]). The [[Hole]] entries themselves are pre-allocated
in a fixed-size array ([[hole[Nhole]]]), and those not
currently describing a free region are kept in a separate
``unused slots'' list.

%\subsection{[[Hole]]}

<<struct [[Hole]]>>=
struct Hole
{
    // between addr and top the memory is free, this is the "hole"
    phys_addr addr; 
    phys_addr top; 
    ulong size; // top - addr (in bytes)

    // Extra
    <<[[Hole]] extra fields>>
};
@
\t phys_addr? I dont think so, it's a kern_addr!
%c: impossible to define memory allocator in ocaml! need to resort to C!
