\subsection{[[poolprint()]]}

%yoann: explain who calls this function and motivations
%claude:
[<poolprint()>] and [<ppanic()>] are the pool's diagnostic
callbacks. They are called by the pool allocator code (in
libc) when it detects corruption or wants to log warnings.
Because the pool lock is held when these are called,
they cannot print directly---[[print()]] calls [[write()]]
which may acquire locks internally, risking deadlock.
Instead, [[poolprint()]] uses [[vseprint()]] (which does
not allocate or take locks) to append to the message buffer
in [[Private]], and [[punlock()]] prints it after releasing
the lock:

<<function [[poolprint]]>>=
/*
 * because we can't print while we're holding the locks, 
 * we have the save the message and print it once we let go.
 */
static void
poolprint(Pool *p, char *fmt, ...)
{
    va_list v;
    Private *pv;

    pv = p->private;
    va_start(v, fmt);
    vseprint(pv->msg+strlen(pv->msg), pv->msg+sizeof pv->msg, fmt, v);
    va_end(v);
}
@



<<function [[ppanic]]>>=
static void
ppanic(Pool *p, char *fmt, ...)
{
    va_list v;
    Private *pv;
    char msg[sizeof pv->msg];

    pv = p->private;
    va_start(v, fmt);
    vseprint(pv->msg+strlen(pv->msg), pv->msg+sizeof pv->msg, fmt, v);
    va_end(v);
    memmove(msg, pv->msg, sizeof msg);
    iunlock(&pv->lk);
    panic("%s", msg);
}
@


\section{Kernel [[malloc()]]}

% the memcpy, memmove, functions of libc use malloc? probably not

% This is for more short-lived or shorter structure.
%claude:
The kernel's [[malloc()]] and [[free()]] are thin wrappers
around [[poolalloc()]]/[[poolfree()]] on the [[mainmem]]
pool. Unlike user-space [[malloc]], the kernel version
always zeroes the memory (via [[memset]]) and can
optionally record the caller's PC in a {tag} area for
debugging (when [[Npadlong]] is nonzero).

\subsection{[[malloc()]]}

<<function [[malloc]]>>=
kern_vp
malloc(ulong size)
{
    kern_vp v;

    v = poolalloc(mainmem, size + Npadlong*sizeof(ulong));
    if(v == nil)
        return nil;
    <<[[malloc()]] if Npadlong>>
    memset(v, 0, size);
    return v;
}
@
% memset 0 by default for kernel memory! used in a few places.


%\subsection{[[free()]]}

% note that don't need to precise the size here! because the size is stored
% in section before the returned pointer in malloc
<<function [[free]]>>=
void
free(kern_vp v)
{
    if(v != nil)
        poolfree(mainmem, (ulong*)v-Npadlong);
}
@
% not that we do not panic when it's == nil, because at many places
% we free(x); and then do x = nil; to avoid double free and because
% we are not sure free will be called again on x (for instance in sysexec()
% we have a waserror finally handler that free even though if free and
% didn't pop the error yet.

% pointer arithmetic here with pointers, so equivalent of 
% Npadlong * sizeof(ulong)

\subsection{Sleeping [[smalloc()]]}

%yoann: Why allows that? useful feature? Complexify the code?
%claude:
[[smalloc()]] (``sleeping malloc'') is a variant of
[[malloc()]] that {never fails}: if the pool is full, instead
of returning [[nil]], it sleeps for 100~ms and retries.
This is useful for code paths where an allocation failure
would be hard to recover from---for instance, when creating
kernel data structures during a syscall where the caller
expects success. The trade-off is that [[smalloc()]] cannot
be called from interrupt context (sleeping in an interrupt
handler would deadlock the system).

% sleep malloc, probably can't be called from interrupt code!
% also memset to 0! so should be called smallocz no?
<<function [[smalloc]]>>=
// non failing malloc! will repeat until it can
kern_vp
smalloc(ulong size)
{
    kern_vp v;

    for(;;) {
        v = poolalloc(mainmem, size + Npadlong*sizeof(ulong));
        if(v != nil)
            break;
        // else
        tsleep(&up->sleepr, returnfalse, 0, 100);
    }
    <<[[smalloc()]] if Npadlong>>
    memset(v, 0, size); // clear
    return v;
}
@
%ocaml: use closures, no need returnfalse hack

