\section{User [[malloc()]]}
%actually brk

% from OS point of view the user malloc granularity is
% done via brk at a page level. malloc is actually
% done in libc on top of brk (cf insa and aubourg :) )
%claude:
User-space [[malloc()]] is entirely in the C library (in
[[lib_core/libc/port/malloc.c]]). It uses the same [[Pool]]
allocator but backed by [[brk()]] instead of [[xalloc()]].
The kernel only sees page-granularity requests via [[brk()]];
the library subdivides those pages for the user.

% in lib_core/libc/port/malloc.c 

%Pool *mainmem = &sbrkmem;
%Pool *imagmem = &sbrkmem;

% note also here that it always grow! brk always bigger.




\section{[[Page]] and [[palloc]]}

% already kindof virtual memory! but generic one.
% virtual because we have this indirection notion! of va vs pa. and segment
% with pagedir and pagetab. but more on this later in virtual memory chapter.
% cf famous quote on indirection

% Page will be building blocks for memory for user. We'll see later that
% they have a huge number of use.
%claude:
The previous allocators ([[xalloc]], [[Pool]], [[malloc]])
manage kernel memory. User memory is managed differently:
the unit of allocation is a 4~KiB {page}, and the kernel
tracks every physical page with a [[Page]] metadata
structure. The [[Palloc]] structure maintains a free list
of all available pages. When a user calls [[brk()]] or
triggers a page fault, the kernel takes a page from
[[palloc]] and maps it into the process's address space.
%claude:
Here is the relationship between the allocators:
\begin{verbatim}
  Physical memory (one Confmem bank):

       +--------------------------------------------+
       | user pages (managed by palloc)             |
       |  each page has a Page struct in palloc.pages|
       +--------------------------------------------+
       | kernel malloc pool (Pool/mainmem)          |
       +--------------------------------------------+
       | Page[] array (xalloc'ed)                   |
       +--------------------------------------------+
       | Proc[] array (xalloc'ed)                   |
       +--------------------------------------------+  <-- end (linker symbol)
       | kernel bss                                 |
       +--------------------------------------------+  <-- edata
       | kernel data:                               |
       |   xlists (Xalloc + Hole[128])  \           |
       |   pmainmem, pimagmem (Pool)     > layer 0  |
       |   conf, devtab, soc, etc.      /           |
       +--------------------------------------------+
       | kernel text                                |
  0x8000 +------------------------------------------+
       | L1/L2 tables, Cpu struct                   |
  0x0  +--------------------------------------------+
\end{verbatim}
%yoann: mention xlists, pmainmem globals in data section to help bootstrap especially xlist 128 holes
%claude:
The kernel data section (between [[edata]] and the text)
contains the statically allocated globals that bootstrap
the memory system: [[xlists]] with its 128-entry [[Hole]]
array, the [[pmainmem]] and [[pimagmem]] pool structures,
[[conf]], [[devtab]], etc. These are layer~0---they exist
before any dynamic allocator runs. The [[end]] symbol marks
where dynamic memory begins; [[xalloc]] starts carving from
there.

\subsection{[[Page]]}

%claude:
A [[Page]] is the metadata for one 4~KiB physical page.
The kernel allocates one [[Page]] for every physical page
available for user processes---this is a large array
([[palloc.pages]]), xalloc'ed during initialization. The
key fields are [[pa]] (the physical address of the page,
set once and never changed) and [[ref]] (the reference
count, because pages can be shared between processes via
copy-on-write):

<<struct [[Page]]>>=
// Page metadata. We will allocate as many Page as to cover all physical memory
// available for the user. xalloc'ed in Palloc.pages
struct Page
{
    phys_addr pa;     /* Physical address in memory */
    user_addr va;     /* Virtual address for user */

    // Why not Ref? to save space (same reason for using 'char' below)
    // but that means needs to use Lock below to access this non-atomic ref.
    ushort  ref;      /* Reference count */ // Pages are shared!

    // bitset<enum<Modref>>
    char  modref;     /* Simulated modify/reference bits */

    <<[[Page]] other fields>>

    // extra
    Lock;
    <<[[Page]] extra fields>>
};
@
