%yoann: explain use of those bits
%claude:
The constants below are {software} modified/referenced bits (the ARM MMU
does not provide hardware dirty bits like x86 does).
[[PG_REF]] is set the first time a page is accessed (in
[<fixfault()>]); [[PG_MOD]] is set when a page is
written.\footnote{How can the kernel track user-space
memory accesses? By initially mapping pages as invalid
(or read-only for writes). When the user program touches
the page, the MMU generates a page fault, giving the
kernel a chance to set [[PG_REF]] or [[PG_MOD]] before
mapping the page with the actual permissions.}

<<enum [[modref]]>>=
enum Modref 
{
    PG_NOTHING = 0x00, // nothing

    PG_MOD    = 0x01,   /* software modified bit */
    PG_REF    = 0x02,   /* software referenced bit */
};
@
%c: nice bitset (more efficient than ocaml record)
% TODO LP split, put just PG_NOTHING for now?

The swapper uses these bits to decide what to do when
reclaiming a page: if [[PG_MOD]] is not set, the page is
clean and can be discarded (or retrieved from the image
cache) without writing it to swap. If [[PG_REF]] is set,
the page was recently used and should be kept longer.

