\section{[[Segment]] and [[Pagetable]]}

%claude:
A [[Segment]] represents a contiguous region of a process's
virtual address space (text, data, bss, or stack). Each
segment contains a two-level {page directory} that maps
virtual addresses within the segment to physical [[Page]]s.
These are the kernel's {segment tables}---separate from
the ARM's {hardware} L1/L2 page tables, although the two
must be kept in sync.

%claude:
Why maintain segment tables when the hardware already
has page tables? Because the hardware tables are
architecture-specific (different format on ARM vs.\ x86),
while [[Segment]]/[[Pagetable]] are portable. They also
store information the hardware does not: reference counts
(for shared pages and copy-on-write), swap addresses (for
paged-out pages), and segment types (text vs.\ data vs.\
stack). The cost is extra memory, but the segment tables
are sparse (only populated on demand via page faults), so
the overhead is proportional to the pages actually used,
not to the full address space.


<<enum [[segtype]]>>=
/* Segment types */
enum Segtype
{
    SG_TEXT   = 00,
    SG_DATA   = 01,
    SG_BSS    = 02,
    SG_STACK  = 03,
    <<[[Segtype]] other cases>>
    SG_TYPE   = 07,   /* Mask type of segment */

    <<[[Segtype]] other flags>>
};
@
