\subsection{No more processes}

% useful feature?
%claude:
If the free list is empty when [<newproc()>] is called,
the kernel sleeps and retries, hoping another process
will exit soon. If the situation persists, it panics
and reboots.

<<[[newproc()]] other locals>>=
char msg[64];
@

<<[[newproc()]] set [[p]] to [[procalloc.free]] and wait if nil>>=
while((p = procalloc.free) == nil) {
    unlock(&procalloc);

    snprint(msg, sizeof msg, "no procs; %s forking", up?up->text:"kernel");
    /*
     * the situation is unlikely to heal itself.
     * dump the proc table and restart by default.
     * *noprocspersist in plan9.ini will yield the old
     * behaviour of trying forever.
     */
    if(getconf("*noprocspersist") == nil)
        noprocpanic(msg);
    resrcwait(msg);
    lock(&procalloc);
}
@

%yoann: explain resrcwait call here (defined below)
%claude:
[[resrcwait()]] (defined later in this chapter) prints
a warning and sleeps for 300~ms before retrying---it is
the kernel's standard ``resource temporarily unavailable''
back-off.

<<function [[noprocpanic]]>>=
void
noprocpanic(char *msg)
{
    /*
     * setting exiting will make hzclock() on each processor call exit(0).
     * clearing our bit in cpus avoids calling exit(0) from hzclock()
     * on this processor.
     */
    lock(&active);
    active.cpus &= ~(1<<cpu->cpuno);
    active.exiting = true;
    unlock(&active);

    procdump();
    arch_delay(1000);
    panic(msg);
}
@ 
% seems a bit rude to reboot because can't allocate newproc, why not just return
% error?

<<function [[resrcwait]]>>=
void
resrcwait(char *reason)
{
    ulong now;
    char *p;
    static ulong lastwhine;

    if(up == nil)
        panic("resrcwait");

    p = up->psstate;
    if(reason) {
        up->psstate = reason;
        now = seconds();
        /* don't tie up the console with complaints */
        if(now - lastwhine > Whinesecs) {
            lastwhine = now;
            print("%s\n", reason);
        }
    }
    tsleep(&up->sleepr, returnfalse, 0, 300);
    up->psstate = p;
}
@ 

<<constant [[Whinesecs]]>>=
Whinesecs = 10,     /* frequency of out-of-resources printing */
@


\section{The user}

%claude: %unix:
In \unix, the process owner is a numeric uid. In \plan, it
is a string ([[Proc.user]]): typically ``eve'' for the
system owner. There is no [[/etc/passwd]]---authentication
is handled per-connection by the file server protocol (9P).
In \plan, file permissions also use strings: [[struct Dir]]
has [[uid]] and [[gid]] fields that are character strings,
not numeric ids. The file server itself decides whether
to grant access by comparing the connection's authenticated
user name against these strings---there is no kernel-level
uid/gid translation.


<<[[Proc]] state fields>>=
// e.g.. "eve" (no uid/gid in plan9, because of its distributed nature?)
