\subsection{[[arch_forkchild()]] (ARM)}

%sched structure explained later in Context switch section.
%The stack will contain value of all user registers.
%claude:
[<arch_forkchild()>] is the key architecture-specific piece
of fork: it sets up the child's kernel stack so that when
the scheduler picks the child, it will ``return'' from the
syscall with [[R0]]=0 (the child's return value). It copies
the parent's saved user registers ([[Ureg]]) onto the child's
kernel stack and sets [[p->sched]] (the [[Label]]) to
point to [<arch__forkret>], which restores these registers
and returns to user mode.

% pass the up->dbgreg of parent process!

% sysrfork -> <>
<<function [[arch_forkchild]](arm)>>=
/* 
 *  Craft a return frame which will cause the child to pop out of
 *  the scheduler in user mode with the return register zero.  Set
 *  pc to point to a l.s return function.
 */
void
arch_forkchild(Proc *p, Ureg *ureg)
{
    Ureg *cureg;

    p->sched.sp = (ulong)p->kstack + KSTACK - sizeof(Ureg);
    p->sched.pc = (ulong)arch__forkret;

    cureg = (Ureg*)(p->sched.sp);
    memmove(cureg, ureg, sizeof(Ureg));
    /* syscall returns 0 for child */ // adjust
    cureg->r0 = 0;

    /* Things from bottom of syscall which were never executed */
    p->psstate = nil;
    p->insyscall = false;

    <<[[arch_forkchild()]] floating point(arm)>>
}
@
%x86: does not use R0 to return from syscall so need extra space in kstack
%//print("%lud setting up for forking child %lud\n", up->pid, p->pid);

<<[[Proc]] state fields>>=
bool insyscall; // true when process inside a syscall
@


% sched? -> <> (as p->sched.pc <- arch_forkchild)
<<function [[arch__forkret]](arm)>>=
/*
 *  here to jump to a newly forked process
 */
TEXT arch__forkret(SB), 1, $-4
    ADD $(4*15), R13        /* make r13 point to ureg->type */
    MOVW    8(R13), R14     /* restore link */
    MOVW    4(R13), R0      /* restore SPSR */
    MOVW    R0, SPSR        /* ... */
    MOVM.DB.S (R13), [R0-R14]   /* restore registers */
    ADD $8, R13         /* pop past ureg->{type+psr} */
    RFE             /* MOVM.IA.S.W (R13), [R15] */
@
%$
% .S ?? for user banked register ?
%claude:
Here is the memory layout after [<arch_forkchild()>] has
set up the child, showing how the parent and child relate:
\begin{verbatim}
  PARENT (up)                         CHILD (p)

  user stack:                         user stack:
  (shared or COW                      (shared or COW
   copy of parent)                     copy of parent)
  +-----------+                       +-----------+
  |  user     |                       |  user     |
  |  code/data|                       |  code/data|
  +-----------+                       +-----------+

  kernel stack (up->kstack, 8 KiB):   kernel stack (p->kstack, 8 KiB):
  +-----------+ <-- kstack+KSTACK     +-----------+ <-- kstack+KSTACK
  |  Ureg     |  (saved by _vsvc      |  Ureg     |  (copied from parent,
  |  r0..r14  |   on syscall entry)   |  r0=0!    |   r0 set to 0)
  |  type,psr |                       |  type,psr |
  |  pc       |  (return to user)     |  pc       |  (same user PC)
  +-----------+ <-- up->dbgreg        +-----------+ <-- p->sched.sp
  |           |                       |           |
  |  (used by |                       |  (empty)  |
  |  syscall  |                       |           |
  |  handler) |                       |           |
  +-----------+ <-- kstack            +-----------+ <-- kstack

  up->sched.pc = (in sched code)      p->sched.pc = arch__forkret
  up->sched.sp = (in sched code)      p->sched.sp = &Ureg on kstack

  When scheduler picks child:
    1. gotolabel(p->sched) -> jump to arch__forkret
    2. arch__forkret restores Ureg from kstack
    3. RFE -> user mode, R0=0 (child sees rfork()=0)
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{File descriptors: [[RFFDG]], [[RFCFDG]]}

%claude:
The next subsections handle resource sharing. They all
follow the same three-way pattern: if the ``G'' flag is
set, {copy} the parent's resource; if the ``CG'' flag is
set, create a {clean} (empty) one; if neither, {share}
the parent's (just increment the reference count). The
two flags are mutually exclusive.
<<[[sysrfork()]] sanity check flags, clean or copy>>=
if((flag & (RFFDG|RFCFDG)) == (RFFDG|RFCFDG))
    error(Ebadarg);
@
%ocaml: use proper type so no need check those cases? make it a bool?

<<[[sysrfork()]] copy, clean, or share file descriptors>>=
if(flag & (RFFDG|RFCFDG)) {
    if(flag & RFFDG)
        p->fgrp = dupfgrp(up->fgrp);
    else
        p->fgrp = dupfgrp(nil);
}
else {
    p->fgrp = up->fgrp;
    incref(p->fgrp);
}
@

\subsection{Namespace: [[RFNAMEG]], [[RFCNAMEG]]}

%claude:
Same pattern as file descriptors, but for the process's
view of the file system (the {namespace}). [[RFNOMNT]] is
an additional flag that, when set, prevents the child from
mounting anything---useful for sandboxing untrusted programs.
<<[[sysrfork()]] sanity check flags, clean or copy>>=
if((flag & (RFNAMEG|RFCNAMEG)) == (RFNAMEG|RFCNAMEG))
    error(Ebadarg);
@
%ocaml: use proper type so no need check those cases? make it a bool?

<<[[sysrfork()]] copy, clean, or share namespace>>=
if(flag & (RFNAMEG|RFCNAMEG)) {
    p->pgrp = newpgrp();
    if(flag & RFNAMEG)
        pgrpcpy(p->pgrp, up->pgrp);
    <<[[sysrfork()]] inherit noattach, RFPROC==1 case>>
}
else {
    p->pgrp = up->pgrp;
    incref(p->pgrp);
}
<<[[sysrfork()]] set noattach to true when RFNOMNT, RFPROC==1 case>>
@

\subsection{Environment variables: [[RFENVG]], [[RFCENVG]]}
%mv later?

<<[[sysrfork()]] sanity check flags, clean or copy>>=
if((flag & (RFENVG|RFCENVG)) == (RFENVG|RFCENVG))
    error(Ebadarg);
@
%ocaml: use proper type so no need check those cases? make it a bool?

<<[[sysrfork()]] copy, clean, or share environment>>=
if(flag & (RFENVG|RFCENVG)) {
    p->egrp = smalloc(sizeof(Egrp)); // newegrp
    p->egrp->ref = 1;
    if(flag & RFENVG)
        envcpy(p->egrp, up->egrp);
}
else {
    p->egrp = up->egrp;
    incref(p->egrp);
}
@

\subsection{Rendezvous group: [[RFREND]]}
% mv later?

%yoann: quickly explain what Rendezvous are for and reference chapter~X, and explain why need share (or not) such a resource
%claude:
Rendezvous is \plan's lightweight IPC mechanism: two
processes that share a rendezvous group can synchronize
by calling [[rendezvous()]] with a matching tag (see
Chapter~\ref{chap:ipc}). [[RFREND]] gives the child
a fresh group, isolating it from the parent's rendezvous
partners.

<<[[sysrfork()]] new or share rendezvous group>>=
if(flag & RFREND)
    p->rgrp = newrgrp();
else {
    incref(up->rgrp);
    p->rgrp = up->rgrp;
}
@

\subsection{Note group: [[RFNOTEG]]}
%mv later?

%yoann: quickly explain what nodeid are for and reference chapter~X and explain why need to share (or not) such a resource
%claude:
Notes are \plan's equivalent of \unix\ signals (see
Chapter~\ref{chap:interrupts}). Processes that share a
note group can send notes to each other; [[RFNOTEG]]
gives the child its own group, so notes sent to the
parent's group will not reach the child.

<<[[sysrfork()]] share or not note group>>=
if((flag&RFNOTEG) == 0)
    p->noteid = up->noteid; // rectify what was done in newproc
@

\subsection{Process sharing settings (no [[RFPROC]])}

%claude:
When [[RFPROC]] is {not} set, [[rfork]] does not create a
child. Instead, it modifies the current process's own
resources---for example, a program can call
[[rfork(RFNAMEG)]] to get its own private copy of the
namespace before mounting something, without forking a
new process. The code below mirrors the RFPROC branch
but operates on [[up]] instead of a new [[p]], and must
carefully close the old resource groups after switching.
