\section{[[sysexec()]]}

%http://dbp-consulting.com/tutorials/debugging/linuxProgramStartup.html
%claude:
[<sysexec()>] is the second half of the fork/exec pair.
It replaces the current process's memory image with a new
program loaded from a file. This is a complex operation
because the old program's memory must be freed while
building the new one---and if anything goes wrong (bad
binary, out of memory), the process must survive with its
old image intact.
%claude:
The logical chain is:
file name $\to$ open channel $\to$ read [[a.out]] header
$\to$ create text/data/bss segments $\to$ count arguments
$\to$ build arguments on temporary stack $\to$ free old
segments $\to$ relocate stack to final position $\to$ set
PC and SP $\to$ return to user mode in new program.
Script files starting with [[#!]] are handled by
re-opening with the interpreter.
%http://lwn.net/Articles/630727/

<<constant [[AOUT_MAGIC]](arm)>>=
/*
 *  parameters for sysproc.c
 */
// E_MAGIC is defined in include/a.out.h
#define AOUT_MAGIC  (E_MAGIC)
@

% struct Exec = binary header in include/a.out.h

%yoann: explain that the chain described above lead to a corresponding series of locals with the corresponding type
%claude:
The logical chain---filename string $\to$ channel $\to$
binary header $\to$ segments---is reflected in the
local variables:

% logical chain: string -> tc -> exec -> segment
