% why for loop above? because of #! code?

%yoann: say long function, and explain important bits (e.g., namec() call hidden in a chunk actually explained later)
%claude:
[[sysexec()]] is one of the longest functions in the
kernel. The key steps are: open the binary via
[<namec()>] (the name-to-channel resolution function,
covered in Chapter~\ref{chap:namespaces}), read its
header to get the text/data/bss sizes, tear down the
old segments, create new ones, and build the stack.

%yoann: explain the binary layout, maybe ASCII diagram? and remember disk offset and virtual offsets are different
%claude:
The binary file (a.out format) starts with an [[Exec]]
header followed by the text and data sections. On disk
the layout is contiguous, but in memory the segments are
placed at different virtual addresses:
\begin{verbatim}
  On disk (a.out file):       In memory (virtual):

  +-------------------+
  | Exec header       |       USTKTOP  +-------------+
  +-------------------+                | stack        |
  | text (code)       |           b    +-------------+
  +-------------------+                | bss (zero)   |
  | data              |           d    +-------------+
  +-------------------+                | data         |
                                  t    +-------------+
                                       | text (code)  |
                              UTZERO   +-------------+
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
The constants [[t]], [[d]], [[b]] below are the virtual
addresses of the boundaries between segments, all
page-aligned:

<<[[sysexec()]] compute end of text, data, bss segments>>=
t = UTROUND(UTZERO+sizeof(Exec)+text);
// data is put at page boundary after text
d = ROUND(t + data, BY2PG);
// note that this is not d + bss here, but t + data + bss!
b = ROUND(t + data + bss, BY2PG);

if(t >= KZERO || d >= KZERO || b >= KZERO)
    error(Ebadexec);
@
% b = ROUND(t + data + bss, BY2PG);
% This is special! it assumes BSS follows directly data segment
% in memory! so it's not ROUND(d + bss, BY2PG)!



% could mv in lib.h? 
<<function [[l2be]]>>=
ulong
l2be(long l)
{
    byte *cp;

    cp = (byte*)&l;
    return (cp[0]<<24) | (cp[1]<<16) | (cp[2]<<8) | cp[3];
}
@ 
% >> >> >>
% a.out format use big-endian integers so l2be long from big-endian


<<macro [[UTROUND]](arm)>>=
#define UTROUND(t)  ROUNDUP((t), BY2PG)
@
%x86: same
\t just use ROUND(...BY2PG)? why special macro? some arch constraint?

% free old segments because they will be overwritten by new segments.

