\subsection{Text segment}

%claude:
The text (code) segment is {shared} and {demand-loaded}:
the pages are not read from disk now but will be faulted
in on first access. If another process is already running
the same executable, the text pages are shared via a
cache image.
<<[[sysexec()]] set Text segment>>=
/* Text.  Shared. Attaches to cache image if possible */
<<[[sysexec()]] get text segment ts via demand loading on tc>>
up->seg[TSEG] = ts;
@
% will see demand loading later

\subsection{Data segment}

<<[[sysexec()]] set Data segment>>=
/* Data. Shared. */
s = newseg(SG_DATA, t, (d-t)>>PGSHIFT);
up->seg[DSEG] = s;
<<[[sysexec()]] adjust data segment s for demand loading on tc>>
@
% same, will see demand loading later.


\subsection{Bss segment}

%claude:
The bss is the simplest: it starts where data ends, and
its pages are zero-filled on demand by the page fault
handler---no disk I/O needed.
<<[[sysexec()]] set Bss segment>>=
/* BSS. Zero fill on demand */
up->seg[BSEG] = newseg(SG_BSS, d, (b-d)>>PGSHIFT);
@
% easy one
% note that the BSS may actually overlap on Data segment.

% note that Bss segment under plan9 are filled with 0, but lazily
% in fixfault.
% VERY IMPORTANT! Some code relies on that under plan9 (ugly?)

\subsection{Stack segment}

%yoann: maybe explanation and ASCII diagram for stack layout and user stack vs kernel stack
%claude:
Each process has two stacks: a {user stack} (in the
[[SSEG]] segment, growing down from [[USTKTOP]]) and a
{kernel stack} (the per-process [[kstack]], used during
syscalls and interrupts). The exec code builds the new
user stack with the program's arguments:
\begin{verbatim}
  USTKTOP  +--------------------+
           | Tos                |  (time-of-stack info)
           +--------------------+
           | argv strings       |  "ls\0" "-l\0" ...
           +--------------------+
           | argv[n]=0          |  (nil terminator)
           | argv[1]            |  (pointer to "-l")
           | argv[0]            |  (pointer to "ls")
           +--------------------+
           | nargs              |  (argument count)
    SP --> +--------------------+
           |                    |
           | (free stack space) |
           |                    |
           +--------------------+
\end{verbatim}

\subsubsection{Arguments count}

<<[[Proc]] state fields>>=
char  *args;
int nargs;    /* number of bytes of args */
@
<<[[newproc()]] set fields of [[p]]>>=
kstrdup(&p->args, "");
p->nargs = 0;
@



<<[[sysexec()]] locals>>=
char **argp;
char *a, *args;
ulong nbytes;
@


% nargs declared in lock in skeleton
<<[[sysexec()]] build args count>>=
/*
 * Args: pass 1: count
 */
nargs = 0;
nbytes = 0;

<<[[sysexec()]] nbytes tos adjustments>>
<<[[sysexec()]] if indir arg adjustments>>

arch_validalign(arg[1], sizeof(char**));
argp = (char**)arg[1];
validaddr((ulong)argp, BY2WD, false);
while(*argp){
    a = *argp++;
    if(((ulong)argp&(BY2PG-1)) < BY2WD)
        validaddr((ulong)argp, BY2WD, false);
    validaddr((ulong)a, 1, false);
    nbytes += ((char*)vmemchr(a, 0, 0x7FFFFFFF) - a) + 1;
    nargs++;
}
ssize = BY2WD*(nargs+1) + ROUND(nbytes, BY2WD);
@


\subsubsection{Temporary stack segment}

\l why need add this stack segment in Proc.seg? because need to
\l  access and write into it and so generate real page fault
\l  that must be resolved?
%claude:
Building the new stack is the trickiest part of exec.
The kernel must write the argument strings and [[argv]]
pointers into the new program's stack, but it cannot
overwrite the current stack---the old program's syscall
frame is still there. So the kernel creates a {temporary}
stack segment at a different virtual address ([[TSTKTOP]]),
builds the arguments there, and only after the old
segments are freed does it relocate this segment to its
final position at [[USTKTOP]].

% Temporary STacK TOP
<<constant [[TSTKTOP]](arm)>>=
// end of new stack in sysexec
#define TSTKTOP     (USTKTOP-USTKSIZE)  /* sysexec temporary stack */
@
%x86: same


<<constant [[TSTKSIZ]](arm)>>=
#define TSTKSIZ     256 // pages in new stack; limits exec args
@
%x86: 100

%yoann: maybe ASCII diagram again of memory layout of those kernel stacks
%claude:
The kernel allocates a temporary stack segment at
[[TSTKTOP]] (well below [[USTKTOP]]) so the old and new
stacks coexist briefly:
\begin{verbatim}
  USTKTOP   +--------------------+
            | old stack (SSEG)   |  <- still in use by syscall
            +--------------------+
            |        ...         |
  TSTKTOP   +--------------------+
            | temp stack (ESEG)  |  <- new args built here
            +--------------------+
\end{verbatim}

<<[[sysexec()]] locals>>=
ulong spage;
@
<<[[sysexec()]] build temporary stack segment and qlock seglock>>=
/*
 * 8-byte align SP for those (e.g. sparc) that need it.
 * arch_execregs() will subtract another 4 bytes for argc.
 */
if((ssize+4) & 7)
    ssize += 4;
spage = (ssize+(BY2PG-1)) >> PGSHIFT;

/*
 * Build the stack segment, putting it in kernel virtual for the moment
 */
if(spage > TSTKSIZ)
    error(Enovmem);

qlock(&up->seglock);
if(waserror()){
    qunlock(&up->seglock);
    nexterror();
}
// why ESEG? and why not TSTKTOP?? ESEG because will free later
// the current SSEG. If we have an error in sysexec we don't want
// to have messed up with the current stack. TSTKTOP-USTKSIZE for
// the same reason, because we don't want overwrite old stack
// all of that will be relocated later.
up->seg[ESEG] = newseg(SG_STACK, TSTKTOP-USTKSIZE, USTKSIZE/BY2PG);
@


\subsubsection{Arguments}

%yoann: again ASCII diagram for that part
%claude:
The arguments are copied into the temporary stack in
two passes: first the string data, then the [[argv]]
pointer array pointing back into the strings.

<<[[sysexec()]] locals>>=
char **argv;
char *charp;
@

<<[[sysexec()]] build args>>=
/*
 * Args: pass 2: assemble; the pages will be faulted in
 */
<<[[sysexec()]] tos settings>>

argv = (char**)(TSTKTOP - ssize);
charp = (char*)(TSTKTOP - nbytes);
args = charp;
<<[[sysexec()]] if indir argp adjustments>>
else
    argp = (char**)arg[1];

for(i=0; i<nargs; i++){
    <<[[sysexec()]] if indir argp adjustments again>>
    *argv++ = charp + (USTKTOP-TSTKTOP);
    n = strlen(*argp) + 1;
    memmove(charp, *argp++, n);
    charp += n;
}
free(file0);
// file0 = nil? to avoid double free?

free(up->text);
up->text = elem;
elem = nil; /* so waserror() won't free elem */
USED(elem);

/* copy args; easiest from new process's stack */
n = charp - args;
if(n > 128) /* don't waste too much space on huge arg lists */
    n = 128;
a = up->args;
up->args = nil;
free(a);
up->args = smalloc(n);
memmove(up->args, args, n);

if(n>0 && up->args[n-1]!='\0'){
    /* make sure last arg is NUL-terminated */
    /* put NUL at UTF-8 character boundary */
    for(i=n-1; i>0; --i)
        if(fullrune(up->args+i, n-i))
            break;
    up->args[i] = 0;
    n = i+1;
}
up->nargs = n;
@

%yoann: smalloc!
%claude:
Note another use of [[smalloc()]] above for the argument
buffer---it sleeps if memory is unavailable.

\subsubsection{Relocate temporary stack segment}


<<[[sysexec()]] relocate temporary stack segment, unlock seglock>>=
/*
 * Move the stack
 */
s = up->seg[ESEG];
up->seg[ESEG] = nil;
up->seg[SSEG] = s;
qunlock(&up->seglock);

poperror(); /* seglock */
