%claude:
We now look at the parent's side of process termination
before seeing the child's ([[sysexits()]]). It is easier
to understand the exit code once you know what the parent
expects to receive.
%claude:
When a child exits, it leaves a {wait message} in the
parent's queue ([[Proc.waitq]]). There is no race: even
if the child exits before the parent calls [[await()]],
the message is preserved (up to 128 per parent). The
parent blocks on [[Proc.waitr]] until a message is
available, then returns it as a formatted string.

%claude:
There are no {zombie processes} in \plan. When a child
exits, it writes a {wait message} (containing its exit
string and resource usage) to the parent's queue and
immediately dies. The parent collects these messages via
[[await()]]. If the parent has already exited, the messages
are simply discarded. In \unix, a zombie is created when
a child exits but its parent has not yet called [[wait()]]
---the child's [[Proc]] entry lingers, holding a process
slot, until the parent collects the exit status. If the
parent never calls [[wait]], zombies accumulate. \plan
avoids this entirely: the exit status is copied into the
parent's wait queue (a bounded buffer, not a [[Proc]]
slot), and the child's [[Proc]] is freed immediately.

\subsection{Parent and children}

%claude:
Each process keeps a pointer to its parent and a count
of living children. But the [[parent]] pointer alone is
not safe: if the parent exits, its [[Proc]] slot is reused
for a new process. The [[parentpid]] field solves this---before
accessing [[parent]], the child checks that
[[parent->pid == parentpid]]. If not, the parent has died
and been replaced, so the child acts as an orphan.
Orphans and zombies are different concepts: a {zombie}
is a dead child whose exit status has not been collected;
an {orphan} is a living child whose parent has died.
\plan has orphans but no zombies.

