\subsection{[[pexit()]]}

% != Dead. Why the logic of killing process is split in pexit()
% here and schedinit()? Because to kill a process we need to free
% everything, but right now we are executing code using the per-process
% kernel stack itself, so by going to schedinit() we switch to
% the main kernel stack which is exterior to the process.
% Note that we never free the per-process kernel stack so we could
% in theory get rid of schedinit, but maybe it's more elegant that way.
% Also in schedinit we will call arch_mmurelease so sounds good
% to do it from another context?
%claude:
[[pexit()]] is the real termination function, and its
design is split into two phases for a subtle reason.
Phase~1 runs on the dying process's own kernel stack:
it frees resources (file descriptors, namespace, segments),
builds the wait message for the parent, and wakes the
parent up. Phase~2 runs on the {CPU's main stack} (inside
[<schedinit()>]): it releases the MMU state and returns
the [[Proc]] to the free pool. The split is necessary
because the process cannot free its own kernel stack while
still using it---it must switch to another stack first.
The process's state goes through [[Moribund]] (between
the two phases) and finally [[Dead]].

%yoann: maybe ASCII diagram with those Proc stack, CPU stack (addr = ? CPUADDR+stack+STACKSIZE?)
%claude:
The two-phase design is necessary because phase~1 runs
on the process's own kernel stack ([[Proc.kstack]]),
which cannot be freed while it is in use. Phase~2 runs
on the CPU's boot stack (inside the [[Cpu]] structure
at [[CPUADDR]]):
\begin{verbatim}
  Phase 1 (Proc.kstack):       Phase 2 (Cpu.stack):

  kstack+KSTACK                CPUADDR+CPUSIZE
      +---------------+            +---------------+
      | pexit() frame |            | schedinit()   |
      | free fds,     |            | frees kstack  |
      | segments,     |            | sets Dead      |
      | namespace...  |            | recycles Proc  |
      +---------------+            +---------------+
  kstack                       CPUADDR
\end{verbatim}

% rename freemem to addbroken? hmmm no
% sysexits | linkproc | procctl | attachimage <>
<<function [[pexit]]>>=
void
proc_pexit(char *exitstr, bool freemem)
{
    Proc *p; // parent
    <<[[pexit()]] other locals>>

    // free 1
    <<[[pexit()]] at the start, free resources>>
    <<[[pexit()]] hook proctrace>>
    // free 2
    <<[[pexit()]] nil out resources under lock and free them>>

    <<[[pexit()]] if a kernel process, do nothing about parent and child>>
    else {
        /*
         * if not a kernel process and have a parent,
         * do some housekeeping.
         */
