\subsection{No waiting for child: [[RFNOWAIT]]}

% now that have seen sysawait and sysexits, can understand
% code of special sysrfork option RFNOWAIT
%linux: nohup?

% code subtle below.
%claude:
Now that we have seen [[sysawait()]] and [[pexit()]], we
can understand the [[RFNOWAIT]] flag in [[sysrfork()]].
When set, [[parentpid]] is cleared to~0, so when the
child exits, [<pexit()>] will see that the parent's pid
does not match [[parentpid]] and skip the wait message
entirely. The child
becomes an orphan: no one will collect its exit status.
If [[RFNOWAIT]] is not set, the parent's [[nchild]] count
is incremented normally. This is used by programs that
spawn helper processes they never need to wait for---for
example, [[rio]] (the window system) and [[lib9p]] use
[[RFNOWAIT]] when forking worker processes.

<<[[sysrfork()]] wait or not for child>>=
if(flag&RFNOWAIT)
    p->parentpid = 0;
else {
    lock(&up->exl);
    up->nchild++;
    unlock(&up->exl);
}
@
% so we do not reset parent here? So a process always a Proc.parent
% but not always a parentpid?



\section{Kernel processes}

% Examples of kernel processes?
%  - page collector (pager),
%  - closing channel collector (clunker?)
%  - dead process collector?? (hmm, maybe done by sched() instead)
%claude:
Not all processes run user programs. The kernel creates
a few background {kernel processes} for housekeeping
tasks: the pager (reclaims pages when memory is low),
the alarm handler, etc. A kernel process has no user
segments---it runs entirely in kernel memory. It is
created by [<kproc()>], which is simpler than [<sysrfork()>]:
it calls [<newproc()>], sets [[kp=true]], stores the
entry function in [[kpfun]], and makes the process
runnable. When scheduled, the process enters [<linkproc()>],
which enables interrupts and calls the function.

