\section{Process control [[/proc/#/ctl]]}

% see /proc, /proc/x/ctl, procctl()
% see section on Debugging where explain procctl
% see also section on notifications
%claude:
Processes can be controlled from outside by writing
commands to [[/proc/#/ctl]]. For example,
[[echo kill > /proc/42/ctl]] sends a ``sys: killed'' note
to process~42. This is how the shell implements job control
and how administrators kill runaway processes.
The full [[/proc]] file system is covered in
Chapter~\ref{chap:devices}. The shell [[rc]] itself does
not use [[/proc/\emph{pid}/ctl]] directly---it sends
notes via [[postnote()]]---but tools like [[kill(1)]]
and [[slay(1)]] do write to [[ctl]].

