%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Interrupts}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:interrupts}
%less: Exceptions?
%less: (ARM) in title because almost everything is arch-specific?

%claude:
This chapter shows how the kernel handles events that
interrupt normal execution: system calls (which we already
traced in the Overview), hardware interrupts (timer, keyboard,
disk), and faults (page faults, undefined instructions).
Most of the code is architecture-specific, but the overall
structure is the same on any architecture: save registers,
dispatch to a handler, restore registers, return.

\section{Overview}

% fault vs trap vs irq vs interrupt vs exception vs syscall
% hardware interrupt vs software interrupt
%claude:
There are two main paths through this chapter. The
{syscall path} (a software interrupt via [[SWI]]) goes
through [[_vsvc]] $\to$ [[arch__syscall]] $\to$
[[systab[n]]] $\to$ return. The {exception/IRQ path}
goes through [[_vxxx]] $\to$ [[_vswitch]] $\to$
[[arch__trap]], which dispatches based on the exception
type: page faults, undefined instructions, or hardware
IRQs.
\begin{verbatim}
  SWI (syscall):          Other exceptions:

  user code               user code (or kernel)
      |                       |
      v                       v
  vectors[2]              vectors[x]
      |                       |
      v                       v
  _vsvc                   _vund / _vdabt / _virq / ...
      |                       |
      | (save Ureg,           | (save R0-R4, set type)
      |  set R10/R9)          v
      v                   _vswitch
  arch__syscall               | (switch to SVC mode,
      |                       |  save full Ureg,
      v                       |  set R10/R9)
  systab[n]()                 v
      |                   arch__trap
      v                       |
  return to user          dispatch by type:
                            - PsrMabt -> faultarm (page fault)
                            - PsrMund -> postnote (signal)
                            - PsrMirq -> irq()   (devices)
\end{verbatim}

% exception|interrupt|trap(|signal) > irq | syscall | fault

% irq is a request from "outside", generating an (hardware) interrupt
% fault is also generating an interrupt, but more from "inside"
% fault used for many things, virtual memory, swap, ... even debugging I think

%"Exceptions occur whenever the normal flow of a program has to be 
% halted temporarily." from ARM ref manual
% (hence use of RFE for Return From Exception)

% Unix signal are a transposition of the interrupt model to userspace program.
% Can also register for different signals/exceptions.

%less: would be nice to have a /sys/interrupts like Linux
% has a /proc/interrupts

% Saw INTREGS in Section~\ref{X}.

% Control flow for hardware interrupt:
% interrupt -> vector[x] -> vtable[x] -> _vxxx -> _vswitch -> trap -> RFE?

% Control flow for syscall (software interrupt):
% SWI -> vector[2] -> vtable[2] -> _vsvc -> syscall -> RFE


