\section{Exception [[vectors]]  (ARM)}

% Exception vector is at address 0 on ARM! (Physical and later Virtual).
% But not convenient so HVECTORS.
% Saw HVECTORS before.

% The vector below will be copied in trapinit()
% and processor will be made error that exceptions should
% be handled by the entries in this vector.

% matches closely the processor mode. Each fault has almost a processor mode.
%claude:
The ARM has 8 exception entries at fixed offsets (0x00 for
reset, 0x04 for undefined, 0x08 for SWI, etc.). Each
entry is a single instruction that loads the PC from a
nearby table ([[vtable]]). The [[vectors]] and [[vtable]]
code below is copied to [[HVECTORS]] ([[0xFFFF0000]]) by
[<arch__trapinit()>] during boot.
%claude:
The indirection through [[vtable]] is necessary because
the ARM vectors are only one instruction wide---not enough
room for a full address. Each vector entry does
[[MOVW 0x18(R15), R15]], which loads the PC from 8
instructions ahead (where [[vtable]] starts), effectively
jumping to the handler:
%yoann1: maybe reference Linker book on ARM and machine code generation so see that MOVW smallint(R15), R15 can fit in 4 bytes in one instr, but MOVW $_vsvc(SB), R15 (or MOVW _vsvc(SB), R15?) would take 8 bytes or more

<<global [[vectors]](arm)>>=
/*
 *  exception vectors, copied by trapinit() to somewhere useful
 */
TEXT vectors(SB), 1, $-4
    MOVW    0x18(R15), R15      /* reset */
    MOVW    0x18(R15), R15      /* undefined instr. */
    MOVW    0x18(R15), R15      /* SWI & SMC */
    MOVW    0x18(R15), R15      /* prefetch abort */
    MOVW    0x18(R15), R15      /* data abort */
    MOVW    0x18(R15), R15      /* reserved */
    MOVW    0x18(R15), R15      /* IRQ */
    MOVW    0x18(R15), R15      /* FIQ */
@
%$
% it's written as a function, but really it's a global
%x86: IDTADDR
\l SMC??
