%claude:
Before dispatching, [[arch__syscall()]] checks that the
[[SWI]] came from user mode---a syscall from kernel mode
would be a bug. [[arch_userureg()]] tests whether the
saved processor mode in [[ureg->psr]] is [[PsrMusr]]:

<<[[syscall()]] sanity check call from userspace(arm)>>=
if(!arch_userureg(ureg))
    panic("syscall: from kernel: pc %#lux r14 %#lux psr %#lux",
        ureg->pc, ureg->r14, ureg->psr);
@

<<function [[arch_userureg]](arm)>>=
bool
arch_userureg(Ureg* ureg)
{
    return (ureg->psr & PsrMask) == PsrMusr;
}
@

\section{Exception handlers}

%claude:
All exceptions other than SWI (which has its own fast
path via [[_vsvc]]) go through the same two-step
mechanism: a short handler [[_vxxx]] that saves a few
registers and records the exception type, then a common
[[_vswitch]] routine that switches to SVC mode and
builds the full [[Ureg]].

\subsection{[[_vxxx()]] (ARM)}

% save R0-R4 because will use those registers later
%claude:
Each exception type has a tiny entry point that saves
[[R0]]--[[R4]] to make working room, loads the exception
type constant into [[R0]], and falls through to
[[_vswitch]]. Note that each exception mode has its own
banked R13, so the [[MOVM.IA]] writes to that mode's
stack---a small scratch area set up during boot, not the
kernel's SVC stack:

<<function [[_vund]](arm)>>=
TEXT _vund(SB), 1, $-4          /* undefined */
    MOVM.IA [R0-R4], (R13)      /* free some working space */
    MOVW    $PsrMund, R0
    B   _vswitch
@
<<function [[_vpabt]](arm)>>=
TEXT _vpabt(SB), 1, $-4         /* prefetch abort */
    MOVM.IA [R0-R4], (R13)      /* free some working space */
    MOVW    $PsrMabt, R0        /* r0 = type */
    B   _vswitch
@
<<function [[_vdabt]](arm)>>=
TEXT _vdabt(SB), 1, $-4         /* data abort */
    MOVM.IA [R0-R4], (R13)      /* free some working space */
    MOVW    $(PsrMabt+1), R0    /* r0 = type */
    B   _vswitch
@
<<function [[_virq]](arm)>>=
TEXT _virq(SB), 1, $-4          /* IRQ */
    MOVM.IA [R0-R4], (R13)      /* free some working space */
    MOVW    $PsrMirq, R0        /* r0 = type */
    B   _vswitch
@

\subsection{[[_vswitch()]] (ARM)}

% need save SPSR/R14/R13 because banked registers that will
% change when switch to SVC mode.
%claude:
[[_vswitch]] is the heart of the exception mechanism. It
must switch from the exception's processor mode (IRQ, ABT,
UND) to SVC mode, because the kernel runs in SVC mode and
needs access to the SVC-mode stack. But switching modes
changes the banked R13 and R14, so [[_vswitch]] saves
them first (SPSR, R14, R13) into general registers
([[R1]]--[[R3]]), then switches:
\begin{verbatim}
  In exception mode (e.g., IRQ):
    R0 = exception type (set by _vxxx)
    R1 = SPSR (saved user/kernel CPSR)
    R2 = R14  (interrupted PC)
    R3 = R13  (pointer to saved R0-R4)
        |
        v  switch CPSR to SVC mode
        |
  Now in SVC mode:
    R13 = SVC stack (kernel stack)
    Build Ureg on this stack, then call arch__trap()
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
It then checks whether the exception interrupted user
code or kernel code ([[AND.S \$0xf, R1]])---the handling
differs because a kernel-mode exception must preserve the
kernel's R10 (CPU) and R9 (up), and may have been
nested (an interrupt inside an interrupt handler).
<<label [[_vswitch]](arm)>>=
    /*
     *  come here with type in R0 and R13 pointing above saved [r0-r4].
     *  we'll switch to SVC mode and then call trap.
     */
_vswitch:
    CLREX
    MOVW    SPSR, R1        /* save SPSR for ureg */
    MOVW    R14, R2         /* save interrupted pc for ureg */
    MOVW    R13, R3         /* save pointer to where the original [R0-R4] are */

    /*
     * switch processor to svc mode.  this switches the banked registers
     * (r13 [sp] and r14 [link]) to those of svc mode.
     */
    MOVW    CPSR, R14
    BIC $PsrMask, R14
    ORR $(PsrDirq|PsrMsvc), R14
    MOVW    R14, CPSR       /* switch! */

    AND.S   $0xf, R1, R4        /* interrupted code kernel or user? */
    BEQ _userexcep
    // else
    /* here for trap from SVC mode */
    <<[[_vswitch]] trap from SVC mode>>
    /* here for trap from USER mode */
    <<[[_vswitch]] trap from USER mode>>
@
%$

<<[[_vswitch]] trap from USER mode>>=
_userexcep:
    MOVM.DB.W [R0-R2], (R13)    /* set ureg->{type, psr, pc}; r13 points to ureg->type  */
    MOVM.IA   (R3), [R0-R4]     /* restore [R0-R4] from previous mode's stack */

    /* avoid the ambiguity described in notes/movm.w. */
    MOVM.DB.S [R0-R14], (R13)   /* save kernel level registers */
    SUB $(15*4), R13        /* r13 now points to ureg */

    MOVW    $setR12(SB), R12    /* Make sure we've got the kernel's SB loaded */

    /* get R(CPU) for this cpu */
    <<[[_vswitch()]] set cpu register(arm)>>

    MOVW    8(R(CPU)), R(UP)        /* up */

    MOVW    R13, R0         /* first arg is pointer to ureg */
    SUB $(4*2), R13     /* space for argument+link (for debugger) */

    BL  arch__trap(SB)

    ADD $(4*2+4*15), R13    /* make r13 point to ureg->type */
    MOVW    8(R13), R14     /* restore link */
    MOVW    4(R13), R0      /* restore SPSR */
    MOVW    R0, SPSR        /* ... */
    MOVM.DB.S (R13), [R0-R14]   /* restore registers */
    ADD $(4*2), R13     /* pop past ureg->{type+psr} */
    RFE             /* MOVM.IA.S.W (R13), [R15] */
@
%$
\t factorize again code to restore?

\t why need different code when trap from user of kernel?
% because kernel state may have to be adjusted? Not enough
% to restore R9/R10? actually want different values?
% Only reason?


%claude:
The SVC-mode (kernel) trap path is trickier. Since
the kernel was already in SVC mode when the exception
occurred, R13 and R14 were not banked---the saved
R0--R4 are on the {exception mode's} stack, not the
SVC stack. The code restores them, then saves {all}
registers onto the SVC stack. On return, it must also
overwrite the saved [[R10]] with the current [[R(CPU)]],
because if a reschedule happened during the trap, this
processor might now be running a different process
whose R10 was stale.

<<[[_vswitch]] trap from SVC mode>>=
    MOVM.DB.W [R0-R2], (R13)    /* set ureg->{type, psr, pc}; r13 points to ureg->type  */
    MOVM.IA   (R3), [R0-R4]     /* restore [R0-R4] from previous mode's stack */

    /*
     * avoid the ambiguity described in notes/movm.w.
     * In order to get a predictable value in R13 after the stores,
     * separate the store-multiple from the stack-pointer adjustment.
     * We'll assume that the old value of R13 should be stored on the stack.
     */
    /* save kernel level registers, at end r13 points to ureg */
    MOVM.DB [R0-R14], (R13)
    SUB $(15*4), R13        /* SP now points to saved R0 */

    MOVW    $setR12(SB), R12    /* Make sure we've got the kernel's SB loaded */

    MOVW    R13, R0         /* first arg is pointer to ureg */
    SUB $(4*2), R13     /* space for argument+link (for debugger) */
    MOVW    $0xdeaddead, R11    /* marker */

    BL  arch__trap(SB)

    MOVW    $setR12(SB), R12    /* reload kernel's SB (ORLY?) */
    ADD $(4*2+4*15), R13    /* make r13 point to ureg->type */
    /*
     * if we interrupted a previous trap's handler and are now
     * returning to it, we need to propagate the current R(CPU) (R10)
     * by overriding the saved one on the stack, since we may have
     * been rescheduled and be on a different processor now than
     * at entry.
     */
    MOVW    R(CPU), (-(15-CPU)*4)(R13) /* restore current cpu's CPU */
    MOVW    8(R13), R14     /* restore link */
    MOVW    4(R13), R0      /* restore SPSR */
    MOVW    R0, SPSR        /* ... */

    MOVM.DB (R13), [R0-R14]     /* restore registers */

    ADD $(4*2), R13     /* pop past ureg->{type+psr} to pc */
    RFE             /* MOVM.IA.S.W (R13), [R15] */
@
%$

\subsection{[[arch__trap()]] (ARM)}

% (_virq |  -> _vswitch) -> <>
%claude:
[[arch__trap()]] is the C-level exception dispatcher,
analogous to [<arch__syscall()>] for system calls. It
receives the saved [[Ureg]] and dispatches based on
[[ureg->type]]: data abort and prefetch abort go to the
page fault handler, undefined instruction to a trap
handler, and IRQ to the interrupt dispatcher. Before
returning to user mode, it checks for pending notes
(signals) and deferred scheduling, just like
[[arch__syscall()]].
%claude:
One subtle detail: the ARM pipeline means the saved PC
points {past} the faulting instruction. For most exceptions,
the interrupted PC is at [[ureg->pc - 4]]; for data aborts
it is [[ureg->pc - 8]] (because the ARM has already
advanced past the faulting instruction and the one
after it). The code below corrects for this.
<<function [[arch__trap]](arm)>>=
/*
 *  here on all exceptions other than syscall (SWI) and fiq
 */
void
arch__trap(Ureg *ureg)
{
    bool user;
    bool clockintr;
    <<[[trap()]] other locals(arm)>>

    <<[[trap()]] sanity check interrupts are disabled(arm)>>
    <<[[trap()]] sanity check enough space in kernel stack(arm)>>

    user = (ureg->psr & PsrMask) == PsrMusr; // TODO: arch_userureg
    if(user){
        up->dbgreg = ureg;
        <<[[trap()]] adjust kentry when interrupt user>>
    }

    /*
     * All interrupts/exceptions should be resumed at ureg->pc-4,
     * except for Data Abort which resumes at ureg->pc-8.
     */
    if(ureg->type == (PsrMabt+1))
        ureg->pc -= 8;
    else
       ureg->pc -= 4;

    clockintr = false;      /* if set, may call sched() before return */

    switch(ureg->type){
    <<[[trap()]] switch exception type cases(arm)>>
    default:
        panic("unknown trap; type %#lux, psr mode %#lux pc %lux", ureg->type,
            ureg->psr & PsrMask, ureg->pc);
        break;
    }
    arch_splhi();

    <<[[trap()]] if delaysched and clockintr>>

    if(user){
        <<[[trap()]] call possibly notify(arm)>>
        arch__kexit(ureg);
    }
}
@
% arch_splhi? who disabled interrupts?

%claude:
[[arch__kexit()]] is called just before returning from
the kernel to user space (after both syscalls and
exceptions). It updates the [[Tos]] structure with the
current CPU frequency and flushes the write-back cache
so that user code sees consistent memory.

% kexit for kernel exit because return to user space
<<function [[arch__kexit]](arm)>>=
/* go to user space */
void
arch__kexit(Ureg*)
{
    <<[[arch__kexit()]] tos adjustments>>
    tos->cyclefreq = cpu->cpuhz;
    <<[[arch__kexit()]] write back cache(arm)>>
}
@
% should be called hook_before_exit_syscall note that
% take Ureg*, so the address is in the stack and the actual
% value are where?


% divide by zero?


<<[[trap()]] sanity check interrupts are disabled(arm)>>=
assert(!arch_islo());
@

<<[[trap()]] other locals(arm)>>=
int rem;
@
<<[[trap()]] sanity check enough space in kernel stack(arm)>>=
if(up != nil)
    rem = ((char*)ureg)-up->kstack;
else
    rem = ((char*)ureg)-((char*)cpu + sizeof(Cpu));
if(rem < 256) {
    iprint("trap: %d stack bytes left, up %#p ureg %#p at pc %#lux\n",
        rem, up, ureg, ureg->pc);
    arch_delay(1000);
    arch_dumpstack();
    panic("trap: %d stack bytes left, up %#p ureg %#p at pc %#lux",
        rem, up, ureg, ureg->pc);
}
@
