\subsection{Undefined instruction fault (ARM)}

%claude:
An undefined instruction in user mode sends a note to the
process (which can handle it or die). In kernel mode, it
is a bug and causes a panic. The handler also checks for
floating-point instructions, which may trap if the FPU
was not enabled for this process.
<<[[trap()]] other locals(arm)>>=
char buf[ERRMAX];
@
<<[[trap()]] switch exception type cases(arm)>>=
case PsrMund:           /* undefined instruction */
    if(user){
        <<[[trap()]] when undefined instruction, if breakpoint(arm)>>
        else{
            <<[[trap()]] when undefined instruction, if float instr(arm)>>
            if(rv == 0){
                snprint(buf, sizeof buf,
                    "undefined instruction: pc %#lux\n",
                    ureg->pc);
                postnote(up, 1, buf, NDebug);
            }
        }
    }else{
        <<[[trap()]] when undefined instruction, round pc(arm)>>
        iprint("undefined instruction: pc %#lux inst %#ux\n",
            ureg->pc, *(u32int*)ureg->pc);
        panic("undefined instruction");
    }
    break;
@
% postnote vs panic


<<[[trap()]] when undefined instruction, round pc(arm)>>=
if (ureg->pc & 3) {
    iprint("rounding fault pc %#lux down to word\n",
        ureg->pc);
    ureg->pc &= ~3;
}
@

\subsection{Prefetch fault (ARM)}

%claude:
A prefetch abort means the CPU tried to fetch an instruction
from an unmapped or protected address. If it is a valid
user address, this triggers a page fault (handled by
[<faultarm()>], which calls the virtual memory system).
Otherwise, it is a fatal error. The Instruction Fault
Status Register ([[IFSR]]) encodes the reason; the code
extracts a 4-bit fault code by concatenating non-contiguous
bits (an ARMv6/v7 encoding quirk).
<<[[trap()]] other locals(arm)>>=
int x;
ulong fsr;
@

<<[[trap()]] switch exception type cases(arm)>>=
case PsrMabt:           /* prefetch fault */
    x = ifsrget();
    fsr = (x>>7) & 0x8 | x & 0x7;
    switch(fsr){
    <<[[trap()]] when prefetch fault, switch fst cases(arm)>>
    default:
        // Page fault on code!!
        faultarm(ureg, ureg->pc, user, true);
        break;
    }
    break;
@
% faultarm later! in Virtual memory chapter.
% true = read

<<function [[ifsrget]](arm)>>=
TEXT ifsrget(SB), 1, $-4            /* instruction fault status */
    MRC CpSC, 0, R0, C(CpFSR), C(0), CpFSRinst
    RET
@
%$
% Saw CpFSR in Overview.

<<type [[CpFSR]](arm)>>=
/*
 * CpFSR opcode2 values.
 */
#define CpFSRdata   0           /* armv6, armv7 */
#define CpFSRinst   1           /* armv6, armv7 */
@




\subsection{Data fault (ARM)}

%claude:
A data abort is the most common exception: it fires when
a load or store accesses an unmapped page. This is the
entry point for {demand paging}---the page fault handler
([<faultarm()>]) checks whether the address belongs to
a valid segment, allocates a page if needed, fills it
from disk or zeros it, and returns. The faulting
instruction is then re-executed. Data aborts can also occur
when the kernel accesses a user address during a syscall
(e.g., copying arguments); this case is handled via the
error/waserror mechanism.
%claude:
The Fault Status Register ([[FSR]]) tells the kernel {why}
the fault occurred. The code extracts a 6-bit fault code
from the FSR and dispatches on it: translation faults
(0x5, 0x7) and permission faults (0xd, 0xf) go to the
page fault handler; domain faults (0x9, 0xb) are access
violations; alignment faults and external aborts are
fatal errors.
<<[[trap()]] other locals(arm)>>=
virt_addr va; // can be a kern_addr?
ulong inst;
@
% faulting instruction

<<[[trap()]] switch exception type cases(arm)>>=
case PsrMabt+1:         /* data fault */
    va = farget();
    inst = *(ulong*)(ureg->pc);
    /* bits 12 and 10 have to be concatenated with status */
    x = fsrget();
    fsr = (x>>7) & 0x20 | (x>>6) & 0x10 | x & 0xf;
    switch(fsr){
    <<[[trap()]] when data fault, switch fst cases(arm)>>
    default:
    case 0xa:       /* ? was under external abort */
        panic("unknown data fault, 6b fsr %#lux", fsr);
        break;
    }
    break;
@

<<function [[farget]](arm)>>=
TEXT farget(SB), 1, $-4             /* fault address */
    MRC CpSC, 0, R0, C(CpFAR), C(0x0)
    RET
@

<<function [[fstget]](arm)>>=
TEXT fsrget(SB), 1, $-4             /* data fault status */
    MRC CpSC, 0, R0, C(CpFSR), C(0), CpFSRdata
    RET
@


<<[[trap()]] when data fault, switch fst cases(arm)>>=
case 0xd:
case 0xf:
    /* permission error, copy on write or real permission error */
    faultarm(ureg, va, user, !writetomem(inst));
    break;
@
% last parameter of faultarm is boolean for read, so !writetomem

%claude:
The page fault handler needs to know whether the faulting
instruction was a load or a store, to set [[PG_MOD]]
correctly. [[writetomem()]] decodes the faulting ARM
instruction: bit~20 distinguishes loads (1) from
stores (0) for most instructions, and swap instructions
(detected by a specific bit pattern) always write.

<<function [[writetomem]](arm)>>=
/*
 *  returns true if the instruction writes memory, false otherwise
 */
bool
writetomem(ulong inst)
{
    /* swap always write memory */
    if((inst & 0x0FC00000) == 0x01000000)
        return true;

    /* loads and stores are distinguished by bit 20 */
    if(inst & (1<<20))
        return false;

    return true;
}
@
% >> >>
% see \book{Linker} and \book{Machine} for instruction format.



<<[[trap()]] when data fault, switch fst cases(arm)>>=
case 0x5:       /* translation fault, no section entry */
case 0x7:       /* translation fault, no page entry */
    // Page fault on data!!
    faultarm(ureg, va, user, !writetomem(inst));
    break;
@

<<[[trap()]] when data fault, switch fst cases(arm)>>=
case 0x9:
case 0xb:
    /* domain fault, accessing something we shouldn't */
    if(user){
        snprint(buf, sizeof buf,
            "sys: access violation: pc %#lux va %#p\n",
            ureg->pc, va);
        postnote(up, 1, buf, NDebug);
    } else
        panic("kernel access violation: pc %#lux va %#p",
            ureg->pc, va);
    break;
@





<<[[trap()]] when data fault, switch fst cases(arm)>>=
case 0x0:
    panic("vector exception at %#lux", ureg->pc);
    break;
@
% ?

<<[[trap()]] when data fault, switch fst cases(arm)>>=
case 0x1:       /* alignment fault */
case 0x3:       /* access flag fault (section) */
    if(user){
        snprint(buf, sizeof buf,
            "sys: alignment: pc %#lux va %#p\n",
            ureg->pc, va);
        postnote(up, 1, buf, NDebug);
    } else
        panic("kernel alignment: pc %#lux va %#p", ureg->pc, va);
    break;
@

<<[[trap()]] when data fault, switch fst cases(arm)>>=
case 0x2:
    panic("terminal exception at %#lux", ureg->pc);
    break;
@
% ??

<<[[trap()]] when data fault, switch fst cases(arm)>>=
case 0x4:       /* icache maint fault */
case 0x6:       /* access flag fault (page) */
case 0x8:       /* precise external abort, non-xlat'n */
case 0x28:
case 0xc:       /* l1 translation, precise ext. abort */
case 0x2c:
case 0xe:       /* l2 translation, precise ext. abort */
case 0x2e:
case 0x16:      /* imprecise ext. abort, non-xlt'n */
case 0x36:
    panic("external abort %#lux pc %#lux addr %#p",
        fsr, ureg->pc, va);
    break;
@

<<[[trap()]] when data fault, switch fst cases(arm)>>=
case 0x1c:      /* l1 translation, precise parity err */
case 0x1e:      /* l2 translation, precise parity err */
case 0x18:      /* imprecise parity or ecc err */
    panic("translation parity error %#lux pc %#lux addr %#p",
        fsr, ureg->pc, va);
    break;
@



\section{IRQs (ARM)}

%claude:
Hardware interrupts (IRQs) come from external devices:
the timer, USB controller, SD card, UART, etc. On the
Raspberry Pi, the BCM2835 has an interrupt controller at
[[INTREGS]] with three 32-bit pending registers (covering
up to 72 interrupt sources). Each device driver registers
its handler via [<arch_intrenable()>], and when an IRQ fires,
[<irq()>] scans the pending bits and dispatches to the
registered handler.
%claude:
The overall pattern is simple: at boot, each device driver
calls [[arch_intrenable(IRQxxx, handler, arg)]] to register
itself. At runtime, when a device raises an interrupt,
the hardware sets a bit in the pending register, the ARM
jumps to [[_virq]], which builds a [[Ureg]] and calls
[[arch__trap]], which calls [[irq()]], which walks the
[[vctl]] list and calls every handler whose pending bit
is set.
<<enum [[IRQ]](arm)>>=
enum IRQ {
    IRQtimer0   = 0, // reserved by GPU?
    IRQtimer1   = 1, // reserved by GPU?
    IRQtimer2   = 2, // reserved by GPU?
    IRQtimer3   = 3,

    IRQclock    = IRQtimer3,

    IRQusb      = 9,  // also IRQfiq
    IRQdma0     = 16, // IRQdma1, IRQdma2, ... via IRQDMA() macro

    IRQaux      = 29,
    IRQi2c      = 53,
    IRQspi      = 54,
    IRQmmc      = 62,

    <<[[IRQ]] basic cases(arm)>>
    <<[[IRQ]] local cases(arm)>>
    <<[[IRQ]] other cases(arm)>>
};
@


\subsection{[[Vctl]] (ARM)}

%claude:
A [[Vctl]] (``vector control'') records one registered
interrupt handler: which IRQ number it handles, the
hardware register and bitmask to check whether this IRQ
is pending, the handler function, and its argument. All
registered handlers form a linked list ([[vctl]]):
<<struct [[Vctl]](arm)>>=
struct Vctl {
    // enum<IRQ>
    int irq;

    u32int  *reg; // VIRTIO address
    u32int  mask;

    void    (*f)(Ureg*, void*); /* handler to call */
    void    *a; /* argument to call it with */

    <<[[Vctl]] other fields(arm)>>

    // Extra
    <<[[Vctl]] extra fields(arm)>>
};
@
%x86: similar structure, but few differences

% Vctl.reg will contain address where register specific to interrupt
% is stored and where can check if IRQ raised was this IRQ by
% getting its value and and it with the mask.

% V?? Vector? Interrupt vector?

<<global [[vctl]](arm)>>=
// list<ref_own<Vctl>>> (next = Vctl.next)
static Vctl *vctl;
@
%x86: [256]

<<[[Vctl]] extra fields(arm)>>=
Vctl    *next;
@

<<global [[vctllock]](arm)>>=
static Lock vctllock;
@
