\subsection{[[Intregs]] (ARM)}

% INTREGS!
%claude:
The BCM2835 interrupt controller is accessed via
memory-mapped registers at [[INTREGS]]. It has separate
pending/enable/disable registers for ARM-specific and
GPU-shared interrupts. The structure fields are laid out
to match the hardware registers exactly---writing to
[[GPUenable[0]]] directly enables the corresponding
interrupt in hardware:

%http://embedded-xinu.readthedocs.io/en/latest/arm/rpi/BCM2835-Interrupt-Controller.html

<<struct [[Intregs]](arm)>>=
/*
 * interrupt control registers
 */
// The order matters! the fields match the memory-mapped external registers.
struct Intregs {
    u32int  ARMpending;
    u32int  GPUpending[2];

    u32int  FIQctl;

    u32int  GPUenable[2];
    u32int  ARMenable;

    u32int  GPUdisable[2];
    u32int  ARMdisable;
};
@
% 2 int, so 64 bits for 64 possible IRQs.
%not used: GPUdisable


\subsection{[[arch_intrenable()]] (ARM)}

%claude:
Device drivers call [<arch_intrenable()>] during
initialization to register their interrupt handler. It
allocates a [[Vctl]], records the handler and the
appropriate pending register/mask, and enables the
interrupt in the hardware controller:
<<macro [[arch_intrenable]](arm)>>=
#define arch_intrenable(i, f, a, b, n) irqenable((i), (f), (a))
@
% does not use b and n? what are those parameters?


<<function [[irqenable]](arm)>>=
void
irqenable(int irq, void (*f)(Ureg*, void*), void* a)
{
    Vctl *v;
    Intregs *ip;
    u32int *enable;

    ip = (Intregs*)INTREGS;
    v = (Vctl*)malloc(sizeof(Vctl));
    <<[[irqenable()]] sanity check v(arm)>>
    v->irq = irq;
    v->cpu = 0;
    <<[[irqenable()]] if IRQlocal(arm)>>
    <<[[irqenable()]] if IRQbasic(arm)>>
    else{
        enable = &ip->GPUenable[irq/32];
        v->reg = &ip->GPUpending[irq/32];
        v->mask = 1 << (irq % 32);
    }
    v->f = f;
    v->a = a;
    lock(&vctllock);
    <<[[irqenable()]] if IRQfiq(arm)>>
    else{
        v->next = vctl;
        vctl = v;
        <<[[irqenable()]] if IRQlocal adjust enable(arm)>>
        else
            *enable = v->mask;
    }
    unlock(&vctllock);
}
@
% >> >> >> >> >>
%x86: also a intrdisable


<<[[irqenable()]] sanity check v(arm)>>=
if(v == nil)
    panic("irqenable: no mem");
@


\subsection{Basic IRQs (ARM)}

%claude:
The BCM2835 splits interrupts into two groups: 64 GPU
interrupts (in [[GPUpending[0..1]]]) and a handful of
ARM-specific interrupts (in [[ARMpending]], starting at
number~64). The ARM timer interrupt ([[IRQtimerArm]]) is
in this second group:

<<[[IRQ]] basic cases(arm)>>=
IRQbasic    = 64,
IRQtimerArm = IRQbasic + 0,
@
% IRQtimerArm used for USB.

<<[[irqenable()]] if IRQbasic(arm)>>=
else if(irq >= IRQbasic){
    enable = &ip->ARMenable;
    v->reg = &ip->ARMpending;
    v->mask = 1 << (irq - IRQbasic);
}
@
% >>

\subsection{[[irq()]] (ARM)}

% when exception, where is stored the exception number?
%
%claude:
[<irq()>] is called from [[arch__trap]] when the exception
type is [[PsrMirq]]. It walks the [[vctl]] list and, for
each handler whose pending bit is set, calls the handler.
It returns [[true]] if a clock interrupt was among
them---the caller uses this to decide whether to trigger
a reschedule (the clock is what drives preemptive
scheduling).

<<[[trap()]] switch exception type cases(arm)>>=
case PsrMirq:
    clockintr = irq(ureg);
    cpu->intr++;
    break;
@

%claude:
The dispatch loop is brute-force: walk the entire [[vctl]]
list and check each handler's pending bit. This is
acceptable because the list is short (a handful of device
drivers). If no handler matches, the interrupt is counted
as spurious. The return value tells [[arch__trap()]]
whether the clock was among the interrupts, which
triggers a possible reschedule.

% trap -> <>
<<function [[irq]](arm)>>=
/*
 *  called by trap to handle irq interrupts.
 *  returns true iff a clock interrupt, thus maybe reschedule.
 */
static bool
irq(Ureg* ureg)
{
    Vctl *v;
    bool clockintr;
    bool found;

    cpu->perf.intrts = arch_perfticks();
    clockintr = false;
    found = false;
    for(v = vctl; v; v = v->next)
        if(v->cpu == cpu->cpuno && (*v->reg & v->mask) != 0){
            found = true;
            <<[[irq()]] before dispatch(arm)>>
            // Dispatch
            v->f(ureg, v->a);
            <<[[irq()]] after dispatch(arm)>>
            if(v->irq == IRQclock || v->irq == IRQcntps || v->irq == IRQcntpns)
                clockintr = true;
        }
    if(!found)
        cpu->spuriousintr++;
    intrtime();
    return clockintr;
}
@
