%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Scheduling}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:scheduling}
%less: virtual CPU?
%less: add (clock interrupt) in title? to relate to Interrupt chapter?

\section{Overview}

% In essence the main role of an OS is to manage programs and so in essence
% it is first and foremost a scheduler!

% Key function is sched() (and its twin schedinit()).

% First part is cooperative scheduling, with sleep/wakeup
%  and people calling sched() themselves.
% Then will see preemptive scheduling with interrupt clock
%  that calls sched() after a certain quantum.

% What a system would look like without (preemptive) scheduling?
%  - a malicious/buggy process could never yield (see MacOS 9 ... windows 3.1)
%  - DOS didn't even offer cooperative scheduling, so could just have one
%    process at a time (at least windows 3.1 improved a bit on that)

% see also section in Debugging about /bin/trace that allows to
% trace scheduler events

%claude:
The scheduler decides which process runs next. Its
central function is [[sched()]] (and its twin
[[schedinit()]]). The chapter has two halves:
{cooperative scheduling}, where kernel code voluntarily
calls [[sched()]] or [[sleep()]]/[[wakeup()]] to yield
the processor; and {preemptive scheduling}, where the
clock interrupt forces a context switch after a time
quantum (100~ms by default). Both halves ultimately
funnel through the same mechanism: save the current
process's context, pick the next one from the run queue,
and restore its context.
%claude:
Processes are organized into priority queues. The
scheduler always picks the highest-priority ready process,
but priorities are dynamically adjusted to prevent
starvation.

\section{Process priority}
%adjustable priority actually

%claude:
There are 20 priority levels ([[Npriq]]). Normal user
processes start at priority~10 ([[PriNormal]]), kernel
processes at~13 ([[PriKproc]]). Higher numbers mean
higher priority. The priority can be adjusted at
runtime via [[/proc/\emph{pid}/ctl]]:

<<constant [[Npriq]]>>=
Npriq   = 20,   /* number of scheduler priority levels */
@
