\section{The scheduler}

\subsection{[[sched()]]}

%claude:
[[sched()]] is the central function. When called with
[[up != nil]] (a running process wants to yield), it saves
the current process's context and jumps to [[schedinit()]].
When called with [[up == nil]] (from [[schedinit()]], on
the CPU's boot stack), it picks the next process via
[[runproc()]] and jumps to it.

% The main function!
% Will be called by many kernel code to call the scheduler to schedule
% another process, so when up is not nil. Will also be called
% at the very beginning by schedinit() when no process at all are running
% and up is nil (and in fact also when up is not nil indirectly because
% sched() calls schedinit which calls it back after resetting up).
% We will see first the code for the second case. Easier cos subtle 
% control flow between different contexts (stacks).

% actually why could not factorize code with sleep()? because of
% extra lock calls.
<<function [[sched]]>>=
/*
 *  If changing this routine, look also at sleep().  It
 *  contains a copy of the guts of sched().
 */
void
proc_sched(void)
{
    <<[[sched()]] locals>>

    <<[[sched()]] sanity check ilockdepth>>
    <<[[sched()]] if up>>
    // else
    <<[[sched()]] if no up>>
}
