\subsection{[[sched()]] and [[schedinit()]] dance}

%claude:
The interplay between [[sched()]] and [[schedinit()]] is
the trickiest part of the scheduler. Here is the flow
when a running process calls [[sched()]]:
\begin{verbatim}
  Process A's kstack:         CPU's boot stack:

  1. sched() called
     arch_setlabel(&up->sched)
     returns 0 (first time)
         |
         v
  2. arch_gotolabel(&cpu->sched)
     ----jumps to-------->  3. schedinit() resumes
                               up->state == Running
                               -> ready(up)
                               up = nil
                               -> sched()
                                    |
                                    v
                            4. p = runproc()
                               (picks process B)
                               arch_gotolabel(&p->sched)
                               ----jumps to-------->
                                                  Process B resumes
                                                  from its setlabel
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
When process~A is eventually picked again by [[runproc()]],
[[arch_gotolabel(\&A->sched)]] returns~1 (into step~1
above), and [[sched()]] calls [[arch_procrestore()]] and
returns---process~A continues where it left off.

% at some point up will be set and the kernel will code
% sched():

<<[[sched()]] if up>>=
if(up){
    <<[[sched()]] when up, possibly increment delaysched and return>>
    arch_splhi(); // schedinit requires this (also sensitive moment)
    cpu->cs++;

    arch_procsave(up);
    if(arch_setlabel(&up->sched)){
        //
        // here when the process has been scheduled back
        // from a arch_gotolabel(up->sched) by another process, see below
        //
        arch_procrestore(up);
        arch_spllo();
        return;
    }else{
        //
        // here to go to schedinit() (which will call sched() back)
        //
        arch_gotolabel(&cpu->sched); // goto schedinit()
        panic("sched: should never reach this point");
    }
}
@

