\subsection{Delayed [[sched()]]}

%claude:
A process holding spin locks must not be switched out---the
lock would remain held, potentially deadlocking other
CPUs. So when [[sched()]] is called while [[up->nlocks > 0]],
it increments [[delaysched]] and returns immediately. The
actual reschedule happens later, when [[unlock()]] sees
[[delaysched > 0]] and calls [[sched()]] after releasing
the last lock. As a safety valve, if [[delaysched]]
exceeds~20 (a lock was probably leaked), the scheduler
forces a switch anyway.

<<[[sched()]] when up, possibly increment delaysched and return>>=
/*
 * Delay the sched until the process gives up the locks
 * it is holding.  This avoids dumb lock loops.
 *
 * But don't delay if the process is Moribund.
 * It called sched to die.
 * But do sched eventually. This avoids a missing unlock
 * from hanging the entire kernel. 
 * But don't reschedule procs holding palloc or procalloc.
 * Those are far too important to be holding while asleep.
 *
 * This test is not exact.  There can still be a few instructions
 * in the middle of taslock when a process holds a lock
 * but Lock.p has not yet been initialized.
 */
if(up->nlocks.ref)
  if(up->state != Moribund)
    if(up->delaysched < 20
      || palloc.Lock.p == up
      || procalloc.Lock.p == up){

        up->delaysched++;
        delayedscheds++;
        return;
    }
// else
up->delaysched = 0;
@
% return so no reschedule

% when can have up->delaysched > 20? If there is a bug
% and process never released a spinlock in which case we still
% reschedule because we dont want to hang forever the kernel
% as the comment above say.


<<[[Proc]] scheduling fields>>=
ulong delaysched;
@

<<[[newproc()]] set fields of [[p]]>>=
p->nlocks.ref = 0;
p->delaysched = 0;
@
%old: there was a certain order but with LP it's less previsible
% but I think the order of field assignment does not matter


% ok so if process got extra time just to release his spinlocks,
% next time it unlocks we call sched()!

<<[[unlock()]] if delaysched>>=
if(up && deccnt(&up->nlocks) == 0 && up->delaysched && arch_islo()){
    /*
     * Call sched if the need arose while locks were held
     * But, don't do it from interrupt routines, hence the arch_islo() test
     */
    sched();
}
@



<<[[trap()]] if delaysched and clockintr>>=
/* delaysched set because we held a lock or because our quantum ended */
if(up && up->delaysched && clockintr){
    sched();
