\subsection{[[Rendez]]}

% see sleep.ps in plan9 documents

% sleep(similar to sched)/wakeup(calls ready)
% sleep/wakeup have a condition attached to it, and so a rendez vous,
% sched and ready are just altruistic, give back without asking.

%claude:
A [[Rendez]] (rendezvous point) is a condition variable
for kernel code. It pairs a sleeping process ([[r->p]])
with a lock. [[sleep()]] puts the current process to
sleep on a [[Rendez]] if a condition is false;
[[wakeup()]] wakes it when the condition becomes true.
This is how all blocking in the kernel works: waiting
for a page, a lock, a child exit, a pipe read, etc.

<<struct [[Rendez]]>>=
struct Rendez
{
    // option<ref<Proc>>
    Proc  *p; // sleeping process

    Lock; // LOCK ORDERING: always do lock(r); lock(p->rlock);
};
