\section{Preemptive scheduling}

%claude:
Cooperative scheduling is not enough---a CPU-bound process
that never calls [[sleep()]] would monopolize the
processor. Preemptive scheduling uses the clock interrupt
(firing [[Arch_HZ]] times per second, i.e., every 10~ms)
to force context switches. Each process gets a time
quantum of 100~ms ([[Arch_HZ/10]] ticks); when the
quantum expires, [[hzsched()]] sets [[delaysched]] to
trigger a reschedule at the next safe point.

% Number of times per second we want to get a clock interrupt.
% At each clock interrupt, a counter is incremented called a tick.

<<constant [[Arch_HZ]](arm)>>=
#define Arch_HZ     100         /* clock frequency */
@
% 100 per second so every 10ms.
% every 10ms increment cpu->tick (see hzclock)
% so in one second cpu->tick has been incremented by Arch_HZ.


\subsection{[[hzsched()]]}

%claude:
[[hzsched()]] is called from [[hzclock()]] on every timer
tick while a process is running. It checks two conditions
for preemption: is there a higher-priority process ready
([[anyhigher()]])? or has the current process's quantum
expired ([[cpu->ticks > cpu->schedticks]])? If either is
true, it sets [[delaysched]] rather than calling
[[sched()]] directly---because we are inside an interrupt
handler and cannot safely switch context here. The actual
switch happens when the interrupt returns and checks
[[delaysched]].

<<[[Cpu]] other fields>>=
ulong schedticks;   /* next forced context switch */
@

<<[[sched()]] after found a new proc, adjust schedticks>>=
cpu->schedticks = cpu->ticks + Arch_HZ/10; // 100ms of allocated time
@
