\section{Real-time scheduling}
% see EDF section

\section{Adjusting priority}

\l move in advanced topics?

% Once you have different priorities queues, you can not just
% always take the process with higher priority. This would prevent
% other process to run at all. So we need to adjust the priority
% gradually.

%claude:
A fixed-priority scheduler would starve low-priority
processes. To prevent this, the kernel dynamically
adjusts each process's priority based on how much CPU
time it has used recently. [[updatecpu()]] decays the
process's CPU usage counter, and [[reprioritize()]]
maps that usage to a priority level. Processes that have
used a lot of CPU time recently get a lower priority;
those that have been sleeping get a higher one. This
ensures that I/O-bound processes (which sleep often)
remain responsive, while CPU-bound processes gradually
drop in priority.

\subsection{[[reprioritize()]]}

