\section{Overview (arm)}

%claude:
This chapter covers the kernel's time infrastructure:
how hardware timers generate interrupts, how the kernel
multiplexes a single hardware timer into many software
timers, and the time-related syscalls ([[sleep]] and
[[alarm]]). We saw [[hzclock()]] in the Scheduling chapter;
here we see how it gets called and what else runs on
each clock tick.
%claude:
The Raspberry Pi has several hardware timers running at
different frequencies. The kernel uses system timer~3
(1~MHz, 64-bit) for [[hzclock]] interrupts and
[[fastticks]], and the ARM timer (250~MHz, 32-bit)
for performance measurement.

