%less: Keyboard/Screen sections before File/Dir/Namespace sections? hmmm hard.

% We will only see a few drivers. Drivers actually are biggest part of
% kernel. But not as core, not as interesting. Lots of specifics.

% will talk about PC version because simpler (for once).
% Raspberry Pi forces to talk about USB and complicated. See Appendix.

\section{The keyboard}

\subsection{Overview}

% will talk about PC version because simpler (for once).

% interrupt i8042intr
% -> kbdputsc (accumulate, handle special keys) sc for scan code
% -> kbdputc (which adjust kbd circular buffer);

% interrupt kbdcclock
% -> echo()
% -> qproduce(kbdq) (and echoscreen()!)

% types:
%  - scan codes (series of bytes?)
%  - rune (int)
%  - char (int8)
%  - utf8 (variable)

% when type a key, it's first a scan code at the device level,
% then transformed by a table in a rune, then
% transformed by a series of bytes (utf8)!

%claude:
Keyboard input passes through a multi-stage pipeline before reaching
a user process. When you press a key, the hardware generates a
{scan code} (a raw byte identifying the physical key). The keyboard
interrupt handler calls [kbdputsc] which translates that scan code
into a {Rune} (a Unicode code point) by looking it up in one of several
tables depending on the modifier state (Shift, Ctrl, Alt, Altgr).
The Rune is then passed to [kbdputc], which converts it to UTF-8 bytes
and stores them in a circular buffer ([[kbd.istage]]).
A periodic clock callback ([kbdputcclock]) drains that buffer,
calling [echo] which both echoes characters to the screen and
enqueues them into [[kbdq]] via [qproduce].
The pipeline looks like this:
%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  hardware    interrupt         clock tick        process reads
    key  --> i8042intr --> kbdputsc --> kbdputc --> kbdputcclock --> echo
              scan code    Rune         UTF-8       |              |
              (1 byte)     (32-bit)     (1-4 bytes) |              |
                                        into        v              v
                                        istage[]  echoscreen()   qproduce(kbdq)
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
The reason for the intermediate [[istage]] circular buffer and the
clock-driven drain is to amortize the cost of queue operations:
calling [qproduce] on every single keystroke interrupt would be
wasteful, so instead characters accumulate at interrupt time and
get flushed in batch every 22~ms by the clock.

\subsection{Scan code}

% Note that the main function here generates unicode characters (Rune=32bits)
% (but they are actually decomposed back in individual chars later)

% http://www.computer-engineering.org/ps2keyboard/

%claude:
The scan code tables map raw hardware bytes to Unicode code points
(Runes). Special keys like Shift, Ctrl, and arrow keys cannot be
represented as normal characters, so they are assigned values in
Unicode's {Private Use Area} (starting at [[0xF000]]).
This is a clever trick: modifier keys and function keys live in the
same Rune space as regular characters, so the entire translation
can be done with a single array lookup rather than complex
conditional logic. The [[Nscan]] constant is 128 because the
8th bit of a scan code encodes key-up vs.\ key-down, leaving
7 bits for the key identity.

\t same than keyboard.h?
<<enum [[specialkey]]>>=
enum {
    KF=         0xF000,     /* function key (begin Unicode private space) */
    Spec=       0xF800,     /* Unicode private space */


    PF=         Spec|0x20,  /* num pad function key */
    View=       Spec|0x00,  /* view (shift window up) */

    Shift=      Spec|0x60,
    Break=      Spec|0x61,
    Ctrl=       Spec|0x62,
    Alt=        Spec|0x63,
    Caps=       Spec|0x64,
    Num=        Spec|0x65,
    Middle=     Spec|0x66,
    Altgr=      Spec|0x67,

    Kmouse=     Spec|0x100,

    No=         0x00,       /* peter */

    /* KF|1, KF|2, ..., KF|0xC is F1, F2, ..., F12 */

    Home=       KF|13,
    Up=         KF|14,
    Pgup=       KF|15,
    Print=      KF|16,
    Left=       KF|17,
    Right=      KF|18,
    End=        KF|24,
    Down=       View,
    Pgdown=     KF|19,
    Ins=        KF|20,
    Del=        0x7F,
    Scroll=     KF|21,

    Nscan=  128,
};
@
