\subsection{Esc}
% actually when type Left on keyboard, it generates e0 4b.
% The esc1 esc2 here are not related to the Esc key.
% The actual Esc key generates scan code 0x01

%claude:
Despite the name, this subsection has nothing to do with the Esc key
(which is just scan code [[0x01]]). The ``esc'' here refers to
{escape sequences} in the PS/2 scan code protocol: certain keys
(arrow keys, Home, End, etc.) generate multi-byte sequences prefixed
by [[0xe0]] (2-byte) or [[0xe1]] (3-byte). The state machine in
[kbdputsc] handles this by setting [[esc1]] or [[esc2]] flags when
it sees the prefix byte and returning immediately, then on the
next interrupt it uses [[kbtabesc1]] instead of [[kbtab]] for the
lookup. This is why arrow keys like Left and Right appear in
[[kbtabesc1]] rather than in the main [[kbtab]].

