\subsection{[[kbd]]}

%claude:
The [[ConsKbd]] structure is the staging area between the keyboard
interrupt and the queue system. Its [[istage]] circular buffer
accumulates UTF-8 bytes deposited by [kbdputc] at interrupt time.
The circular buffer uses three pointers: [[iw]] (write position),
[[ir]] (read position), and [[ie]] (end sentinel). This is a classic
lock-free single-producer single-consumer ring buffer -- the interrupt
handler writes at [[iw]] and the clock callback reads from [[ir]].

<<struct [[ConsKbd]]>>=
struct ConsKbd
{
    /* a place to save up characters at interrupt time before dumping them in the queue */
    char    istage[1024];
    // pointers into istage to implement a circular buffer
    char    *iw; // write
    char    *ir; // read
    char    *ie; // end
    ILock    lockputc;

    <<[[ConsKbd]] other fields>>
    // extra
    QLock;
};
@
% why not using Rune line[1024] and Rune istage[1024]? will simplify things
% and anyway kputsc already handles unicode and produce unicode characters?
% because plan9 manages queue of bytes, it's the code reading those bytes
% that have the job to possibly call the rune functions on it.


<<global [[kbd]]>>=
static struct ConsKbd kbd = 
{
    .iw = kbd.istage,
    .ir = kbd.istage,
    .ie = kbd.istage + sizeof(kbd.istage),
};
@ 

% called from raw kbd functions in previous section
%claude:
[kbdputc] bridges the Rune world and the byte world. It takes the
Rune produced by [kbdputsc] and converts it to UTF-8 via [[runetochar]],
then writes those bytes into the [[istage]] circular buffer.
This is where the [[/dev/cons]] interface becomes UTF-8 encoded --
even though the keyboard hardware deals in scan codes and the
internal processing uses 32-bit Runes, what reaches user processes
through the queue is a stream of UTF-8 bytes.
Note the use of [[ilock]] rather than [[qlock]]: this function runs
at interrupt time, so it must use a spin lock rather than a
sleeping mutex.

<<function [[kbdputc]]>>=
/*
 *  Put character, possibly a rune, into kbd at interrupt time.
 *  Called at interrupt time to process a character.
 */
void
kbdputc(Rune ch)
{
    int i, n;
    char buf[UTFmax]; // pad's fourth bugfix :)
    Rune r;
    char *next;

    <<[[kbdputc()]] debugging>>

    if(kbd.ir == nil)
        return;       /* in case we're not inited yet */
    
    ilock(&kbd.lockputc);       /* just a mutex */
    r = ch;
    n = runetochar(buf, &r);
    for(i = 0; i < n; i++){
        next = kbd.iw+1;
        // circular buffer
        if(next >= kbd.ie)
            next = kbd.istage;
        if(next == kbd.ir) // full
            break;
        *kbd.iw = buf[i];
        kbd.iw = next;
    }
    iunlock(&kbd.lockputc);
    return;
}
@ 
%old: used to take a queue argument, but was not using it so I removed it
%bug: see pad's bugfix above
\l should rename kbdputr for rune

% runetochar! (runetoutf8) this is where /dev/cons interface will be utf8!

%claude:
[kbdputcclock] is called every 22~ms from the clock interrupt. It
drains the [[istage]] circular buffer by calling [echo] on whatever
bytes have accumulated. The wraparound case (when [[iw < ir]])
requires two calls to [echo]: one for the tail of the buffer
(from [[ir]] to [[ie]]) and one for the head (from [[istage]] to
[[iw]]). There is no explicit lock here because the clock callback
and the keyboard interrupt are carefully ordered: the clock reads
[[iw]] once into a local variable, creating a consistent snapshot.

<<clock callback kbdputcclock>>=
/*
 *  we save up input characters till clock time to reduce
 *  per character interrupt overhead.
 */
static void
kbdputcclock(void)
{
    char *iw;

    /* this amortizes cost of qproduce */
    if(kbd.iw != kbd.ir){
        iw = kbd.iw;
        if(iw < kbd.ir){
            echo(kbd.ir, kbd.ie-kbd.ir);
            kbd.ir = kbd.istage;
        }
        if(kbd.ir != iw){
            echo(kbd.ir, iw-kbd.ir);
            kbd.ir = iw;
        }
    }
}
