\section{The console device [[/dev/cons]]}

% should be able to answer the interview question: "what happens
% when you type 'ls' on the keyboard" :)

% far cleaner than /dev/tty on linux!

%claude:
The console device exposes keyboard input and screen output through
the file system as [[/dev/cons]] and [[/dev/consctl]]. Reading
[[/dev/cons]] in cooked mode gives line-edited input: the kernel
buffers characters until a newline or Control-D, handling backspace
and Control-U (kill line) internally. This is much cleaner than
Unix's layered tty/pty/termios system -- in \plan, all line
discipline lives in this single device driver.

% What C-D actually do:
%https://utcc.utoronto.ca/~cks/space/blog/unix/TypingEOFEffects

\subsection{Overview}

