%###############################################################################

\part{Beyond the Basics}

%claude:
The previous two parts covered the kernel's core: process
virtualization and the file abstraction. This part covers
the remaining subsystems that build on top of that
foundation: inter-process communication (pipes, notes,
shared memory), the debugging and profiling infrastructure,
special file servers, and advanced topics that crosscut
multiple subsystems.

%******************************************************************************
\chapter{IPC}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:ipc}

% of course can use fs to communicate between process :)
% also when fork child inherit fd and can share stuff there
% also child can communicate to parent fix exit code (if parent calls wait())
%  and this exit code is now even a string! as opposed to unix

% finally debugging is a form of IPC, the debugger communicate/control
% the debuggee process

%claude:
Plan 9 provides several IPC mechanisms beyond the filesystem (which is
itself an IPC mechanism via [[read]]/[[write]] on shared channels).
This chapter covers notes (the Plan 9 equivalent of Unix signals, but
string-based), pipes (bidirectional, unlike Unix), shared memory segments,
user-level semaphores with kernel backing, and rendezvous (a lightweight
synchronization primitive for exchanging values between processes).

<<[[systab]] ipc syscalls>>=
