\section{Core dumps and broken processes}
% When get a suicide, or a signal with NDEBUG, then put in a broken state.
% Also when have faulterror in pio().
% kinda of core dumps except don't pollute disk with it and keep everything
% intact for post mortem analysis.

% can then do 'db <pid>' and start debug!

%claude:
Instead of writing core dumps to disk like \unix, Plan 9 keeps
a crashed process alive in the [[Broken]] state. The process
retains its address space and registers intact, so a debugger
can attach to it with [[db \emph{pid}]] and do post-mortem analysis
without any intermediate file. This is both more convenient (no
multi-megabyte core files) and more faithful (the entire process
state is preserved, not just what the kernel chose to dump).
The kernel limits broken processes to [[NBROKEN]] (4) at a time;
when a new one arrives and the table is full, the oldest is
evicted and allowed to finish dying.

<<[[Procstate]] cases>>=
Broken,
@

<<struct [[Broken]]>>=
/*
 * weird thing: keep at most NBROKEN around
 */
#define NBROKEN 4
struct Broken
{
    // array<ref<Proc>>
    Proc    *p[NBROKEN];
    // number of entries used in p
    int n;

    // extra
    QLock;
};
@ 

<<global [[broken]]>>=
struct Broken broken;
@ 

<<[[pexit()]] if not freemem, add process to broken processes list>>=
// instead of a core dump we just keep the process around
if(!freemem)
    addbroken(up); // will call sched()
@
%when call pexit without freemem? 



% when call via pexit(exitstr, freemem=false)

%claude:
When [[addbroken()]] is called (from [[pexit()]] with [[freemem]]
false), the process is suspended in the [[Broken]] state and added
to the fixed-size [[broken]] array. If the array is full, the oldest
broken process is evicted by calling [[ready()]] on it, which resumes
its [[pexit()]] and lets it finally free its resources and die.
Killing a broken process (via ``kill'' in its ctl file) calls
[[unbreak()]], which also readies it to resume dying. The
[[freebroken()]] function is a last-resort call from the pager when
memory is critically low.

<<function [[addbroken]]>>=
void
addbroken(Proc *p)
{
    qlock(&broken);
    if(broken.n == NBROKEN) {
        ready(broken.p[0]);
        memmove(&broken.p[0], &broken.p[1], sizeof(Proc*)*(NBROKEN-1));
        --broken.n;
    }
    broken.p[broken.n++] = p;
    qunlock(&broken);

    edfstop(up);
    p->state = Broken;
    p->psstate = nil;
    sched();
}
@ 


% usually unbreak will actually resume to pexit() ands and really finish the
% process
<<function [[unbreak]]>>=
void
unbreak(Proc *p)
{
    int b;

    qlock(&broken);
    for(b=0; b < broken.n; b++)
        if(broken.p[b] == p) {
            broken.n--;
            memmove(&broken.p[b], &broken.p[b+1],
                    sizeof(Proc*)*(NBROKEN-(b+1)));
            ready(p);
            break;
        }
    qunlock(&broken);
}
@ 

% call by the pager when we really really need memory
<<function [[freebroken]]>>=
int
freebroken(void)
{
    int i, n;

    qlock(&broken);
    n = broken.n;
    for(i=0; i<n; i++) {
        ready(broken.p[i]);
        broken.p[i] = nil;
    }
    broken.n = 0;
    qunlock(&broken);
    return n;
}
@ 

<<[[procctlreq()]] CMkill case, Broken case>>=
        case Broken:
            // will resume the broken process to finally die and free its mem
            unbreak(p); 
            break;
@


