\section{Floating point}

\subsection{[[FPSaveStatus]]}

%trans: see hardware support for float later. Here how plan9 adapts that.

%claude:
The kernel uses {lazy floating point context switching}: the FPU is
kept disabled by default, and only enabled when a process actually
executes a floating point instruction. This avoids the cost of
saving and restoring 32 double-precision registers on every context
switch for processes that never use floating point.
The [[FPSaveStatus]] enum tracks where each process stands in this
lifecycle: [[FPinit]] means the process has never used the FPU,
[[FPactive]] means the FPU is currently on for this process,
and [[FPinactive]] means the FPU state has been saved and the
hardware disabled. The [[FPillegal]] bit is or'd in during note
(signal) handling to prevent note handlers from corrupting the
interrupted code's FPU state.

<<enum [[fpsavestatus]]>>=
/*
 * FPsave.status
 */
enum FPSaveStatus
{
    /* this is a state */
    FPinit=   0,

    FPactive= 1,
    FPinactive= 2,

    /* the following is a bit that can be or'd into the state */
    FPillegal=  0x100,
};
@ 
%dead: 
%    FPemu = 3, // used by bcm/ only
% was used before but with VFP3 I do not need that anymore

% If process does not use any float registers, then no need to save them!
% So kinda opti?

%claude:
Each process carries an [[fpstate]] field that the scheduler hooks
consult to decide whether FPU registers need saving or restoring.
New processes start in [[FPinit]], and a forked child inherits the
parent's state minus the [[FPillegal]] bit so it is not penalized
for something the parent did in a note handler.

<<[[Proc]] other fields>>=
// enum<FPSaveStatus>
