\subsection{Floating point hooks}
% many of those hooks seems portable ... so I removed the (ARM)

%claude:
The lazy FPU scheme plugs into the scheduler through a set of hooks
called at key process lifecycle points. The flow is:
%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  procsave()    --> fpuprocsave()       save FPU if FPactive, mark FPinactive
  procrestore() --> fpuprocrestore()   (no-op: restored lazily on fault)
  sysrfork()    --> fpusysrfork()      save parent's FPU before fork
  forkchild()   --> fpusysrforkchild() copy state to child
  sysexec()     --> fpusysprocsetup()  reset to FPinit, disable FPU
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
The key insight is that [fpuprocrestore] is intentionally empty.
Rather than eagerly restoring FPU state when a process is rescheduled,
the kernel leaves the FPU disabled. If the process tries to use
floating point, it triggers an ``undefined instruction'' trap, and
[fpuemu] restores the state at that point. This means processes
that were using FPU before being descheduled but happen not to use
it in their next quantum pay zero cost.

<<[[arch_forkchild()]] floating point(arm)>>=
fpusysrforkchild(p, cureg, up);
@
<<function [[fpusysrforkchild]](arm)>>=
/*
 * Called later in sysrfork() via the machine-dependent
 * sysrforkchild() routine.
 * Copy the parent FPU state to the child.
 */
void
fpusysrforkchild(Proc *p, Ureg *, Proc *up)
{
    /* don't penalize the child, it hasn't done FP in a note handler. */
    p->fpstate = up->fpstate & ~FPillegal;
}
@

<<[[arch_procsetup()]] floating point(arm)>>=
fpusysprocsetup(p);
@

<<function [[fpusysprocsetup]](arm)>>=
/*
 * Disable the FPU.
 * Called from sysexec() via sysprocsetup() to
 * set the FPU for the new process.
 */
void
fpusysprocsetup(Proc *p)
{
    p->fpstate = FPinit;
    fpoff();
}
@


<<[[arch_procsave()]] floating point(arm)>>=
/* TODO: save and restore VFPv3 FP state once 5[cal] know the new registers.*/
fpuprocsave(p);
@

%claude:
When a process is about to be descheduled, [fpuprocsave] saves the
FPU registers only if the process was actively using them. A dying
process ([[Moribund]]) gets its FPU cleared outright since its state
will never be needed again. The subtle point in the comment is that
[fpsave] cannot handle pending unmasked exceptions here because
[postnote] requires the process lock, which [sleep] may already
hold. Instead, exception handling is deferred until the process
runs again and triggers a new FPU fault.

<<function [[fpuprocsave]](arm)>>=
/*
 * Called from sched() and sleep() via the machine-dependent
 * procsave() routine.
 * About to go in to the scheduler.
 * If the process wasn't using the FPU
 * there's nothing to do.
 */
void
fpuprocsave(Proc *p)
{
    if(p->fpstate == FPactive){
        if(p->state == Moribund)
            fpclear();
        else{
            /*
             * Fpsave() stores without handling pending
             * unmasked exeptions. Postnote() can't be called
             * here as sleep() already has up->rlock, so
             * the handling of pending exceptions is delayed
             * until the process runs again and generates an
             * emulation fault to activate the FPU.
             */
            fpsave(&p->fpsave);
        }
        p->fpstate = FPinactive;
    }
}
@

<<[[arch_procrestore()]] floating point(arm)>>=
fpuprocrestore(p);
@
<<function [[fpuprocrestore]](arm)>>=
/*
 * The process has been rescheduled and is about to run.
 * Nothing to do here right now. If the process tries to use
 * the FPU again it will cause a Device Not Available
 * exception and the state will then be restored.
 */
void
fpuprocrestore(Proc *)
{
}
@


<<[[syscall()]] if RFORK, handle floating point(arm)>>=
if(scallnr == RFORK)
    fpusysrfork(ureg);
@
% why intercept call in syscall()? can not do that as rfork hook?
<<function [[fpusysrfork]](arm)>>=
/*
 * Called early in the non-interruptible path of
 * sysrfork() via the machine-dependent syscall() routine.
 * Save the state so that it can be easily copied
 * to the child process later.
 */
void
fpusysrfork(Ureg*)
{
    if(up->fpstate == FPactive){
        fpsave(&up->fpsave);
        up->fpstate = FPinactive;
    }
}
@

% fpuprocsave | fpusysrfork -> <>

%claude:
The actual register save loop iterates over all FPU registers
(16 for VFPv2, 32 for VFPv3), reading each via [fpsavereg] which
dynamically constructs a VSTR instruction. The FPSCR (floating point
status and control register) is saved as both [[status]] and
[[control]] so that pending exception flags and configuration bits
are preserved separately.

<<function [[fpsave]](arm)>>=
/* should only be called if p->fpstate == FPactive */
void
fpsave(Arch_FPsave *fps)
{
    int n;

    fpon();
    fps->control = fps->status = fprd(Fpscr);
    assert(cpu->fpnregs);
    for (n = 0; n < cpu->fpnregs; n++)
        fpsavereg(n, (uvlong *)fps->regs[n]);
    fpoff();
}
@




%claude:
Note handlers are forbidden from using the FPU because their
execution is interposed between the interrupted code and its eventual
resumption. If a note handler used floating point, it would silently
corrupt the interrupted code's FPU registers. The [[FPillegal]] bit
enforces this: [fpunotify] sets it before delivering the note, and
if the handler tries to execute an FP instruction, [fpuemu] will
see the bit and post an error note. When the handler finishes,
[fpunoted] clears the bit.

<<function [[fpunotify]](arm)>>=
/*
 * Called when a note is about to be delivered to a
 * user process, usually at the end of a system call.
 * Note handlers are not allowed to use the FPU so
 * the state is marked (after saving if necessary) and
 * checked in the Device Not Available handler.
 */
void
fpunotify(Ureg*)
{
    if(up->fpstate == FPactive){
        fpsave(&up->fpsave);
        up->fpstate = FPinactive;
    }
    up->fpstate |= FPillegal;
}
@

<<function [[fpunoted]](arm)>>=
/*
 * Called from sysnoted() via the machine-dependent
 * noted() routine.
 * Clear the flag set above in fpunotify().
 */
void
fpunoted(void)
{
    up->fpstate &= ~FPillegal;
}
@






\subsection{ARM floating point coprocessors (ARM)}

%claude:
On ARM, floating point is accessed through coprocessors 10 (single
precision) and 11 (double precision). The kernel detects whether
the hardware implements VFPv2 (16 registers) or VFPv3 (32 registers)
and records this in [[cpu->fpnregs]]. This fork of Plan~9 relies
on the compiler ([[5l -f]]) generating native VFP3 instructions,
so the old software FPU emulation code (fpiarm.c) has been removed.

<<[[Coprocessors]] other cases(arm)>>=
#define CpFP        10          /* float FP, VFP cfg. */
#define CpDFP       11          /* double FP */
@
