\section{CPU cache}

%https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CPU_cache

%http://duartes.org/gustavo/blog/post/intel-cpu-caches/

%claude:
CPU caches are small fast memories that sit between the processor
and main RAM. The ARM has separate L1 caches for instructions (I-cache)
and data (D-cache), which means code modifications (like the
self-modifying FPU trick above, or writing exception vectors)
require explicit cache maintenance: the D-cache must be written
back so the new data reaches memory, and the I-cache must be
invalidated so the processor fetches the updated instructions.
The kernel must also manage caches around MMU operations, because
changing page tables can make cached virtual-to-physical translations
stale.

\subsection{Instruction and data cache (ARM)}

% L1, L2. Split data vs instruction cache. Related is TLB.
% Cacheline size = granularity of entry. 
% Cache entry = a cache of a cacheline from memory in the cache.

%in kernel/docs/arm/readme.txt
% l1 I & D VIPT caches
% 	16K each: 4-way, 128 sets, 32-byte lines
% 	l1 D is write-through, l1 I is write-back
% unified l2 PIPT cache 128K: 4-way?, 1024? sets, 32-byte lines, mostly for gpu
% (by default CPU doesn't see it)
%pad: PIPT = Physically Indexed, Physically Tagged

% confusing than ARM (or Miller?) use L1/L2 terminology for MMU
% and L1/L2 for cache techno.

<<[[CpSC primary registers]] other cases(arm)>>=
#define CpCACHE     7           /* cache/write buffer control */
@

<<[[CpCONTROL.CpMainctl]] other cases(arm)>>=
#define CpCdcache   0x00000004  /* C: data cache on */
#define CpCicache   0x00001000  /* I: instruction cache on */
@

% instruction cache = prefetch buffer. 

<<[[armstart()]] disable features(arm)>>=
BIC $(CpCdcache|CpCicache), R1
@
%$

<<[[armstart()]] invalidate caches(arm)>>=
MCR CpSC, 0, R0, C(CpCACHE), C(CpCACHEinvu), CpCACHEall
@
<<[[armstart()]] reenable features(arm)>>=
ORR $(CpCdcache|CpCicache), R0
@
%$

\subsection{Cache policy}
% write-through, write-back

%claude:
The cache can operate in write-through mode (every store goes
immediately to memory) or write-back mode (stores stay in the cache
and are written to memory later). Write-back is more efficient but
requires explicit ``writeback'' operations before other bus masters
(DMA, other CPUs) need to see the data. The [[Buffered]] and
[[Cached]] page table entry attributes select write-back caching
for normal DRAM pages. Memory-mapped I/O regions must not be
cached, since reading a device register should always go to the
hardware, not return a stale cached value.

% Cache/write-bufffer because cache for reading, but also cache/postpone
% writing with write-buffer.

