\subsection{Memory barriers (ARM)}

% When switch processor, virtual mem, then interfere
% with cache as virtual address may now correspond to something else.
% Also issue about VIRTIO space that should not be cached.

%claude:
On ARMv6, ISB and DSB are implemented via MCR instructions to
coprocessor~7, not as dedicated instructions. ISB invalidates the
instruction prefetch buffer, DSB drains the write buffer. They
are combined into the [[BARRIERS]] macro used in boot code.

<<instruction ISB(arm)>>=
#define ISB \
    MOVW    $0, R0; \
    MCR CpSC, 0, R0, C(CpCACHE), C(CpCACHEinvi), CpCACHEwait
@
% I for instruction

<<instruction DSB(arm)>>=
#define DSB \
    MOVW    $0, R0; \
    MCR CpSC, 0, R0, C(CpCACHE), C(CpCACHEwb), CpCACHEwait
@
% D for data

\subsection{Cache operations (ARM)}

%claude:
The ARM cache operations are accessed through MCR/MRC instructions
to coprocessor 7 ([[CpCACHE]]). The terminology is confusing:
ARM's ``flush'' means invalidate (discard cached data without
writing back), and ``clean'' means writeback (push dirty data to
memory). The operations come in three granularities: entire cache
([[CpCACHEall]]), single cache line by virtual address
([[CpCACHEse]]), and by set/way index ([[CpCACHEsi]]).
The kernel provides C-callable wrappers: [[cachedwb]] (writeback),
[[cachedwbinv]] (writeback + invalidate), [[cachedwbse]]
(writeback a range), [[cacheiinv]] (invalidate I-cache), and
[[cacheuwbinv]] (unified: writeback D-cache + invalidate I-cache).

