\section{The Raspberry Pi 2 machine}

%https://www.raspberrypi.org/documentation/hardware/raspberrypi/bcm2836/README.md

% Raspberry Pi 2 has 4 processors. Cortex-a7 (used in many smartphones).

%claude:
The Raspberry Pi~2 uses a BCM2836 SoC with four Cortex-A7 cores,
1~GB of RAM, and peripheral I/O remapped to 0x3F000000 (versus
0x20000000 on the Pi~1). Most of the kernel is portable between
Pi~1 and Pi~2, but SMP support, the different cache line size
(64 bytes vs 32), the generic ARM timer, per-CPU local registers,
and the LDREX/STREX atomic instructions are Pi~2-specific.
The [[Soc]] structure captures these hardware differences so the
same kernel source can target both machines.

<<global [[soc]](raspberry pi2)(arm)>>=
Soc soc = {
    .dramsize   = 1024*MiB,
    .physio     = 0x3F000000,
     <<[[soc(raspberry pi2)]] other fields(arm)>>
};
@
