\subsubsection{[[main()]] other processors ([[cpustart()]])}

% No need to do confinit, xinit, etc.
% Just need setup information for your own processor

%claude:
The C entry point for secondary CPUs is much simpler than [[main]]:
there is no need to initialize memory pools, the device table, or
the first user process---all of that was done by CPU~0. Each
secondary CPU just needs to finalize its own MMU, set up its
trap vectors and local timer, then call [schedinit] to enter the
scheduler loop and start running processes. The [[unlock]] of
[[startlock]] signals to CPU~0 that this CPU is ready.

% Assumes cpu has been set, its mmul1 set (see launchinit?)

<<function [[cpustart]](raspberry pi2)(arm)>>=
void
cpustart(int xcpu)
{
    Mboxes *mb;

    up = nil;
    arch__cpuinit();
    mmuinit1((void*)cpu->mmul1);

    mb = (Mboxes*)(ARMLOCAL + Mboxregs);
    mb->clr[xcpu].doorbell = 1;

    arch__trapinit();
    clockinit();
    timersinit();

    arch_cpuidprint();
    archreset();

    machon(cpu->cpuno);

    unlock(&startlock[xcpu]);

    // schedule a ready process (not necessarily the first one now)
    schedinit();

    panic("schedinit returned");
}
@
%//pad: cpus[] set? and cpu->cpuno??


<<[[arch__cpuinit()]] it not cpu0>>=
if (cpu->cpuno != 0) {
    /* synchronise with cpu 0 */
    cpu->ticks = cpu0->ticks;
}
@
%dead:    cpu->fastclock = cpu0->fastclock;


