\section{Advanced virtual memory}

% large memory system: vpt/vpd, tmpmap, arch_kmap
% other: vmap? for devices? framebuffer related?
% 9atom also provides patches for PAE support and amd64 support

%claude:
This section covers virtual memory features beyond the basic
page fault handler presented in Chapter~\ref{chap:vm}: page
coloring (a cache optimization), physical memory segments (for
memory-mapped I/O), and the [[flushme]] mechanism for maintaining
instruction cache coherency when text pages are modified.

\subsection{Page coloring}
\t seems unused in bcm/ too, so remove again?

%claude:
{Page coloring} is a technique to reduce cache conflicts in
virtually-indexed caches. By assigning pages to ``colors'' based on
their physical address, the kernel ensures that pages mapped at
different virtual addresses do not compete for the same cache lines.
On the ARM, the data cache is set-associative rather than
direct-mapped, so coloring is less important---[[NCOLOR]] is set
to~1, effectively disabling it. The machinery remains in the code
because other architectures (like MIPS) benefit from it.

