%claude:
On a uniprocessor, if a real-time process spins on a lock held by
a lower-priority process, the lower-priority process will never get
to run and release the lock---classic priority inversion. The fix is
to set the EDF deadline to ``now'', which causes the real-time
process to be descheduled at the next scheduling point, giving the
lock holder a chance to run. On a multiprocessor, this is not
needed because the lock holder may be running on another CPU.

<<[[lock()]] optional priority-inversion for real-time process>>=
if(conf.ncpu < 2 && up && up->edf && (up->edf->flags & Admitted)){
    /*
     * Priority inversion, yield on a uniprocessor; on a
     * multiprocessor, the other processor will unlock
     */
    print("inversion %#p pc %#lux proc %lud held by pc %#lux proc %lud\n",
        l, pc, up ? up->pid : 0, l->pc, l->p ? l->p->pid : 0);
    up->edf->d = todget(nil);   /* yield to process with lock */
}
@




<<enum [[edfflags]]>>=
enum EdfFlags 
{
    /* Edf.flags field */
    Admitted    = 0x01,
    Sporadic    = 0x02,
    Yieldonblock    = 0x04,
    Sendnotes   = 0x08,
    Deadline    = 0x10,
    Yield     = 0x20,
    Extratime   = 0x40,
};
@ 


%claude:
The [[Edf]] structure stores both the task parameters (period~T,
deadline~D, cost~C) and the per-instance state (current release
time~r, current deadline~d, remaining slice~S). It also embeds
a [[Timer]] (via anonymous inclusion) so the scheduler can set
deadline and release timers directly. The [[testDelta]]/[[testtime]]
fields are used only during the admission test, which simulates
the schedule to verify that adding a new real-time task will not
cause any existing task to miss its deadline.

<<struct [[Edf]]>>=
struct Edf {
    /* All times in µs */
    /* time intervals */
    long    D;    /* Deadline */
    long    Delta;    /* Inherited deadline */
    long    T;    /* period */
    long    C;    /* Cost */
    long    S;    /* Slice: time remaining in this period */
    /* times (only low-order bits of absolute time) */
    long    r;    /* (this) release time */
    long    d;    /* (this) deadline */
    long    t;    /* Start of next period, t += T at release */
    long    s;    /* Time at which this proc was last scheduled */
  
    /* for schedulability testing */
    long    testDelta;
    int   testtype; /* Release or Deadline */
    long    testtime;
    Proc    *testnext;
  
    /* other */
    // set<enum<edfflags>>
    ushort    flags;
  
    Timer;
  
    /* Stats */
    long    edfused;
    long    extraused;
    long    aged;
    ulong   periods;
    ulong   missed;
};
@ 

\subsection*{[[processes/edf.c]]}

%claude:
The EDF implementation centers on three interrupt-driven callbacks:
[deadlineintr] fires when a process has consumed its time slice
and forces a reschedule, [releaseintr] fires at the start of a
new period to make the process eligible again, and [release]
resets the per-period bookkeeping (remaining slice~S, new
deadline~d). The [edfadmit] function performs an offline
schedulability test before admitting a new real-time task:
it simulates the combined schedule of all admitted tasks to
verify that no deadlines will be missed. Sporadic tasks (those
with the [[Sporadic]] flag) are released at most once per period,
while periodic tasks are released at fixed intervals regardless
of when they last ran.

