%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Conclusion}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:conclusion}

% already lots of pages ... so network, graphics, security, etc in another volume
% actually even fs in other volume, and advanced subjects like:
%  SMP, storage (scsi, ata, floppy, ...) real time scheculing EDF,

%claude:
You now know how the \plan kernel works, to the smallest
details: from the first instruction at [[_start]] to the
scheduler loop, from page faults to pipes, from system
calls to the 9P protocol.

%claude:
Despite being a complete operating system kernel---with
virtual memory, preemptive scheduling, multiprocessor
support, a file-oriented device framework, and a
network-transparent namespace---the entire kernel fits in
roughly 30\,000 lines of C and a few hundred lines of
assembly. This is remarkably small. The key to this
compactness is the ``everything is a file server''
philosophy: instead of adding features to the kernel,
\plan pushes them to user-space file servers communicating
over 9P. The kernel provides just enough mechanism
(processes, memory, files, namespaces) and leaves policy
to user space.

%claude:
Along the way, you have seen many recurring patterns:
reference counting for shared resources ([[Ref]]),
sleep/wakeup for blocking ([[Rendez]]),
two-level tables for sparse mappings
([[Segment]]/[[Pagetable]], L1/L2 page tables),
dispatch tables for polymorphism ([[systab]], [[devtab]]),
and the [[waserror]]/[[poperror]] mechanism for
exception handling in C.
%
You have also seen how a well-chosen set of abstractions
---[[Chan]], [[Dev]], [[Segment]], [[Proc]], [[Page]]---can
compose to build a complete system where each piece
is understandable in isolation.

\section{Connections to other books}

%claude:
The kernel is the foundation on which every other
program in \principia runs. The books are deeply
interconnected:

%claude:
\begin{itemize}

\item The \book{Shell} explains [[rc]], the first
program most users interact with. Every command
you type in [[rc]] exercises [[rfork()]], [[exec()]],
[[wait()]], pipes, and file descriptors---all of which
you now understand from the kernel side.

\item The \book{Compiler} and \book{Assembler}
describe the tools that produce the kernel binary
itself, including the [[5c]]/[[5a]] compilers whose
calling conventions and [[extern register]] extension
you have seen throughout the ARM-specific code.

\item The \book{Linker} explains how [[5l]] produces
the a.out binary that [[sysexec()]] loads, and how
the static base register [[R12]] is set up.

\item The \book{Builder} explains [[mk]], which
orchestrates the kernel build and whose [[mkfile]]
rules drive the compilation of all the source files
discussed in this book.

\item The \book{Graphics} covers [[devdraw]] and the
framebuffer infrastructure that this book only
touched briefly (the screen output and [[screenputs]]
hook).

\item The \book{Libcore} explains the C library that
sits between user programs and the kernel: the
[[pwrite()]]/[[brk()]]/[[rfork()]] wrappers, the
[[Pool]] allocator shared with the kernel's [[malloc]],
and the [[print()]] formatting engine.

\end{itemize}

\section{What this book does not cover}

%claude:
This book focused on the core kernel mechanisms. Several
important subsystems were left for other books or
future work:

%claude:
\begin{itemize}

\item {\em Networking:} The IP stack ([[devip]]),
the Ethernet driver ([[devether]]), and the network
file servers are substantial enough for their own
treatment.

\item {\em Graphics:} The draw device ([[devdraw]]),
the window system [[rio]], and the graphics libraries
deserve a dedicated \book{Graphics}.

\item {\em On-disk file systems:} The file servers
[[fossil]], [[cwfs]], and [[hjfs]] implement the actual
storage layer that the kernel's [[devmnt]] connects to
over 9P.

\item {\em Authentication:} The [[factotum]]
authentication agent and the security architecture
(capabilities, [[srvauth]], tickets) are covered only
superficially here.

\end{itemize}

%claude:
Despite these omissions, the kernel described in this
book is complete and self-contained: it can boot on a
Raspberry Pi, run user programs, manage memory, handle
interrupts, and serve files. Everything else is built
on top of the mechanisms you now understand.

\section{Beyond the \plan kernel}

%claude:
The \plan kernel is intentionally minimal. Modern
production kernels like Linux, macOS/XNU, and Windows
NT are far larger and more featureful. Some of that
complexity is essential, some is accidental---but all
of it is worth understanding in contrast to \plan's
deliberate simplicity:
\begin{itemize}

\item \emph{Scheduling}: \plan uses a simple
multi-level priority scheduler.
Linux's EEVDF (formerly CFS) scheduler uses a
virtual-runtime red-black tree with cgroups for
hierarchical resource control, providing fair
CPU sharing across thousands of tasks with
fine-grained isolation between workloads.
macOS uses a Mach-derived scheduler with
separate ``clutch'' groups for efficiency and
performance cores on Apple Silicon.

\item \emph{Virtual memory}: \plan has straightforward
demand-paged virtual memory with a simple [[Page]]
free list. Linux adds huge pages (2\,MB/1\,GB),
NUMA-aware allocation, memory cgroups with
per-group limits, Kernel Same-page Merging (KSM)
for deduplicating identical pages across processes,
and memory compaction to reduce fragmentation.
These are sophisticated mechanisms that make a
real difference at datacenter scale.

\item \emph{Security}: \plan's security model---per-process
namespaces and the [[factotum]] authentication
agent---is conceptually elegant and was ahead of
its time. Linux has since added mandatory access
controls (SELinux, AppArmor), fine-grained POSIX
capabilities, seccomp-BPF syscall filtering, and
ASLR. macOS adds code signing and sandboxing.
Notably, Linux's namespace mechanism---the
foundation of containers---was directly inspired
by \plan's [[rfork(RFNOMNT)]].

\item \emph{Containers and virtualization}:
\plan's [[rfork]] flags were doing namespace
isolation before ``containers'' existed as a
concept. Modern container runtimes (Docker,
Kubernetes) build on Linux namespaces combined
with cgroups, overlay file systems, and seccomp
policies. On the virtualization side, Linux's KVM
turns the kernel itself into a hypervisor,
enabling efficient virtual machines without
a separate hypervisor layer.

\item \emph{File systems}: \plan's approach of
delegating file systems to user-space 9P servers
is architecturally clean---crashes in a file
server cannot panic the kernel, and new file
systems need no kernel modifications. The
trade-off is the lack of an in-kernel caching
layer comparable to Linux's page cache, dentry
cache, and inode cache. Linux also supports journaling (ext4, XFS) and
copy-on-write snapshots (ZFS, btrfs) directly in
the kernel for performance. Linux's FUSE, which
allows user-space file systems, follows a similar
idea to the 9P model.

\item \emph{Networking}: the \plan IP stack is
a clean, readable implementation. Linux adds
zero-copy networking, TCP offload, eBPF for
programmable in-kernel packet processing, and
XDP for line-rate packet filtering---driven by
datacenter demands where every microsecond
matters and where \plan's simplicity would
genuinely be insufficient.

\item \emph{Device model}: \plan's static [[Dev]]
table is simple---adding a device means adding one
entry. Linux's dynamic model with sysfs, udev,
device tree, and power management (suspend/resume,
runtime PM) handles hotplug, hardware discovery,
and the vast diversity of modern peripherals.

\end{itemize}

%claude:
The pattern is consistent: features that \plan
pioneered (per-process namespaces, user-space file
servers, a unified file-based interface) have been
partially adopted by mainstream systems, often with
considerably more complexity. The \plan kernel shows
that a complete, working kernel can be built from a
small set of well-chosen abstractions. Understanding
it gives you the conceptual foundation on which the
additional engineering of production kernels is built.

